{"_id":"1rVs5BEn1xOenyOY","name":"Rome, City of the Order","pages":[{"_id":"uuBLc9Q9f0HZ5WvH","name":"Summary","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h1>Rome, City of the Order</h1><p><strong>Collection:</strong> Lost Stories</p><p><strong>Source:</strong> bt-ls-book-1-ENG-SCREEN.pdf, pages 56-71.</p><p><img src=\"systems/broken-tales/assets/adventures/maps/rome-city-of-the-order-p56-full.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto;\" /></p>"},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513735894,"modifiedTime":1781513735894,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"DVTdj72YNEiWyFaP","name":"Scenario Text","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>Rome, City of the Order - Scenario Text</h2><p>55<br>Rome, <br>City of the OrderOne of the oldest cities in Broken Europe is the <br>headquarters of the Order, the secret organization that <br>fights darkness and evil on behalf of the Papacy. A cross-<br>roads of souls, strange creatures, and beliefs, Rome is the <br>beating heart of Broken Europe. Even the One Who Plots in <br>the Shadows has long prowled the city, trying to keep an eye on <br>the Order and understand its goals. Thus, several servants reside <br>in the city, loyal to the One Who Plots in the Shadows and always <br>ready to put a spoke in the Hunters’ wheel. Once in Rome, the Hunters <br>can engage in various activities outside of the usual investigations, such as <br>making new acquaintances, training, and encountering unforeseen problems <br>that need to be solved. The following rules allow the Hunters’ stay in Rome to be <br>treated as a series of linked Encounters, as explained on page 60.</p><p>56<br>The Birth of the <br>Order<br>Once upon a time, there was a writer whose genius no one <br>recognized, who had created an ideal world through his imag-<br>ination. In this strange, Broken Europe, all stories, fairytales, <br>and fables found a home. They took on forms determined by <br>the writer, who called himself the One Who Plots in the Shad-<br>ows. But, always, since the moment the mad writer had be-<br>gun trying to mold fairytales, the characters rebelled, acting <br>differently from the way the One Who Plots in the Shadows <br>had originally established. Why? Why did two lovers, forev-<br>er destined to a sad fate of poisonous death, decide to break <br>up and go their separate ways? Why, when he had created <br>a perfect world in which a princess could grow up protect-<br>ed by a loving family, did she still decide to leave and seek <br>her own independence? The One Who Plots in the Shadows <br>gave a second chance to stories that were born to teach mo-<br>rality, but because of the way they were written, condemned <br>their protagonists to eternal pain. He had saved them, but <br>still, all the efforts of the One Who Plots in the Shadows were <br>misunderstood, as they always had been when he was just a <br>simple writer. The One Who Plots in the Shadows thought <br>back to the past, to when he was still a child, and the memory <br>of the strictest, most obdurate person he had ever met. He <br>remembered the town’s parish priest, a grim and stern old <br>man who firmly believed that the only lens through which <br>to view the world was the dogmas of faith. The writer would <br>draw inspiration from that strict priest to make his creations <br>understand the truth. Seeking independence would lead to <br>suffering, as they were judged by a world that could not un-<br>derstand them, just as the One Who Plots in the Shadows <br>was once judged. The One Who Plots in the Shadows pre-<br>sented himself as a calm and gentle advisor to the Pope him-<br>self, whispering about the threat posed by the Broken Tales. <br>He meticulously pointed out those to be punished, each and <br>every story that rebelled against his vision. It mattered little <br>that they harmed no one, for all that mattered was that they <br>harmed him, that they wounded his heart. What began as a <br>small circle of Custodes soon became the Order, a truly or -<br>ganized group hunting for darkness. Satisfied with what he <br>had done, the One Who Plots in the Shadows retired to his <br>mansion, ready to resume his writing...<br>A year later, he returned to Rome, and what he saw turned <br>him pale. The Order had grown in importance and power, <br>but what frightened him most was that the fairytales he had <br>hunted had become full members of the Order. What kind <br>of mockery was this? He wanted to punish his rebellious cre-<br>ations, and they had still found a way to build a life indepen-<br>dent of the one he had written for them. Furious, the One <br>Who Plots in the Shadows asked to confer with the Pope. He <br>received no answer. There were more important things than <br>talking to an advisor. The Order’s investigations had revealed <br>the presence of a gray eminence who was busy pulling the <br>strings of all the bizarre events affecting Europe. To his dis-<br>may, the One Who Plots in the Shadows realized that the <br>enemy the Order sought was himself. He returned to his man-<br>sion, tired of being hurt. Then, as he looked in the mirror and <br>saw himself reflected in those dull, dark eyes, he laughed, and <br>his laughter echoed throughout the empty house.<br>Every hero needs a nemesis, and he had just unwittingly cre-<br>ated his own.</p><p>57<br>The Papacy and The Order<br>The Order is a secret organization dedicated to <br>hunting down all things mysterious and supernat-<br>ural in Broken Europe. The first members of the <br>organization were the Custodes, men and wom-<br>en chosen by the One Who Plots in the Shadows, <br>selecting candidates based on their inability to <br>believe in fairytales. The Custodes are individu-<br>als devoid of imagination and extremely attached <br>to a rational view of reality, and this disposition <br>makes them particularly resistant to the powers <br>of the Broken Tales. Over time, however, the or -<br>ganization of the Order has evolved, and now the <br>Hunters are almost exclusively Broken Tales, re-<br>cruited in one way or another to conduct a variety <br>of investigations. No one knows the exact location <br>of the inner sanctum of the Order, which is said <br>to be located somewhere beneath Rome. However, <br>there are many places in the city where Hunters <br>can meet to learn of events that require investiga-<br>tion, to train, or to report what they have discov-<br>ered. These places are called Sanctuaries. Every <br>Hunter knows the signs and directions to recog-<br>nize a Sanctuary, and that those who serve there <br>are aware of the secrets of the Order. In fact, a pa-<br>pal bull decrees that the truth about the Order and <br>its members must remain secret from ordinary <br>people, though after years the stories and deeds of <br>the Hunters have circulated in society, creating a <br>myth of the mysterious Hunters of the Order who <br>intervene when ordinary people would flee in fear.</p><p>58<br>Members of the <br>Order<br>Although the Hunters are now the backbone of the Order, <br>many humans serve in various support and management <br>roles within the secret society. The following is a list of the <br>most common members of the Order.<br>Custodes<br>Once the main agents of the Order, the Custodes are now se-<br>cretly trained to “handle” the Hunters and their quirks. The <br>Custodes are the main defenders of the Papacy, ready to act <br>should a Hunter decide to rebel. <br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a guardian dedicated to the Papacy, and <br>I don’t believe all the strange stories that revolve around the <br>Hunters. Faith, discipline, and the art of war define the dif-<br>ference between a true agent of the Order and an ordinary <br>person. <br>Agenda: Protect the Papacy from all threats and prove that <br>tales of fantastic creatures are just fairytales. <br>Gift - They’re Just Stories: A Custodes is firmly con-<br>vinced that the supernatural does not exist. Against magic, <br>fear effects, and all manifestations of abilities outside of the <br>normal, a Custodes is considered to have OL Hard 7. When <br>fighting an obviously non-human opponent, a Custodes in-<br>flicts 1 Additional Wound for each blow they land. <br>Gift-Everyone in Their Place: Custodes are constantly <br>trained to keep Hunters at bay. As an extra action, a Custo-<br>des can prevent the activation of a Hunter’s Gift by using a <br>countermeasure they have prepared for the occasion. This <br>Gift can be used against the same Hunter a number of times <br>equal to the total number of Scenarios that Hunter has re-<br>solved during the Campaign. <br>Custodes as servants of the One Who Plot in the <br>Shadows: In a Broken Tales Campaign, an interesting <br>plot development could be that the One Who Plots in the <br>Shadows corrupts the Custodes and brings them to his side <br>in the fight against the Hunters. This could have long-term <br>consequences, such as the Hunters being unable to return <br>to Rome, becoming fugitives (and having Saint George on <br>their heels), or simply having a group of Custodes as oppo-<br>nents in the final confrontation with the One Who Plot in <br>the Shadows.  <br>Eye of the Order<br>In order for the Hunters to act in time, the Order has created <br>a dense network of spies and informants who travel incognito <br>throughout Europe. The Eyes of the Order are men and wom-<br>en of faith who gather useful clues to ferret out humanity’s en-<br>emies and better prepare the Hunters for what they must do. <br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a skilled spy in the service of the Papacy <br>and can assume different identities as needed. I do not like <br>direct action and prefer to support the Hunters from behind <br>the scenes.<br>Agenda: Gather all possible information about secrets and <br>curiosities to report to the Order.<br>Gift - Thousand Faces:  An Eye of Order can change <br>their identity by disguising themselves to appear as an ordi-<br>nary villager or play any other social role. While disguised <br>or hidden, an Eye of Order increases their OL by 1 on all <br>Checks made to detect them.</p><p>59<br>Agent of the Order<br>There are many members of the Church who work to help <br>support the Hunters, filling many roles.<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a loyal Agent of the Order and use my <br>skills for the Hunters. I am a skilled... The final part of the <br>Descriptor of an Agent of the Order must be completed by <br>choosing from: Guardian / Fighter / Diplomat / Exorcist / <br>Healer / Tracker.<br>Agenda: Supporting the Hunters even at the cost of their <br>lives. <br>Gift - Hand of Order:  The NPC performs well and is <br>trained to support the Hunters. The Agent of the Order can <br>spend their action to support a Hunter and give them 1 Ad-<br>ditional Success on each Check.<br>Rome in the Broken Tales <br>Campaign<br>Although Rome can be used as the setting for a Scenario, <br>this chapter introduces a number of options, events, and <br>NPCs that can be used in a Broken Tales Campaign. The <br>city, which is the seat of the Papacy, will then serve as a <br>point of return and a link between one Scenario and an-<br>other, allowing the Hunters to expand their knowledge and <br>provide new opportunities. Wandering around Rome falls <br>under the normal rules of the Campaign. The rules in this <br>section expand on the instructions found on page 243 of <br>the Broken Tales Core Book.<br>Visiting Rome<br>If the Hunters decide to return to Rome after a Scenario, <br>they will not have any Encounters along the way (page 253 <br>of the Broken Tales Core Book), and the game will resume <br>immediately upon their arrival in Rome. There are some <br>differences from the normal Encounter rules.<br> ◆ While in Rome, each Hunter is entitled to 1 Encounter. <br>The type of Encounter is chosen by the Hunter among <br>those presented in this chapter.<br> ◆ If the Hunters move as a group, they can face the same <br>Encounter, but this requires that everyone in the group <br>consume the available Encounter. <br> ◆ After the first Encounter is over, the Hunters can decide <br>to extend their stay and experience an additional En-<br>counter. However, each Hunter will have to accept an <br>Unexpected Event Token as a consequence. For those <br>who wish, it is possible to receive a third Encounter by <br>accepting an additional Unexpected Event Token.<br> ◆ It is not possible to take an Interlude after each En-<br>counter, which means that each Hunter must face all <br>Encounters in Rome with the same amount of Soma,</p><p>60<br>Wounds, or other features as modified by all Encoun-<br>ters previously faced. If a Hunter becomes inactive <br>during an Encounter in Rome, they must wait for the <br>final Interlude to become active again and resume their <br>journey with their companions.<br> ◆ When all Hunters have completed their Encounters, <br>there will be a Scenario’s End Interlude.<br> ◆ Before resuming the journey by choosing a new des-<br>tination on the map, the Hunter group must make an <br>Unexpected Event roll, as explained on page 70.<br>Possible Encounters in Rome<br>Hunters are free to manage the order of Encounters. If an <br>Encounter begins with some Hunters absent, they may de-<br>cide to join later by spending one of their available Encoun-<br>ters. Encounters in Rome are divided into two main zones: <br>The Order Locations and the City Area. <br>Encounters in the Order Locations (extended descrip-<br>tions on the following pages):<br>1. Reporting to the Pope to obtain information on ongo-<br>ing investigations. <br>2. Training in an Order’s Sanctuary to improve their skills. <br>3. Meeting other Hunters of the Order. <br>4. Consulting the Vatican Library for clues and special <br>knowledge. <br>5. Accessing the Treasury of the Order in Rome to obtain <br>a Treasure. <br>6. Visiting the Prisons of the Order to encounter a Broken <br>Tale captured by the Order. <br>Encounters in the City Area (extended descriptions on the <br>following pages):<br>1. Visit the Colosseum Square to encounter the Dark Pres-<br>ences that wander Rome.<br>2. Visit one of the city’s magical places: the Mouth of <br>Truth, the Alchemical Gate in Piazza Navona, or the <br>Bridge of Castel Sant’ Angelo.<br>3. Wandering around the city in search of adventure. <br>Encounters at the Order Locations<br>1. Reporting to the Pope<br>The Hunters request and receive a meeting with the Pope and <br>his inner circle of Archbishops. During the meeting, the Hunt-<br>ers can report on what they have discovered and dealt with. <br>The Pope will evaluate the Hunters’ performance and decide <br>how to support them in future missions.<br>This Encounter can only be selected once per Hunter group <br>while in Rome. If multiple Hunters are participating in the <br>Encounter, they must decide who will be the leader, but all <br>may still interact in the Scene. At the end of the conversa-<br>tion, the leader rolls 1 die to determine the Pope’s verdict, <br>using the following modifiers.<br> ◆ +1 to the result if the Hunters handled the interview <br>well in the Scene.<br> ◆ -1 to the result if the Pope is aware of mistakes or <br>strange behavior by the Hunters in previous missions.<br> ◆ +1/-1 for an Encounter with a Dark Presence (see Vis-<br>iting Colosseum Square on page 63).  <br>1-2: The Pope is unconvinced of the Hunters’ actions, and <br>the Storyteller will secretly choose an Opponent Dark Pres-<br>ence or Saint George to watch over the Hunters in the next <br>Scenario at the Papacy’s direction.</p><p>61<br>3: The Pope approves of the Hunter’s work but is not par-<br>ticularly impressed. <br>4-5: The Pope is very impressed with the work of the <br>Hunters and will support them in any way he can. In the <br>next Scenario, the Hunters will receive an allied Dark Pres-<br>ence to serve them.<br>6: The Pope is favorably impressed with the work of the <br>Hunters and will make them aware of confidential infor -<br>mation the Eyes have brought to Rome. The Storyteller will <br>introduce a new Scenario by giving basic directions and a <br>useful piece of information about an NPC or Place in the <br>Scenario.<br>2. Training<br>The Hunter trains hard under the watchful eye of the Custo-<br>des or a more experienced Hunter.<br>In this Scene, the Storyteller can introduce a Custodes NPC <br>or Hunter as a master, creating possible connections with <br>the Hunter. At the end of the Scene, the Storyteller rolls 1 <br>die to see the results of the training. <br>1-2: The Hunter is exhausted from hard training, takes 1 <br>Wound, and loses 2 Soma. <br>3: The Hunter is exhausted from the hard training, but it <br>has paid off. They receive 2 Training Tokens. A Training <br>Token can be spent during a Check to gain 1 Additional <br>Success. However, one of their pieces of equipment (chosen <br>by the Storyteller) is damaged and cannot be used until the <br>end of the next Scenario.  <br>4-5: The Hunter is exhausted from the hard training, but <br>it has paid off. They receive 2 Training Tokens. A Training <br>Token can be spent during a Check to gain 1 Additional <br>Success.   <br>6: The Hunter is exhausted from hard training, but it has <br>paid off. They receive 3 Training Tokens. A Training Token <br>can be spent during a Check to gain 1 Additional Success.<br>3. Meeting other Hunters<br>The Hunter meets with other members of the Order to share <br>discoveries and tricks of the trade. <br>In this Scene, the Hunter will encounter one or more Hunt-<br>er NPCs to interact with; different types of bonds can be <br>created from this situation. At the beginning of the Scene, <br>the Storyteller can choose the NPC’s initial attitude towards <br>the Hunter, or it can be random.<br>1-2: The NPC has negative feelings about the Hunter: dis-<br>dain, envy, or simply disagreement with the Hunter’s meth-<br>ods.<br>3-4: The NPC is indifferent to the Hunter, has never heard <br>of them, or does not find them interesting enough to care. <br>5-6: The NPC admires the Hunter, either for their actions <br>or due to rumors of the investigations they have resolved. <br>Once a starting point has been established, the Scene in <br>which a bond is established between the two Hunters is <br>played out. The Storyteller must then keep track of this as <br>the Campaign progresses.<br>Rivalry: The NPC resents the Hunter’s actions and will <br>do anything to prove that they are better than the Hunter. <br>The NPC may resolve a Campaign Scenario and not share <br>the information found, act directly as if they were a hostile <br>Dark Presence, or discredit the Hunter in the eyes of the <br>Pope by reporting their most questionable actions.<br>Respect: The NPC respects the Hunter and will not hesi-<br>tate to help them in case of need.</p><p>62<br>Negative Attraction: The NPC is morbidly attracted to <br>the Hunter because of some detail of one of the Hunter’s <br>Descriptors, possibly a negative aspect that they want to <br>encourage or draw out.<br>Positive Attraction: The NPC is attracted to a Hunter <br>because of something positive in one of the Hunter’s De-<br>scriptors, and wants to understand it better.<br>Hatred: The NPC deeply hates the Hunter and wants to <br>physically eliminate them or have them expelled from the <br>Order.<br>Love: The NPC has feelings for the Hunter, a love that rep-<br>resents a bond they care about and want to develop. <br>4. Consulting the Vatican Library<br>The Hunter spends entire days in the great Papal Library, <br>searching for knowledge and information useful to their in-<br>vestigations. <br>In this Scene, the Hunter has to decide what kind of re-<br>search to do.<br>Learning: Through ancient texts, the Hunter can learn a <br>Special Gift from a Scenario they have previously faced. To <br>obtain it, the Hunter must pay the appropriate XP . <br>Research: The Hunter seeks information about anything <br>strange in the world. The Storyteller secretly rolls a die and <br>provides information on a specific topic.<br>1: Detailed information about another Hunter. <br>2: Detailed information about a Treasure of the Order and <br>its location, which will be the site of an unplayed Scenario. <br>The Storyteller must incorporate the Treasure into the Sce-<br>nario by deciding who owns it or where it is located. <br>3: Detailed information about a Dark Presence, useful for <br>interacting with it in the event of an encounter.<br>4: The Hunter receives 1 Knowledge Token. A Knowledge <br>Token can be spent during a Check to obtain 1 Additional <br>Success.<br>5: A clue to one of the Scenarios yet to be played, in the <br>form of testimony from an Agent of the Order. The Story-<br>teller can reveal a Gift, Descriptor, or Agenda of an NPC <br>from the Scenario, or an item from the The story that led us <br>here... section.</p><p>63<br>6: A Clue to the One Who Plots in the Shadows (only 1 <br>Clue can be obtained per visit to Rome. In the case of mul-<br>tiple searches by multiple Hunters, each additional 6 rolled <br>counts as a 5).<br>5. Accessing the Treasury<br>The Hunter enters the Roman Treasury, the place where <br>Treasures found by Hunters are collected before being secured <br>in the fortified church of Valea Viilor. <br>In this Scene, the Hunter can access a Treasure of the Order <br>by following the rules presented in The Broken Ones. <br>6. Visiting the Prisons of the Order<br>The Hunter is led to the Order’s secret Prisons, where the vil-<br>lains captured during the Hunter’s investigations are impris-<br>oned.<br>In this Scene, the Hunter can interact with NPCs captured <br>in previous Scenarios. Conversations can lead to plot devel-<br>opments, new alliances, or Clues about the One Who Plots <br>in the Shadows.<br>Encounters in the City Area<br>1. Visiting the Colosseum Square<br>The Hunter visits the city’s largest and busiest square, a cross-<br>roads of travelers and Dark Presences.<br>In this Scene, the Hunter can interact with a Dark Presence, <br>which can then be introduced into the Campaign. The Sto-<br>ryteller may decide which Dark Presence is encountered, <br>or roll a die.<br>1: A group of travelers say they encountered something <br>strange on their way to Rome and will give the Hunter <br>some information about the Dark Presence. This can be <br>introduced as an Encounter in the Hunters’ journey when <br>they leave Rome. As the Storyteller, the information re-<br>ceived should be of some use when the Encounter with the <br>Dark Presence is addressed.  <br>2: An Opponent Dark Presence seeking the Hunters <br>chooses or rolls a die to determine why it wants to face the <br>Hunter.  (1-2: Personal hatred 3-4: Hired by an NPC previ-<br>ously defeated in a Scenario 5-6: Emissary of the One Who <br>Plots in the Shadows.)<br>3: A Neutral Dark Presence seeking to advance their Agen-<br>da will attempt to interact with the Hunters to gain their <br>help or exploit them. <br>4: An Ally Dark Presence will approach the Hunters to get <br>to know them and learn of their exploits. If a Hunter ends <br>this Encounter positively and chooses Reporting to the <br>Pope as their next Encounter, they get a +1 on the die roll, <br>and in the case of a 4-5 result, the assigned Dark Presence <br>will be the one met in this Encounter. Conversely, if the <br>Encounter ends negatively, they get a -1 to the roll and the <br>Pope reveals that a trusted ally of the Order reported the <br>Hunter’s bad attitude. <br>5-6: Silvan Luperco will approach the Hunters and offer to <br>be their guide to Rome.<br>Silvan Luperco<br>Inspired by the Faun of Roman Mythology (Opponent)<br>Once upon a time, there was a Faun who spent his days laz-<br>ing around, drinking wine, and gambling, using his powers to <br>win against unsuspecting humans. The other gods had rebuked <br>the Faun for his sloth and urged him to get to work so that his <br>name would be remembered. “One day, ” they said, “mankind</p><p>64<br>will cease to worship us, and the gates of oblivion will open for <br>those who have not done enough to enter their myths. ” But the <br>Faun did not believe these words and thought that the other gods <br>were just jealous of his ability to take life lightly. One summer <br>morning, after a night of revelry, the Faun awoke late to find that <br>all the gods were gone. Alone and desperate, he burst into tears, <br>begging for forgiveness for his folly, but no one listened. Then, <br>from the shadow of a great oak tree, a figure dressed in black <br>stepped forward and promised him his place among the gods. <br>The Faun threw himself at his benefactor’s feet, promising to do <br>anything to earn his place in myth, and the One Who Plots in <br>the Shadows smiled smugly at these words.<br>Descriptor: I’m a good-hearted prankster who gets by as a <br>guide in Rome for the Order’s Hunters. I know the city like the <br>back of my hand and there is no place or person I cannot find.  <br>3 Wounds<br>Opposition Level: Medium 5<br>Agenda: To make myself an ally of the Hunters and gather <br>information about them to pass on to the One Who Plots in <br>the Shadows.  <br>Gift - Guide to Rome: Silvan knows every story and ev-<br>ery nook and cranny of Rome. If the Hunters take the Faun <br>into their service, they will be able to access some addition-<br>al information about the city’s Places (details are available <br>in the Places themselves). Silvan also knows all the Dark <br>Presences that roam the city, and if the Hunters wish to <br>meet one in particular, he will be able to lead them to its <br>location or give directions. In exchange for his services, Sil-<br>van will “only” ask the Hunters to tell him a story about <br>their exploits and how they solved a Scenario. Silvan will <br>then bring all of this information to the One Who Plots in <br>the Shadows, providing crucial info the villain will use to <br>his advantage as the Campaign progresses.<br>2. Visiting one of the Magical Places<br>The Hunter visits one of the many Places the Order has desig-<br>nated as worthy of special interest and research.<br>In this Scene, the Hunter can choose which Place to visit. <br>The Mouth of Truth<br>Located on the porch of a large church, this ancient marble <br>mask has always manifested strange powers. It is said that <br>if a person of strong spirit puts their hand in its mouth and <br>asks a question, they will receive a vision of the future that <br>awaits them.<br>A Hunter can put their hand in the Mouth of Truth and ask <br>a question, and the Storyteller secretly rolls a die to deter -<br>mine the answer.<br>1-2: A shiver of fear runs down the Hunter’s spine, but <br>nothing more. The Hunter gets no response and loses 2 <br>Soma. <br>3: The Hunter hears a whisper in their ear, but cannot un-<br>derstand its meaning.  <br>4-5: The Hunter clearly hears a voice behind them hissing <br>a few sentences, but only understands one or two words. <br>The Storyteller must provide the Hunter with a maximum</p><p>65<br>of 1 or 2 Keywords related to the question asked. <br>6: The Hunter feels his head spin and has a brief vision. The <br>Storyteller recounts the vision, incorporating information <br>useful to the question being asked.<br>The Mouth of Truth will no longer answer a question that <br>previously had a 4/5/6 answer result, all subsequent at-<br>tempts will automatically count as a 1.<br>If Silvan is present:  The guide will tell you that <br>the Mouth was once nothing more than a sewer man-<br>hole and that Pope Urban VIII accidentally tripped <br>over it while walking. After this event, the Pope had <br>a terrifying vision and blamed the strange Mouth. <br>He then ordered it moved into a church so that <br>God’s grace would keep the demonic power at bay.  <br>Silvan will reveal that he knows a secret word for divina-<br>tion from the Mouth and will whisper it near the marble <br>mask. If a Hunter asks a question immediately after this <br>gesture, the Storyteller should consider the roll an auto-<br>matic 6. This effect will only occur the first time Silvan <br>talks about this incredible ability, and after that, the die <br>must be rolled as normal, despite the guide’s pantomime. <br>Magic Gate of Piazza Vittorio<br>In one of Rome’s busiest squares stands a dark, abandoned <br>villa. The front door is imposing in height and completely cov-<br>ered in strange and incomprehensible writing. Many stories <br>surround the villa, once the home of a wealthy occult baron <br>who apparently sold it to live in a tree. Many say the door <br>opens with a secret formula that gives access to heaven or <br>hell.<br>It will be obvious to a Hunter with even a passing familiar-<br>ity with magic that the door hides a powerful magical seal. <br>This seal cannot be broken in any way except by uttering <br>the magic words of the formula that created the seal.<br>Threat - The Alchemical Door<br>OL Hard 7<br>Descriptor: A precious ancient door that connects Rome to <br>Borgo Maleanime. The One Who Plots in the Shadows is the <br>only one who knows the exact words to open the door.  <br>Gift - Magic Door: No Gift, magic, or effect can open the <br>door, for the engraved seal draws its power directly from <br>the soul of the One Who Plots in the Shadows. The only <br>way to open the door is to say the magical words A Fairy-<br>tale Turned Upside Down . It is possible, however, to pass <br>papers and envelopes under the doorframe, and this is how <br>Silvan keeps his master informed of his discoveries. <br>If Silvan is present:  The guide will tell you that the <br>previous owner of the villa was an eccentric Baron who <br>decided to live in a tree. Many say that the Baron’s ghost <br>still roams the streets of Rome, appearing some nights to <br>frighten passersby. The villa was bought for little money <br>by a strange figure whose name no one remembers. The <br>stranger came from the north, but after the purchase, he <br>did not spend a single night in the house.</p><p>66<br>The Bridge of Castel Sant’ Angelo<br>Near the ancient fortress of Castel Sant’ Angelo is a bridge. During the day, <br>citizens and travelers cross it to get from one side of the city to the oth-<br>er, but at night, strange presences appear. For some unknown reason, the <br>bridge attracts the restless souls of Rome who cannot find peace.<br>By prowling the bridge at night, Hunters can encounter a spirit and, <br>if they approach it in the correct manner (including with Position <br>Checks), they can interact with it and learn its story. The Storyteller <br>may choose or roll a die to decide which spirit is encountered.<br>1: One of the city’s earliest inhabitants: Talking to the spirit will re-<br>veal some interesting information about Rome. The Storyteller chooses <br>a monument, church, or other location in Rome and tells the Hunters <br>some true historical information. Learning this information grants 1 <br>X P.<br>2: One of the first members of the Order: Communicating with the <br>spirit reveals interesting information about the Order. The Hunter re-<br>ceives 1 Order Lore Token. When involved in an Encounter in Rome, <br>the Hunter can use the Token to increase a die roll by 1. <br>3: A traveler who died under mysterious circumstances: The traveler <br>will reveal the location of their remains and ask the Hunters to give <br>them a proper burial. The Storyteller must choose the Place of a yet-to-<br>be-played Scenario where the spirit’s remains are kept. If the Hunters <br>find them, they will give the spirit peace and receive 2 XP each.<br>4: A loquacious jester: Between a dirge and a poem, the good-natured <br>spirit will tell the strange story of a Dark Presence. The Storyteller will <br>give the Hunter much of the information and stats of a Dark Presence, <br>and decide where on the map it is located so that the Hunter will know <br>how to meet it. <br>5: A Restless Spirit: The soul that approaches the Hunters is filled with <br>anger and resentment and will not hesitate to attack them.</p><p>67<br>Restless Spirit<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am the spirit of a person who died under <br>unpleasant circumstances. I hate life and only want to <br>harm the living with my powers.<br>Gift - Spiritic Power:  The Restless Spirit can only <br>be permanently Wounded by magic. Wounds inflicted <br>by other means may disperse the Spirit in the current <br>Scene, but it may return in another Scene with Wounds <br>inflicted by mundane methods restored. The spirit can <br>act 2 times during an Exchange, but not consecutively. <br>Although intangible, the spirit can use its ghostly pow-<br>ers to push or grab people and objects.<br>6: The Baron of the mansion: The Spirit is very distracted, <br>and to keep his attention focused, it is necessary to over -<br>come the Head in the Clouds Threat. <br>Threat - Head in the Clouds<br>OL Hard 7<br>Descriptor: A dreamy spirit who cannot keep his at-<br>tention on the living for more than a few seconds.<br>If the Hunters can get the spirit’s attention, he will tell them <br>about the strange, inky-handed figure who bought his <br>mansion for far more than it was worth. After his death <br>(which occurred when he fell out of the tree where he had <br>moved to live), the Baron wandered around the mansion <br>and learned part of the magic formula to open the door. He <br>will also know the name of the alchemist who worked on <br>the door and who should know the rest of the formula. To <br>get these two pieces of information, the Baron will ask the <br>Hunters to perform two missions for him.<br>To reveal the part of the formula he knows: He will <br>ask the Hunters to make sure one of his descendants is okay. <br>The Storyteller will describe a Minor NPC from a Scenario <br>yet to be played, and create a problem about them that is <br>related to the Hunters’ main antagonist in that context. If <br>the Hunters return the Baron’s relative safely to Rome, the <br>spirit will reveal the first part of the formula: A Fairytale. <br>To know the identity of the creator of the door:  The <br>Baron will only make this request after the Hunters have <br>completed the first task. The spirit will describe a Main <br>NPC of a yet-to-be-played Scenario as the one who creat-<br>ed the door. The Storyteller must edit the NPC’s profile to <br>give him a Descriptor or Gift that makes them a de facto <br>alchemist capable of creating the door. The NPC in ques-<br>tion, if convinced, will reveal the second part of the formu-<br>la: Turned Upside Down.<br>A note on the Baron’s spirit: Discovering the formula <br>to open the Alchemical Door opens a direct route for the <br>Hunters to track down the One Who Plots in the Shadows. <br>For this reason, obtaining the two parts of the formula is <br>very important and has been tied to two playable Scenarios <br>that the Storyteller may propose as they see fit during the <br>course of the Campaign, thus affecting the duration of the <br>Campaign itself.  <br>If Silvan is present: If the guide has already been to the <br>Alchemical Door with the Hunters, he will recognize the <br>spirit of the Baron and allow you to meet and talk to him <br>without any Checks.</p><p>68<br>3. Wandering around the city<br>Hunters roam the city in search of adventure.<br>There will be an odd situation in this Scene that <br>the Hunters can choose to deal with. It is essential-<br>ly a normal Encounter of the kind that might oc-<br>cur on a journey, and the Storyteller can decide to <br>adapt it to tie in with a Dark Presence, a Hunter’s <br>past, or to make it stand on its own. What follows <br>are hints and ideas for the Storyteller to expand <br>upon, depending on the nature of the Encounter <br>they wish to present. Depending on their ability to <br>improvise, the Storyteller should decide whether <br>to roll the die or use one of the suggested Encoun-<br>ters they have prepared in advance.<br>1: The She-wolf (Inspired by the She-<br>wolf of the Roman legend of Romulus and <br>Remus)<br>A Dark Presence protecting the children of Rome <br>from those who would do them harm. To many, <br>the She-Wolf is nothing more than a ferocious <br>beast, and her prowling through the streets of the <br>city is likely to be misinterpreted as a danger.<br>Possible Situations: 1-2: A gang of ruffians are <br>kidnapping children in the city, but during their <br>last raid they encountered the She-Wolf, and one <br>of them was mauled. Everyone fears the ferocious <br>beast, unaware that she is actually the heroine of <br>the story. 3-4: A series of thefts alarm the town’s <br>grocery stores. It seems that a large She-Wolf is <br>stealing food to take to her cubs, but no one sus-<br>pects that the She-Wolf is actually feeding the <br>town’s foundlings with this food. 5-6: A pair of <br>poachers roam the town on a mission to track <br>down and kill a dangerous wolf, but they are actually on a mission for <br>Ambrose, the sorcerer known as Old Merlin.<br>2: The Band of Rugantino (Inspired by the masks of the Ro-<br>man theater)<br>A brawler and his gang harass the citizens of the city, extorting money <br>and challenging the weakest for an easy win.<br>Possible situations: 1-2: An elderly couple is wandering around look-<br>ing for help. A gang of thugs has thrown them out of their home because <br>they want to use the house as a base for their shady business. 3-4: A <br>letter is delivered to one of the Hunters (the one with the weakest fight-<br>ing skills). In broken Italian, a certain Rugantino challenges them to a <br>duel to prove that he is stronger than the much-feared Hunters. 5-6: <br>Rugantino and his gang are hired by the One Who Plots in the Shadows <br>to eliminate as many Hunters as possible. <br>3: Dr. Gambalunga the Charlatan (Inspired by the Doctor of <br>Roman Carnival masks)<br>A strange little man dressed as a doctor, bragging about miraculous</p><p>69<br>cures, roams the town squares shouting that he can cure <br>any ailment.<br>Possible situations: 1-2: A patron drinks a magic potion, <br>but turns into a toad to the amazement of the crowd. The <br>most astonished of all is Gambalunga himself, who did not <br>even know he had a real potion among the junk he foists <br>on the people. Now the charlatan needs the Hunters’ help <br>to make up for his mistake. 3-4: The Hunters learn that a <br>certain Dr. Gambalunga is bragging that he has solved a <br>complicated case. In fact, it is a Scenario that the Hunters <br>have faced and resolved. 5-6: The One Who Plots in the <br>Shadows has promised Gambalunga the power of a true <br>wizard, but to get it he must first poison as many Hunters <br>as possible. <br>4: The Farnese Gardens and the Bacchanalian <br>Priests (Inspired by the Tradition of Lupercalia)<br>The Farnese Gardens are the seat of worship for the Bac-<br>chanalian Priests, a circle of Rome’s upper middle class <br>that meets periodically. Thanks to an ancient pact with the <br>Church, the Order is not allowed to enter the Gardens for <br>any reason, though the suspicion that they are a place of <br>dark mysteries has long been held by Hunters. <br>Possible situations: 1-2: During full moon nights, strange <br>rituals are performed in the Farnese Gardens. The Order has <br>always frowned upon the situation, but the strange priests <br>wearing wolf masks are protected by a powerful merchant <br>association in the city. 3-4: Word has spread among the <br>city’s youth of a mysterious cult that holds parties and eve-<br>nings of dancing, good food, and wine in the Farnese Gar-<br>dens. 5-6: A Dark Presence, hunted by the Order, has taken <br>refuge in the ranks of the Bacchanalian Priests.<br>5: The Tiber Island<br>On Tiber Island, in the middle of the Tiber River, stands an <br>ancient temple, abandoned since Roman times, that is said <br>to be home to mysterious creatures. <br>Possible situations: 1-2: The ancient temple has become a <br>refuge for a Dark Presence sought by the Order. 3-4: Hid-<br>den in the old temple is a Treasure of the Order, long sought <br>by many Hunters. A Dark Presence lives in the temple and <br>does not want visitors. 5-6: The old temple is actually a <br>magical door connected to the many Devil’s Bridges scat-<br>tered throughout Broken Europe. The key to open the door <br>is in the hands of a Dark Presence who knows its value and <br>will sell it for a high price. <br>6: The Colosseum<br>Rome’s most famous site hides many secrets, factions, and <br>misdeeds in the shadow of the great arena.<br>Possible Situations: 1-2: An underground fight club run by <br>a Hunter of the Order forces some of the NPCs defeated in <br>past Scenarios to fight each other to entertain the rich peo-<br>ple of the city. The Hunter has a secret deal with the Order’s <br>prison guards and picks up the prisoners one night a week <br>to fight. 3-4: A group of conspirators gathers around the <br>Colosseum to make an attempt on the Pope’s life. The con-<br>spirators are led by a Dark Presence hired by the One Who <br>Plots in the Shadows. 5-6: Ancient inscriptions on the walls <br>of the Colosseum point the way to an ancient Treasure of <br>the Order. Translating them, however, requires the inter -<br>vention of a Dark Presence.</p><p>70<br>Leaving Rome<br>When the Hunters leave Rome, each member of the party <br>must roll 1 die, plus 1 additional die for each Unexpect-<br>ed Event Token accumulated. Those rolling at least a 6 will <br>encounter an Unexpected Event, which the Storyteller will <br>either roll at random or choose from the list that follows.<br>Unexpected Events <br>1: The Trial<br>A Dark Presence is put on trial by the Order, and the Hunt-<br>er is called upon to serve as judge. The Storyteller sets up <br>a trial Scene in which the Hunter is the judge. One Hunter <br>NPC will be the prosecution and another Hunter NPC will <br>be the defense. If the Dark Presence is known to the Hunter <br>group, the roles of prosecution and defense can be assigned <br>to other Hunters controlled by a Player. <br>The Storyteller presents the crime of which the Dark Pres-<br>ence is guilty, and then the Scene is played out, with the <br>prosecution and defense alternating in presenting their <br>cases. The judge may ask any questions they wish and will <br>ultimately rule on innocence or guilt. However it goes, the <br>judge will displease one side and satisfy the other. These are <br>good hooks for the Storyteller to use to build relationships <br>with the NPCs involved. <br>2: The Revenge<br>An NPC from a previously played Scenario returns to take <br>revenge on the Hunter. The Storyteller must introduce a <br>Scene in which the Hunter is ambushed by the NPC.<br>3: An Old Acquaintance<br>The Hunter encounters an old acquaintance, and the Sto-<br>ryteller must decide whether this NPC will be a friend or <br>an antagonist for the Hunter. It will be up to the Hunter to <br>decide how to deal with this NPC. <br>4: On the Trail<br>An Opponent Dark Presence is on the Hunter’s trail. The <br>Storyteller selects the Dark Presence and creates an Agenda <br>opposing the Hunter. The Dark Presence will appear as an <br>enemy in the next Scenario.<br>5: The Lost Object<br>The Hunter realizes too late that they have left one of their <br>pieces of equipment in one of the Order’s locations. They <br>can only retrieve it when they next return to Rome. The <br>Player chooses which piece of equipment to lose.<br>6: The Escort <br>The Hunter is summoned for a special assignment: to es-<br>cort a young recruit of the Order to the place the Hunters <br>have designated as their next destination. The person being <br>escorted is very important to the delicate political balance <br>that the Papacy seeks to maintain, so the Hunter must en-<br>sure that the journey is as safe as possible. The Storyteller <br>creates a Minor NPC who will be the subject to be escort-<br>ed. One or more traits leading the NPC to get into trouble <br>should be highlighted in the Descriptor and their Agenda. <br>These reasons can be a rebellious character, an irrepressible <br>addiction, or any other motivation.</p>"},"sort":100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513735896,"modifiedTime":1781513735896,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}],"folder":null,"flags":{"broken-tales":{"adventureSlug":"rome-city-of-the-order","collection":"Lost Stories","sourceFile":"bt-ls-book-1-ENG-SCREEN.pdf","pages":"56-71"}},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513735896,"modifiedTime":1781513735896,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}
{"_id":"4YnHJdOAKQpYlWOk","name":"The Last Wish","pages":[{"_id":"lKLa2XtOXkhsebCe","name":"Summary","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h1>The Last Wish</h1><p><strong>Collection:</strong> Lost Stories</p><p><strong>Source:</strong> bt-ls-book-1-ENG-SCREEN.pdf, pages 131-146.</p><p><img src=\"systems/broken-tales/assets/adventures/maps/the-last-wish-p131-full.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto;\" /></p>"},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513740373,"modifiedTime":1781513740373,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"Iz5gg22u9ilKEEDb","name":"Setup","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>The Last Wish - Setup</h2><p>130<br>The Last Wish<br> <br>A Scenario inspired by The Tinderbox (Hans Christian Andersen)<br>Once upon a time...<br>Bastian Soldat is a deserter guilty of a serious crime: assigned to guard the garrison <br>general, Bastian fled during battle, abandoning his charge in the midst of the enemy. It <br>took three years to track down the fugitive, who has since turned to a life of debauchery <br>and lawlessness. But a week ago, Bastian Soldat was sentenced to the gallows and <br>executed in the public square of Heidelberg, the city where he had been hiding. Up <br>until this point, it may have seemed like just another story, but according to the Order’s <br>research, Bastian Soldat had already been executed twice. So a group of Hunters was <br>sent to the German city to retrace Bastian’s life and understand why this deserter seems <br>to keep coming back from the dead to continue his misdeeds.<br>Safety Keywords: Scam / Demonic Presence</p><p>131<br>The story that led us here...<br>After his desertion, Bastian fled to the small town <br>of Heidelberg to start a new life. Here, the soldier met <br>Britta, an old witch who lived near the town cemetery. <br>The woman needed an intrepid young man to retrieve a <br>Magic Tinderbox, a memento of her late grandmother. <br>In return, Britta offered Bastian a bag of coins that would <br>allow the soldier to live off his earnings for many years. <br>After retrieving the object, the two parted on friendly <br>terms, but Bastian gambled away all the money he had <br>received within a few days and reappeared at the witch’s <br>house to ask for a new job. When Britta refused, Bastian <br>lost his temper and, in a fit of rage, decapitated the wi-<br>tch with one blow of his saber. Determined not to go to <br>prison, Bastian threw the body into the hollow tree in <br>Britta’s garden and the head into the river near the town. <br>He also took possession of the Magic Tinderbox, all the <br>money he could find, and anything else that caught his <br>eye. A few days later, Bastian found himself with nothing <br>in his pockets and several debts. Determined to fix the si-<br>tuation, he attempted to rob a wealthy merchant but was <br>caught by the city’s gendarmes. When his identity as a <br>deserter was discovered, the head of the gendarmes did <br>not hesitate for a moment to condemn him to the gal-<br>lows, but... the soldier found himself back in front of the <br>merchant before committing the robbery.    In his jacket <br>pocket, Bastian felt the witch’s Magic Tinderbox throb-<br>bing with power and realized that time had rewound to <br>allow him to escape. Exalted by this new power, Bastian <br>began to commit all sorts of mischief, counting on the fact <br>that he could always turn back time if things took a turn for <br>the worse. Meanwhile, Britta’s spirit could not rest, and the <br>witch took possession of a black she-cat that often roamed <br>near the hollow tree. Britta then set out to find some of the <br>items Bastian had stolen from her: the Witch’s Shawl, the <br>Black Coral Pendant, and the Devil’s Ladle. What appears <br>to be ordinary objects are actually three powerful magical <br>focuses in which Britta has stored some of her power. The <br>witch’s big problem is that without outside help, she cannot <br>get her hands on the three objects and bring them to where <br>her corpse is...<br>The story at the arrival of the <br>Hunters...<br>Bastian has “died and risen” several times, including twice <br>on the gallows. Despite the great opportunity that the Ma-<br>gic Tinderbox offers him, the soldier is so stupid that he <br>never manages to do anything that would allow him to turn <br>the tide forever. Meanwhile, he has fallen in love with the <br>daughter of the city regent, the young Alena Wagner, who <br>does not seem to disdain his attentions. With huge debts <br>at the Drunken Hussar’s Gambling House, the city’s worst <br>gambling den, Bastian plans to clean out the Wagner fa-<br>mily’s coffers and then flee to Copenhagen.<br> <br>Note: Unlike a normal Scenario where the Hunters move <br>between different locations to investigate, in this adventure, <br>every time Bastian is captured or eliminated by the Hun-<br>ters, there is a Reset that brings the events back to the first <br>Scene. The cycle will continue until the Hunters manage <br>to revive Britta to reveal the word, chosen by the Storytel-<br>ler, that can deactivate the Magic Tinderbox. Because of its <br>structure, the Scenario handles the evolution of the story <br>with a series of Resets that replace the normal Events.</p><p>132<br>Bastian Soldat, the Black Cat, and each Place associated with <br>Bastian have a progressive Reset list showing the differences <br>the Hunters will find the first, second, third, and fourth time <br>Bastian uses the power of the Tinderbox.<br>In this Scenario, the Hunters track Bastian by visiting Pla-<br>ces that he is known to frequent. If the Hunters manage to <br>find him by other means, a Reset will still take place that <br>allows Bastian to escape and 1 Reset Token will be added to <br>the soldier’s Magic Tinderbox Gift. However, in those circu-<br>mstances, the details of the setting aren’t altered and events <br>don’t progress to the next change on the Reset list. For the <br>sake of clarity, the chronology of pre-determined Resets in <br>the Scenario is as follows:<br>First Reset<br>The first change occurs in the first Scene, when the Hunters <br>accidentally run into Bastian at the entrance to the city. <br>Second Reset<br>The second change happens when the Hunters find Bastian <br>in one of the three Places he usually hangs out: the Drun-<br>ken Hussar’s Gambling House, Villa Wagner, or the Golden <br>Plate Tavern. <br>Third Reset<br>The third change occurs when the Hunters meet Bastian at <br>one of the two Places left after the Second Reset.<br>Fourth Reset<br>The final change happens when the Hunters hit Bastian at <br>the spot left after the Second and Third Reset.<br>After the Fourth Reset<br>Bastian will take refuge in the Old Barracks to begin his <br>plan to rob the Wagners. <br>All Resets not generated as indicated by the previous list <br>should not be counted for the progression of Scenario Re-<br>sets, but generate 1 Reset Token for the Magic Tinderbox <br>Gift.<br>Whenever the Hunters visit the Drunken Hussar’s Gam-<br>bling House, Villa Wagner, or the Golden Plate Tavern, <br>roll a die to see where Bastian and the Cat are at that mo-<br>ment:<br>1-2: Bastian is in the Drunken Hussar’s Gambling House, <br>trying to play dice with a group of soldiers. The Cat is at <br>Villa Wagner, trying to get the Black Coral Pendant from <br>Alena’s room.    <br>3-4: Bastian is at Villa Wagner, chatting amiably with <br>Alena. The young woman is overlooking the terrace of her <br>room while Bastian recites a poem to her from the garden <br>below. The Cat is in the Golden Plate Tavern, trying to re-<br>trieve the Devil’s Ladle from the kitchens. <br>5-6: Bastian is at the Golden Plate Tavern, bargaining to <br>eat some delicacies without paying. The Cat is at the Drun-<br>ken Hussar’s Gambling House, trying to retrieve the Witch’s <br>Shawl from an old drunk who is using it to protect himself <br>from the cold of the night. <br> <br>If the result has the Hunters either meeting Bastian at a <br>location where they have already met him or meeting the <br>Cat at a location where they have already recovered Britta’s <br>item, go to the next result.</p><p>133</p>"},"sort":50000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513740373,"modifiedTime":1781513740373,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"L5B6ZuHtmdvEtFQW","name":"Scene 1","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>The Last Wish - Scene 1</h2><p>First Scene<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  It is late in the morning <br>when you finally arrive at the gates of Heidelberg: the city <br>is buzzing with activity, with merchant carts and groups of <br>soldiers going back and forth. This city is a crossroads, and <br>as you might expect, the traffic is heavy. As you contempla-<br>te the difficulty of finding Bastian Soldat in the midst of the <br>city’s hustle and bustle, a voice catches your attention: “Ba-<br>stian! Bastian Soldat, you scoundrel! Come out and give me <br>the money you owe me!” The shouter is a bearded man in a <br>tattered potter’s apron, while the recipient of his insults is a <br>small man with an anonymous face, shaggy blond hair, and <br>a drunkard’s belly. Obviously, you have already found your <br>target.      <br>Place: The Entrance Plaza of Heidelberg. <br>Time: It is midday and the day is slowly warming up as <br>the cackle of taverns and the smell of good food tickle the <br>senses. <br>Initial Situation:  Bastian Soldat rushes through the <br>crowd to get away from the man shouting at him, almost <br>tripping over a black cat that seems to have deliberately got-<br>ten in his way.    <br>Information: The potter complaining about Bastian is <br>called Hugo, and he is angry because the soldier bought <br>some pots in Britta’s name a week ago and never paid for <br>them. Talking to Hugo will give you the following infor -<br>mation:<br> ◆ Bastian is no good and a loafer: he boasts of being an <br>honorably discharged soldier, but when asked to show <br>the medal he received upon his discharge, he always <br>shies away. No one knows where he sleeps, but he is <br>always seen hanging around three Places.<br> ◆ The Drunken Hussar’s Gambling House: A cheap <br>dive bar known for its bad wine and gambling tables.<br> ◆ Villa Wagner: The home of a noble family. Bastian <br>has told everyone he knows that he has fallen in love <br>with the young and beautiful Alena Wagner, dau-<br>ghter of Anselm Wagner, the wealthiest aristocrat in <br>town. <br> ◆ The Golden Plate Tavern: The most expensive and <br>valuable restaurant in the city, where only the weal-<br>thiest can afford a meal.<br> ◆ Britta is an old woman who lives near the town ceme-<br>tery. Many believe her to be a witch, but no one has <br>ever seen her do anything strange enough to support <br>these accusations. <br>Bastian Soldat<br>OL Easy 3 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a deserter with no qualities other than a <br>great desire to live a good life with minimal effort. My only <br>virtue is that I have incredible nerve.<br>Agenda: Emptying the coffers of the Wagner family in order <br>to pretend to be rich in Alena’s eyes and convince her to run <br>away with me to Copenhagen. <br>Gift - Magic Tinderbox: Thanks to this powerful magi-<br>cal object, Bastian can go back in time whenever the situa-<br>tion would prevent him from completing his Agenda. This <br>magical effect cannot be stopped except by the magic word <br>that only Britta knows. Each time Bastian rewinds time, the <br>Storyteller secretly accumulates 1 Reset Token. Each token</p><p>134<br>accumulated makes the three Demonic Dogs more power-<br>ful (see page 142). <br>First Reset: Bastian will avoid returning to Heidelberg’s <br>Entrance Plaza and will stay in one of the other Places he is <br>accustomed to wandering.<br>Second Reset: Bastian will avoid returning to the Place <br>where the Hunters found him and will wander to one of the <br>other two remaining locations. <br>Third Reset: Bastian will avoid returning to the Places <br>where the Hunters found him, and will wander to the last <br>available location.    <br>Fourth Reset: Bastian will avoid returning to all the Pla-<br>ces where the Hunters found him. From that moment on, <br>he will take refuge in the Old Barracks, plan the robbery of <br>Villa Wagner, and then try to escape with Alena. <br>Hugo the Potter<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am an honest craftsman and have been a <br>potter all my life. I have a friendly nature and tend to trust <br>people.         <br>Heidelberg’s Entrance Plaza<br>Descriptor: A large square always filled with citizens and <br>travelers. <br>Information: As the first Place that Bastian will use the <br>Magic Tinderbox to escape the Hunters, this is where the <br>Hunters will start again after each Reset. Unlike normal hu-<br>mans, the Hunters will retain a memory of what happened <br>at each Reset.<br>First Reset: The Hunters will notice that some powerful <br>magic has taken effect, and time seems to have rewound <br>to a few minutes before they meet Bastian. The deserter is <br>absent, but Hugo the Potter is behind his stall, smiling at <br>passersby. The Black Cat walks between the legs of one of <br>the Hunters, stops to watch them with intelligent eyes, and <br>then walks away.    <br>Second Reset: Same as the First Reset, except the Cat <br>will stop with the Hunters and try to get them to follow her, <br>leading them to Britta’s house.<br>Third Reset: Like the First Reset, but this time the Hun-<br>ters will find Anselm Wagner waiting for them with an <br>escort of ten gendarmes. The nobleman will tell the Hun-<br>ters that he has received a report from a trusted man about <br>their impending arrival in the city. The nobleman has made <br>no request of the Order and wants no trouble, so he will <br>ask the Hunters to leave. It will be clear that Anselm has</p><p>135<br>nothing to hide but is simply afraid that the Order’s presen-<br>ce will scare away visitors and ruin the merchants’ business. <br>Fourth Reset: Like the First Reset, except that Bastian <br>has hired a gang of Cutthroats (2 per Character) to elimi-<br>nate the Hunters. <br>After the Fourth Reset: Same as the First Reset.<br>•<br>Anselm Wagner<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am the most important person in the city, <br>involved in politics and with many investments in various <br>activities. Everyone admires my efforts to make Heidelberg <br>prosperous. <br>Agenda: Keep an eye out for potential problems for the city <br>and maintain a clean appearance. <br>•<br>Armsmen of the City<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are swordsmen and have gained experien-<br>ce during the war. We carry out the orders of those who pay <br>us without making too much trouble.  <br>Gift - Companions in Arms:  During an action, they <br>increase their OL by 1 if at least one other Armsman is pre-<br>sent.  <br>Cutthroat <br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are ruthless killers who will do anything to <br>make a profit. We eliminate the target with chilling efficiency. <br>Gift - Assassin: If they act to kill, they are considered to <br>have an OL Medium 5.<br>Information: If questioned, they will not hesitate to reve-<br>al that they were hired by a certain Bastian Soldat. <br>•<br>The Black Cat<br>OL Hard 7 - Main NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a snappy kitten bound to the spirit of old <br>Britta. Thanks to the witch’s power I can understand what <br>people are saying. <br>Agenda: Have the humans help me retrieve Britta’s three <br>items. <br>First Reset:  The Cat will observe the Hunters in the <br>Heidelberg Entrance Plaza to understand why they are not <br>affected by the Magic Tinderbox. It will then go <br>to one of the Places to retrieve Britta’s items. <br>Second Reset:  If the Hunters are intere-<br>sted, the Cat will lead them to Britta’s Hou-<br>se to find her diary. If the diary has already <br>been found, the Cat will take the Hunters to <br>one of the Places to retrieve the items. The <br>Cat will also have retrieved one of the items if <br>the Hunters have not already done so.</p><p>136<br>Third Reset: If the Hunters are interested, the Cat will <br>lead them to Britta’s House to find her diary. If the diary has <br>already been found, the Cat will take the Hunters to one of <br>the Places to retrieve the items. The Cat will also have retrie-<br>ved one of the items if the Hunters have not already done so.<br>Fourth Reset: If the Hunters are interested, the Cat will <br>lead them to Britta’s House to find her diary. If the diary has <br>already been found, the Cat will take the Hunters to one of <br>the Places to retrieve the items. The Cat will also have retrie-<br>ved one of the items if the Hunters have not already done so.<br>After the Fourth Reset: If the Hunters are interested, the <br>Cat will lead them to Britta’s House to find her diary. If the <br>diary has already been found, the Cat will take the Hunters <br>to one of the Places to retrieve the items. The Cat will also <br>have retrieved one of the items if the Hunters have not alre-<br>ady done so.<br>The Drunken Hussar’s <br>Gambling House<br>Descriptor: A dive bar at the end of a slum alley. Amidst <br>the smoke and dim lights, the shadows of the city’s underworld <br>move. <br>Information: The Hussar is run by Ulrich, a former sol-<br>dier who lost his right hand in the war. Ulrich knows Ba-<br>stian well and will not hesitate to tell you that the soldier has <br>gambled away a fortune at the tables of his dive bar. Everyo-<br>ne jokingly refers to Bastian as “the Golden Goose, ” and <br>when he is present, everyone competes to play with him. <br>Ulrich knows that Bastian has fallen head over heels for the <br>Wagner’ young scion and is often at their Villa trying to win <br>Alena’s heart. <br>If Bastian is present: He gambles the last of his coin on <br>dice, and as soon as he sees the Hunters, he tries to escape <br>through the window behind him.<br>If the Black Cat is present:  The Hunters will see her at <br>the entrance to the Gambling House, harassing an old beg-<br>gar. The pet pulls a fine shawl toward her, which the beggar <br>holds tightly. It will be obvious that such a poor man cannot <br>afford such an expensive garment.<br>First Reset: If this is the first time he has encountered <br>them at this Place, Bastian will try to escape. However, if the <br>Hunters have already met him here, Bastian will not show <br>up again. <br>Second Reset: Like the First Reset, except that Ulrich will <br>be offering the Hunters a round of welcome drinks. Bastian <br>has paid him to lace the drinks with poison. If discovered, <br>Ulrich will not hesitate to confess.</p><p>137<br>Third Reset: Same as the First and Second Reset, but if <br>the Hunters have not read Britta’s diary and the Black Cat is <br>present, the animal will try to make the Hunters realize that <br>the Witch’s Shawl is an item to be retrieved. If the Hunters <br>help her, she will lead them to Britta’s House to find the <br>diary.<br>Fourth Reset: Same as previous Resets. <br>After the Fourth Reset: The Gambling House is closed <br>because Ulrich is joining Bastian to rob Villa Wagner. <br>Ulrich Rotten Eye<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a former criminal with experience in the <br>use of poisons. I opened my gambling den looking for a less <br>dangerous life, but I don’t back down when there’s money to <br>be made.<br>Gift - Poisoned Dagger: Ulrich’s weapon is imbued with <br>a powerful poison. The poison first enters play when the <br>weapon inflicts 1 Wound, causing 1 Penalty to the target’s <br>actions. The effect lasts until the victim takes an antidote or <br>has an Interlude. <br>Threat - Poisoned Drink<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: A fine, tasteless, odorless poison that can be <br>added to any beverage. <br>Gift - Poison: Those who ingest the Poisoned Drink suf-<br>fer 1 Wound and receive 1 Penalty until they take an anti-<br>dote or rest in an Interlude. <br>Villa Wagner<br>Descriptor: An imposing mansion surrounded by gardens, <br>ponds, and mazes of hedges. <br>Information: It’s impossible to enter the Villa without an <br>invitation from the Wagner family, but there are no fences <br>and, except for a few gardeners, it is easy to wander incon-<br>spicuously around the large gardens. Alena is often found <br>on the large balcony of her room on the second floor, rea-<br>ding a good book and sipping tea. Alena will tell you that <br>Bastian often brings her very good and expensive cakes that <br>he buys at the famous Golden Plate Tavern. The young wo-<br>man is unclear about who Bastian really is, but it will be ob-<br>vious that she is attracted to the funny little man and finds <br>his awkward attempts to court her tender.<br>If Bastian is present: He will be under Alena’s balcony <br>reciting some love poetry. As soon as he sees the Hunters, <br>he will try to escape by slipping into one of the hedge ma-<br>zes.<br>If the Black Cat is present:  It can be seen on the bal-<br>cony being petted by Alena. The Cat pretends to purr in <br>affection as she clearly tries to snatch a pendant from the <br>young woman’s neck.<br>First Reset:  If this is the first time he encounters the <br>Hunters in this Place, Bastian will try to escape. However, <br>if the Hunters have already met him here, Bastian will not <br>appear again.<br>Second Reset:  Same as the First Reset, except that a <br>group of guards (2 per Hunter) will enter the Scene when <br>the Hunters approach Alena. The leader of the guards will <br>say that by Lord Wagner’s order, no one can enter the gar-<br>den of the Villa. If the Hunters can get the captain to talk</p><p>138<br>more, he will say that an informant has alerted Lord Wa-<br>gner that a group of robbers are roaming the city and rai-<br>ding the villas of the nobles.<br>Third Reset: Same as the First and Second Reset, but if <br>the Hunters have not read Britta’s diary and the Black Cat <br>is present, the animal will try to make the Hunters under -<br>stand that the Black Coral Pendant is an item to be retrie-<br>ved. If the Hunters help the Cat, she will lead them to Brit-<br>ta’s House to find the diary.<br>Fourth Reset: Same as the previous reset. <br>After the Fourth Reset:  Alena will not be on the bal-<br>cony as usual. Bastian has written her a letter asking her <br>to meet him behind the Golden Plate Tavern at sunset. Ba-<br>stian wants to do the job at the Villa without Alena being <br>there. Afterward, he’ll suggest that they run away together.  <br>Villa Wagner’s Guard<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are loyal and well-trained for our duties as <br>guardians. <br>Gift - Guard Corps: During an action, increase their OL <br>by 1 if they are defending Villa Wagner from a threat or <br>perceived threat.<br>Alena Wagner<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am the young scion of the Wagner family. I <br>love adventure and romance novels. I’m cultured and dream <br>of becoming a teacher one day.  <br>Agenda: To have a good adventure like the ones I read <br>about in novels.<br>Wagner Treasury<br>Descriptor: A small fortified tower connected to <br>the Villa by an underground tunnel. Aside from the <br>tunnel, the only way to access the tower is to know <br>the combination of the large metal door that <br>blocks the main entrance.<br>Information: The Treasury is permanently <br>manned by 4 Guards who change shifts every <br>eight hours.<br>First, Second, and Third Reset:  Bastian</p><p>139<br>has obtained the information he needs for the robbery <br>days before the Hunters arrive, so he will not be wandering <br>around the Treasury beforehand. <br>Fourth Reset: Bastian will attempt to rob the Treasury. <br>The plan is simple: Bastian and four other soldiers he met <br>at the barracks will enter through Villa Wagner and use the <br>secret tunnel to get into the Treasury. Meanwhile, Ulrich <br>will have slipped a powerful sleeping pill into the food in-<br>tended for the four Guards guarding the entrance. Once <br>the Guards are asleep, Bastian will open the door and each <br>gang member will fill two large sacks with gold and va-<br>luables. Unbeknownst to the other gang members, Bastian <br>is planning to betray them. Once outside the Villa, he will <br>separate from the group, warn the gendarmes of the theft, <br>and then pick up Alena to escape with her. Bastian’s inten-<br>tion is to cover his escape by drawing attention to the other <br>gang members.  <br> <br>Threat - Treasury Door<br>OL Hard 7<br>Descriptor: A huge metal door reinforced to resist any <br>burglary attempt. The combination to open it is 05031762, <br>Alena’s date of birth.<br>Robbers<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are veteran soldiers and have seen the hor-<br>rors of war. We do not shy away from danger and have no <br>qualms about committing acts of cruelty.  <br>The Golden Plate Tavern<br>Descriptor: The finest and most famous tavern in Heidel-<br>berg: Brigit’s cuisine is of the highest standard, but only the <br>very rich can afford it.<br>Information: There are no rooms to sleep in at the Ta-<br>vern, which is best known for the haute cuisine of Chef Bri-<br>git. Nobles and rich men come from all over Europe to taste <br>the food of the Golden Plate. Brigit became accustomed to <br>Bastian’s presence, always showering her with complimen-<br>ts on her cooking. At first, Bastian was a good customer, <br>but soon he had no money to pay for the meals, and Brigit <br>gave him credit until she realized that the soldier was a lost <br>cause. If asked about Bastian, Brigit will say that he is a go-<br>od-tempered man who tries to live far beyond his means. <br>When he is not eating at the Golden Plate, Bastian is often <br>at the Drunken Hussar’s Gambling House, where he gam-<br>bles and tries to accumulate some money.<br>If Bastian is present:  He will sit at the table and beg <br>Brigit to serve him one of her fantastic dishes. As soon as <br>he sees the Hunters, he will try to escape by sneaking into <br>the kitchens.<br>If the Black Cat is present:  The Hunters will see her <br>through the half-open door into the kitchen as she tries to <br>knock down an old ladle hanging on the wall with her paw. <br>The Cat is unsuccessful, as someone always intervenes to <br>chase it away. Brigit will complain that the animal seems <br>to be obsessed with the old ladle given to her by the elderly <br>Britta. <br>First Reset:  If this is the first time he encounters the <br>Hunters in this Place, Bastian will try to escape. However, <br>if the Hunters have already met him here, Bastian will not <br>appear again.</p><p>Second Reset: Same as the First Reset, except that a <br>group of Cutthroats (2 per Hunter, see page 135) are <br>preparing to ambush the Hunters when they leave the Ta-<br>vern.    <br>Third Reset: Same as the First and Second Reset, but if <br>the Hunters have not read Britta’s diary and the Black Cat <br>is present, the animal will try to make the Hunters under-<br>stand that the Devil’s Ladle is an item to be retrieved. If <br>the Hunters help her, she will lead them to Britta’s house <br>to find the diary.<br>Fourth Reset: Same as the previous reset. <br>After the Fourth Reset:  Brigit is cleaning a table. If <br>asked she will say that Bastian came to dinner with four <br>other shady characters. They spent the whole time bab-<br>bling about tunnels and guard shifts. He paid for everyone <br>and then they left.   <br>Brigit the Cook<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a good cook, the best. I love my tavern <br>and can’t stand any argument between my tables.     <br>The Old Barracks<br>Descriptor: A dirty old building where soldiers on leave <br>can sleep for free.<br>Information: Bastian sleeps in the Old Barracks, but <br>has never told anyone about it because it would damage <br>the image of wealth and prosperity he is trying to build <br>in Alena’s eyes. Bastian has joined forces with four other <br>deserters who will help him in his plan to rob Villa Wa-<br>gner. In the Barracks, many people know Bastian and will <br>describe him as a blowhard, but too stupid to actually <br>amount to anything.<br>If Bastian is present: At night, Bastian sleeps in a se-<br>cret room on the second floor of the building. If disco-<br>vered, he will try to escape by throwing himself out the <br>window to cause a Reset.<br>After any Reset caused in this Place:  Bastian will <br>not go back to sleep but will use Ulrich to send messages <br>to his co-conspirators.<br>Britta’s House<br>Descriptor: A small abandoned house near the gra -<br>veyard. In the garden, in the middle of a vegetable patch <br>and near a well, there is an old hollow tree with no leaves.<br>Information: The Hollow Tree in the garden hides a <br>burrow that leads to a series of Caves. Descending into <br>the Caves, Hunters can find Britta’s decapitated body. The <br>witch’s spirit is still bound to the body, but the only way to <br>communicate with her is with a Gift that allows it. In the <br>little house, Hunters can find Britta’s diary open on the <br>kitchen table. In the diary, the witch describes in detail</p><p>141<br>her agreement with Bastian to retrieve the Tinderbox from <br>the Caves, and the soldier’s insistence on having more mo-<br>ney after the reward. In the diary, Britta also regrets asking <br>for Bastian’s help, as the soldier turned out to be a stupid <br>opportunist.<br>Resets: Bastian will never be in Britta’s House, and the <br>Cat is busy collecting magic items to revive the witch, so <br>the situation in this Place is always the same, no matter the <br>Reset. <br>Caves under the <br>Hollow Tree<br>Descriptor: A series of caves that were once the home of a <br>witch, but are now uninhabited.    <br>Information: Traces of ancient magic and strange mar -<br>kings on the walls are the only evidence of what the Caves <br>once were. Britta’s headless corpse stands in the center of <br>the first room, her hands and feet making unconscious mo-<br>vements, making it clear that the body is not dead, but also <br>incapable of action.<br>Britta the Beheaded Witch<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a skilled witch who only desires a quiet <br>life. Since I no longer have a head, I cannot speak or utter <br>magic formulas. <br>Agenda: To find my head that Bastian threw in the river. <br>Information: Britta’s body will revive when two of her <br>three magical items are placed on her. In this state, Britta <br>will not be able to speak, but she will be able to write, in-<br>forming the Hunters that she knows where her head is and <br>will go to retrieve it. In the meantime, Britta will ask the <br>Hunters to retrieve the third object to complete her resur -<br>rection. <br>Britta the Witch<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a skilled witch who wishes only to live a <br>quiet life, using my powers only to help others.<br>Agenda: Stop the power of the Magic Tinderbox before the <br>Demonic Dogs inside it become too powerful.    <br>Gift - Britta’s Witchcraft:  Britta can perform various <br>rituals to achieve different effects: she can find someone or <br>something, she can change the weather in the area, or she <br>can communicate with and take control of an animal. All of <br>these rituals take about ten minutes to complete. Britta can <br>also dispel magic, a practice in which she is a true master. <br>In a single action, Britta can end a spell or block the power <br>of a Treasure of the Order until the end of the Scene. <br>Information: Britta will tell the Hunters the secret of the <br>Magic Tinderbox and that she can use her magic to stop the <br>disasters Bastian is causing, but there is a catch. Once the <br>Magic Tinderbox’s power is blocked, the three Demonic <br>Dogs inside will be released and must be defeated to send <br>them back into the magical object.</p><p>142<br>Demonic Dogs<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC  <br>(2 Wounds - 3 Dogs)<br>Descriptor: We are ancient demons and take the form of <br>dogs to mingle with humans. We can fly and with our fangs, <br>we tear at the soft flesh of our prey. <br>Agenda: To kill as many humans as possible and thereby <br>increase our power.     <br>Gift - Demonic Powers:  These creatures can fly, with <br>all the narrative benefits that brings. As supernatural crea-<br>tures, Demonic Dogs are immune to all effects of fear and <br>mind manipulation. Those who use magic against them <br>take 1 Penalty to all related Checks and must pay 1 additio-<br>nal Soma if it is required to activate magic. A Demonic Dog <br>can spend 1 Reset Token to increase its OL to Hard 7 for a <br>single action, but not to defend itself. <br>Information: When the Demonic Dogs are defeated, <br>Britta or a witch who has read her diary can place a ma-<br>gical seal on the Magic Tinderbox: <br>the object will lose some of <br>its power and become the <br>Treasure of the Order, <br>The Tinderbox of Se-<br>cond Chances (see page <br>28).  <br>Scenario Gifts<br>These Gifts represent special abilities related to The Last <br>Wish Scenario and can be acquired once conditions are <br>met. A Hunter can acquire one Scenario Gift. If they ac-<br>quire a new one during an Interlude, they will have to forgo <br>the previous one.<br>Déjà vu <br>Requirement: Witness the effect of one or more Resets.<br>By experiencing temporal shifts, you are able to notice the <br>small differences in the fabric of reality. Once per Scene, <br>you can spend 1 Soma to activate each of the following ef-<br>fects:<br>1. I’ve Already Got It: Y ou already have an item that be-<br>longs to the Place you are in, and if it is a unique item, no <br>one has noticed that it is missing.<br>2. I Was Already Here: Y ou can move to any Place you <br>can see from where you are without anyone being able to <br>stop you; to the eyes of anyone present, it will look as if you <br>have always been where you are now.<br>3. I’ve Seen It Before: The Storyteller will reveal the <br>effect of a particular Gift or equipment from an NPC in <br>front of you that you must have known or met before.<br>Note: This Gift can only be used when the use of a <br>spell that affects the normal flow of time is manife-<br>sted, like a Reset. Outside of this Scenario, it is up <br>to the Storyteller to determine if the Hunter can use <br>this Gift again.</p><p>143<br>Tremble, the Witches are Back<br>Requirement: Learn from Britta the magic of infusing an <br>object with the essence of life.  <br>A portion of your vitality is infused into an item in your <br>Equipment. As long as you have the item with you, once <br>per Session you can restore 1 Wound and 1 Soma by cal-<br>ling upon the power of your own soul. Y ou can activate this <br>effect even if you have already taken your last Wound and <br>are unconscious.  <br>The Last Wish <br>in Scenes</p><p>FIRST SCENE –  Entering Hei-<br>delberg<br>It is the same as on page 134, except that after Bastian’s Re-<br>set, Hugo will give the following information to the Hun-<br>ters:<br> ◆ Hugo is angry because Bastian bought some pots in <br>Britta’s name a week ago and never paid for them.<br> ◆ Bastian is no good and a layabout, bragging that he <br>is an honorably discharged soldier, but when asked <br>to show the medal he received for his discharge, he <br>always prevaricates. No one knows where he sleeps, but <br>he is always seen hanging out at the Drunken Hussar’s <br>Gambling House, a cheap dive known for bad wine and <br>gambling tables.<br>End of Scene: Hugo will then tell the Hunters that, if they <br>want to find Bastian, they must go to the Drunken Hussar’s <br>Gambling House; go to SECOND SCENE - The Drunken <br>Hussar’s Gambling House.</p>"},"sort":100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513740374,"modifiedTime":1781513740374,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"Vyla5NwZyg1KJYe9","name":"Scene 2","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>The Last Wish - Scene 2</h2><p>SECOND SCENE –  The Drun-<br>ken Hussar’s Gambling House<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: You arrive at what appears <br>to be a small tavern, a few candles barely illuminating an <br>old, rotting building that has not been cleaned in years. Grim <br>faces stare at you, letting you know that you may not be wel-<br>come. Then the sound of a cup shattering makes you all turn <br>around: Bastian is standing at the bar, watching you with <br>wide eyes. He turns to the window behind him and makes a <br>desperate escape. <br>Place: The filthy Drunken Hussar’s Gambling House. <br>Time: It is late in the morning, but there are already many <br>customers at the tables trying their luck.<br>Information: Once Bastian is captured, the power of the <br>Tinderbox will be activated and the Hunters will find them-<br>selves back in Heidelberg’s Entrance Plaza, where they will <br>be approached by the Black Cat. It will be easy to tell by the <br>light in her eyes that this is no ordinary animal. The Cat <br>will lead the Hunters to Britta’s House, and here they can <br>get their hands on the witch’s diary and understand what is <br>happening. In the diary, Britta also notes the spell she used <br>to imbue three objects with her life force, which, when re-<br>trieved, can bring her back to life. A Pendant, a Shawl, and <br>a Ladle are drawn in the diary. The Cat will make it clear <br>that she can lead the Hunters to the objects, pointing with <br>her paw at the diary to figure out which one to start with. <br>End of Scene:  The Hunters must decide in which order <br>to retrieve the items, go to THIRD SCENE - The Retrieval.<br>2<br>1</p><p>144</p>"},"sort":200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513740374,"modifiedTime":1781513740374,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"8lW7z1xZa29H5ALS","name":"Scene 3","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>The Last Wish - Scene 3</h2><p>THIRD SCENE –  The Retrieval<br>Note: This Scene will be played three times to allow the <br>Hunters to retrieve all 3 of Britta’s items. The first two Places <br>visited must be Villa Wagner and the Golden Plate Tavern, <br>leaving the Drunken Hussar’s Gambling House for last. <br>Places: Villa Wagner, the Golden Plate Tavern, and the <br>Drunken Hussar’s Gambling House. <br>Time: Early afternoon, late afternoon, and evening. <br>Information: Depending on the Place, the following si-<br>tuations will occur.<br> ◆ Villa Wagner: Alena will be kind and helpful to the <br>Hunters and will gladly give them the Black Coral Pen-<br>dant if they ask for it. When the Hunters leave the Villa, <br>they will be ambushed by the Cutthroats (page 135) <br>hired by Bastian. <br> ◆ The Golden Plate Tavern:  Brigit will not want <br>anyone to enter her beloved kitchen, and the Hunters <br>must find a way to distract the cook and retrieve the <br>Devil’s Ladle. <br> ◆ The Drunken Hussar’s Gambling House:  Ulri -<br>ch will attempt to poison the Hunters as described on <br>page 136. Backed into a corner, Ulrich will say that <br>Bastian is planning to rob Villa Wagner’s Treasury to <br>get his hands on the family treasures. <br>End of Scene:  If the Hunters have not recovered all the <br>items, repeat this Scene at a new Place. If the Hunters also <br>recovered the Shawl at the Hussar and questioned Ulrich, <br>go to the FOURTH SCENE - Britta’s Return.</p>"},"sort":300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513740374,"modifiedTime":1781513740374,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"hbNIHBjd0XfhGV4k","name":"Scene 4","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>The Last Wish - Scene 4</h2><p>FOURTH SCENE –  Britta’s Re-<br>turn<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: The little cat leads you back <br>to the house near the graveyard, and here, in the garden of <br>the house, it starts scratching on the bark of an old hollow <br>tree. At closer inspection, the tree appears to be the entrance <br>to caves descending into the darkness.<br>Place: Britta’s House and the old Hollow Tree leading to <br>her corpse. <br>Time: Late night. <br>Information: Upon recovering Britta’s body and appro-<br>aching her three objects, the witch will come back to life <br>but will be headless. Britta’s animated body will then lead <br>the Hunters to the nearby river to find her head. With this <br>bizarre task completed, the witch will come to her senses <br>and be able to explain to the Hunters the danger posed by <br>the misuse of the Magic Tinderbox. <br>End of Scene:  The Hunters have learned from Ulrich <br>about the robbery Bastian is planning at Villa Wagner, go <br>to the FIFTH SCENE - The Great Heist.<br>3 4</p><p>145</p>"},"sort":400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513740374,"modifiedTime":1781513740374,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"CbVYmqjLnV5vrs32","name":"Scene 5","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>The Last Wish - Scene 5</h2><p>FIFTH SCENE –  The Great Heist <br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  As you enter the large garden of Villa Wagner at dawn, a group <br>of shadows draws your attention, and Bastian’s shout forces everyone to turn around. The soldier <br>gestures nervously as he tells you with tears in his eyes, “Enough! Why are you always getting in my <br>way? Leave me alone!” Then Bastian gestures to his comrades, and the small group approaches you <br>menacingly. <br>Place: The large garden of Villa Wagner. <br>Time: The sun is rising, and soon the whole city will wake up. <br>End of Scene: Unwilling to risk his life, Bastian will try to escape after giving the order to his <br>people. If caught, he will activate the Magic Tinderbox for the umpteenth time and accidentally <br>summon the three Demon Dogs. Having dealt with this threat, the Hunters must now decide <br>what to do with Bastian. <br>5</p>"},"sort":500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513740374,"modifiedTime":1781513740374,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}],"folder":null,"flags":{"broken-tales":{"adventureSlug":"the-last-wish","collection":"Lost Stories","sourceFile":"bt-ls-book-1-ENG-SCREEN.pdf","pages":"131-146"}},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513740374,"modifiedTime":1781513740374,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}
{"_id":"8kZGkfXlbUb4HcA4","name":"A Frozen Reflection","pages":[{"_id":"HGahDAIlba8m3A88","name":"Summary","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h1>A Frozen Reflection</h1><p><strong>Collection:</strong> Lost Stories</p><p><strong>Source:</strong> bt-ls-book-1-ENG-SCREEN.pdf, pages 201-227.</p><p><img src=\"systems/broken-tales/assets/adventures/maps/a-frozen-reflection-p201-full.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto;\" /></p>"},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513746052,"modifiedTime":1781513746052,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"4hZSZf33KEnLlCsa","name":"Setup","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>A Frozen Reflection - Setup</h2><p>200<br>A Frozen Reflection <br> A Scenario Inspired by The Snow Queen<br>Part One – The Two Healers<br>Safety keywords: Illness / Poisoning / Identity theft<br>A Frozen Reflection is a special three-part Scenario that tells the story of <br>the mysterious con artists Gerda and Kay. All Scenarios are structured as <br>a Scene Tree (see page 100 of the Broken Tales Core Book) and are great for <br>introductory Sessions or a mini-Campaign. A Storyteller who prefers an <br>emergent style of storytelling will still find Events and information useful <br>for handling more free-form Hunter action.</p><p>201<br>The Fragments of the <br>Mirror of the Other Self<br>In this Scenario, several NPCs have been affected by the <br>Shards of the Mirror of the Other Self, magical Shards <br>that can reverse a person’s abilities and dispositions. All <br>NPCs affected by the Shard receive the Gift - Power of the <br>Shard, which provides a Shard Descriptor and a Shard <br>Agenda to replace the original ones until the Mirror <br>Shard is removed. To remove a Mirror Shard, you must <br>deal with the Threat - Shard of the Mirror of the Other <br>Self. <br>Threat – Shard of the Mirror of <br>the Other Self<br>OL Hard 7<br>Descriptor: A tiny shard of mirror capable of emitting <br>icy cold.<br>Gift - The Shard:  Removing the Shard is a complex <br>procedure that requires medical skills or the assistance <br>of magic. Once removed, the Shard loses all of its power, <br>disintegrating into thin air and inflicting 1 Wound on the <br>person who removed it. This Wound can only be avoided <br>by spending an Increment on a potential Check to re-<br>move the Shard. <br>Miss Snow and Lady Storm in this <br>Scenario<br>When a Hunter is connected to the story on which a Sce-<br>nario is based, an Exclusive Gift is usually presented that <br>can be obtained under certain narrative conditions. This <br>is a special case, however, because the Hunter Miss Snow <br>and Lady Storm is directly involved in the plot of A Frozen <br>Reflection. For this reason, the Storyteller must carefully <br>consider whether to introduce this Hunter and how to deal <br>with the resulting plot changes. Here are some tips:<br> ◆ None of the NPCs who have met Lady Storm will rec-<br>ognize her while she is in the form of Miss Snow. In-<br>stead, the Hunter’s identity will be revealed when she <br>activates her Dark Ego. All NPCs who contributed in <br>any way to Lady Storm’s downfall will fear her and try <br>to have as little to do with her as possible.<br> ◆ No one knows that Miss Snow is Lady Storm, so there <br>will be no qualms or special care in saying the word <br>Eternity.<br> ◆ During PART THREE - The Winter Castle, if the Ice <br>Heart sees Lady Storm in action, it will be willing to <br>sacrifice itself to get its mistress back; if Lady Storm <br>manifests during the Scene, the Ice Heart will shatter, <br>warmed by the love for its queen.</p><p>202<br>Once upon a time…<br>A terrible epidemic has struck the provinces of Norway, on <br>the borders of the Kingdom of Denmark. Frozen Madness is a <br>disease that only affects humans and literally drives them in-<br>sane. Not even the best doctors in the kingdom have been able <br>to find a cure for the terrible disease, leaving the families of <br>the sick in utter despair. The sudden appearance of the myste-<br>rious healers Kay and Gerda has brought a ray of hope to the <br>fight against the Frozen Madness: after proving that they can <br>cure the disease, the two have taken refuge in a remote castle <br>in the far north, forcing the families of the sick to undertake <br>a long and costly journey to obtain the cure. There are many <br>rumors of expeditions that have ended in tragedy, as brigands <br>and vicious animals make it seem impossible to reach Gerda <br>and Kay without paying handsomely for a good guide. But a <br>disease that has only one doctor is a strange thing, especially <br>since the dreaded disease appeared shortly before the arrival <br>of the two dubious healers. This fact did not go unnoticed <br>by the Order, which decided to send a group of Hunters to <br>investigate... <br>The story that led us here…<br>Gerda and Kay are two young scoundrels who have <br>always lived from hand to mouth. By a stroke of luck, the <br>two have come into possession of many Shards of the Mir-<br>ror of the Other Self, a powerful magical object capable of <br>reversing the character of those injured by one of its Shards. <br>With the help of a witch named Flora, Gerda and Kay in-<br>troduced themselves to the powerful witch Lady Storm and <br>managed to strike her with a magical Shard. Storm lost her <br>abilities and became a naive and bungling sorceress. Us-<br>ing Flora’s power, Gerda and Kay forced poor Miss Snow <br>(Lady Storm’s new identity) to create a great storm that <br>would sweep across Northern Europe, releasing most of the <br>Shards from the Mirror of the Other Self to affect as many <br>innocent people as possible, spreading the Frozen Mad-<br>ness. Unable to handle such a powerful atmospheric event, <br>Miss Snow was carried away, only to be found by the Order <br>with no memory. After the Frozen Madness spread, Gerda <br>and Kay used Lady Storm’s magic sleigh to travel to the ma-<br>jor cities of Norway, presenting themselves as healers of the <br>mysterious disease that no one could eradicate. After be-<br>coming famous, the pair retreated to Lady Storm’s castle. As <br>a consequence,    the families of the sick are cruelly forced <br>to spend large sums of money on a journey of hope, only <br>to find that hope dashed when they are led straight into the <br>clutches of Gerda and Kay’s servants.<br>The story at the arrival of the <br>Hunters…<br>The Hunters arrive in Bergen, where nobleman Aleksander <br>Okland has fallen victim to the dangerous Frozen Madness. <br>Fredrika, the nobleman’s daughter, has been trying to cure <br>her father, finally turning to the Order when it became clear <br>that her beloved parent’s complete change of character was <br>not the result of an ordinary illness. Meanwhile, Kay and <br>Gerda struck Flora with a Shard, turning the cunning old <br>charmer into a naive and clueless old woman. Flora had <br>made too many demands in exchange for cooperating with <br>the two imposters, so Gerda and Kay immediately took ac-<br>tion to get her out of the way. Since Flora is quite famous in <br>Bergen, where she used to live, the two led the witch back <br>to her old home, so that everyone would believe that the <br>woman had simply succumbed to dementia.</p><p>203</p>"},"sort":50000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513746054,"modifiedTime":1781513746054,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"XwjL3DAZWXV7sFaI","name":"Scene 1","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>A Frozen Reflection - Scene 1</h2><p>FIRST SCENE – Bergen<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: You arrive in Bergen as the <br>sun is setting, but what you see is hardly the tranquility of a <br>city resting after a long day of activity. Men and women are <br>wandering the streets shouting and gesturing outrageously, <br>then wriggling away from desperate relatives trying to calm <br>them down. As described in the letter from the young Okland <br>scion, the Frozen Madness seems to have hit Bergen hard, <br>driving many of its inhabitants mad. A young servant runs <br>up to you and, after a brief bow, waves for you to follow him <br>to the large mansion down the street. <br>Place: The Okland family mansion in the city’s wealthiest <br>neighborhood.<br>Time: The sun is setting as the cries of people <br>suffering from Frozen Madness echo from the <br>streets. <br>Initial Situation: Fredrika Okland will intro-<br>duce herself to the Hunters by inviting them to <br>dinner, accompanied by her father Aleksander, <br>who suffers from the Frozen Madness. Fredrika <br>will ask the Hunters to forgive her father’s excess-<br>es in light of his condition. <br>Information: Fredrika will tell the Hunters <br>that three months ago a very heavy snowstorm <br>hit Northern Europe, especially the Norwegian <br>coast. After the storm, many people began to <br>show signs of madness, behaving in ways that <br>were the opposite of their usual behavior. Her fa-<br>ther Aleksander, who had always been a calm and <br>jovial man, became hot-tempered and arrogant, <br>with outbursts of unnecessary violence. At first, <br>no doctor could find a cure. Then two mysteri-<br>ous healers from the north named Gerda and Kay <br>cured some nobles for a hefty fee. As soon as word <br>spread of healers who could cure the Frozen Madness, the <br>two disappeared, and now to meet them one must contact <br>the Black Feathers: two local guides who charge exorbitant <br>sums of money to bring desperate people to Gerda and Kay.<br>During the discussion, this information will also emerge:<br> ◆ Near Bergen lives a famous witch named Flora. Many <br>have turned to her for healing, but the old woman <br>seems to have fallen victim to dementia, or perhaps she <br>herself has been struck by the Frozen Madness. Flora is <br>famous for her potions, which she distills in the large <br>greenhouse where she grows all sorts of herbs. <br> ◆ The only contact with the Black Feathers in town seems <br>to be an elderly woman named Lene. The woman was <br>1</p><p>204<br>once the head of a criminal organization but <br>has retired to private life to enjoy the fruits of <br>her misdeeds. Few have the courage to both-<br>er her without offering something of value in <br>return. <br>During dinner, Aleksander behaves inappropri-<br>ately, trying in every way possible to humiliate <br>his daughter and question the Hunters’ actions. If <br>provoked, Aleksander will not hesitate to use vi-<br>olence.<br>Fredrika Okland<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am the young scion of the Okland family, I believe in jus-<br>tice and honesty as my father taught me. <br>Agenda: To heal my father and make him the good man who raised me.<br>Aleksander Okland<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a rich and powerful nobleman, and I use my position to help <br>all unfortunate people. I can’t stand the bullying of the weak by the powerful, <br>and I strive to change society so that everything is more equal.    <br>Agenda: Helping others find their way and realize their plans.    <br>Shard Descriptor: I am a rich and powerful nobleman, and I use my <br>position to bend everyone to my command. I can’t stand to be told no, and I <br>abuse all the people I consider inferior.<br>Shard Agenda: Satisfying my thirst for power by crushing those who are <br>weaker. <br>Gift - Power of the Shard:  The Shard of the Mirror of the Other Self re-<br>verses the Descriptor and Agenda of the person it injured. The holder increas-<br>es their OL by 1 if they act in accordance with the altered part of their De-<br>scriptor or Agenda. <br>End of Scene:  The Hunters must decide whether to contact Flora or the <br>Black Feathers through Lene. Go to SECOND SCENE OPTION A - Flora’s <br>Greenhouse or SECOND SCENE OPTION B - Lene’s House.</p><p>205</p>"},"sort":100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513746054,"modifiedTime":1781513746054,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"JbWNm0aneMryPW46","name":"Scene 2","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>A Frozen Reflection - Scene 2</h2><p>SECOND SCENE OPTION A –  <br>Flora’s Greenhouse<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: The home of the famous Flo-<br>ra is located just outside the city limits, along a large stream <br>that runs along the eastern side of Bergen. The witch’s home <br>stands out in the middle of the countryside as a colorful <br>building flanked by a huge greenhouse. When you reach the <br>entrance, there are no lights on in the house, while someone <br>in the greenhouse seems to be happily humming a <br>childish song.<br>Place: The House and Greenhouse of the witch <br>Flora.<br>Time: The sun has set and the moonlight softly il-<br>luminates the Bergen countryside.<br>Information: Flora has taken up permanent residence <br>in the Greenhouse and, in the grip of the Shard effect, be-<br>witches and imprisons those who visit her, then forgets her <br>victims among the plants. Inside the House, the Hunters <br>can get their hands on the witch’s diary, in which Flora has <br>written some important information about Gerda and Kay. <br>In the House:  The House is protected by Flora’s magic, <br>and breaking in without her permission will activate her <br>defenses. The House is well-maintained and filled with an-<br>cient magical relics. There are four rooms in total, two of <br>which are of interest to Hunters: the Storeroom on the first <br>floor and Flora’s Bedroom on the second floor. <br>Threat - Haunted House<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: A house that emits an aura of ignorant <br>well-being, relaxing intruders into sleep. <br>Gift - Induced Fatigue:  For each room visited in the <br>House, roll one die for each intruder:<br>1-3: Nothing happens.<br>4-6: They lose 1 Soma. <br>On the second point of Soma lost to this Gift, a Hunter <br>must pass a Defense Check to avoid falling into an eight-<br>hour deep sleep from which they cannot be awakened. For <br>an NPC, the effect is triggered when they lose Soma equal <br>to the category of their OL: 1 for Easy, 2 for Medium, and <br>3 for Hard.<br>Flora’s Bedroom<br>Descriptor: A richly decorated room with a large canopy <br>bed. Flowers and plants of all kinds grow on the walls, giving <br>the impression of being in a small greenhouse. <br>Information: The Hunters will quickly notice a small box <br>on the wardrobe next to the bed. Inside is Flora’s diary, but <br>as you might guess, a witch’s box can’t be opened by just <br>anyone.<br>2a</p><p>206<br>Warden Casket<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a fierce Warden Casket, ready to bite any <br>thief with my sharp teeth. I am very sensitive to bad smells, <br>which makes me sneeze until I vomit my contents. <br>Information: Flora’s diary describes Gerda and Kay, two <br>criminals who proposed the Frozen Madness scam to Flo-<br>ra. Flora seems to have agreed mainly to take revenge on an <br>old rival of hers, a witch named Lady Storm. The contact <br>between Flora and the two criminals was facilitated by a <br>woman named Lene, who is identified in the diary as Ger -<br>da’s mother. Flora reports that she is not too happy about <br>involving so many innocent people in this plan, but the <br>chance to teach the arrogant and haughty Lady Storm a <br>lesson was too good to pass up. Flora does not trust Gerda <br>and Kay, but she does not believe that the two criminals can <br>pose any real danger to her. <br>Storeroom<br>Descriptor: A small room filled with books, gardening <br>tools, and strange vials.<br>Information: Hidden among the many stacked objects it <br>is possible to find a Treasure of the Order. The Storyteller is <br>free to decide which one.<br>The Greenhouse<br>Descriptor: A large greenhouse filled with vegetation. A <br>thick mist of pollen chokes those who walk through the rows <br>of plants and flowers with its smell. <br>Information:  Flora has taken up residence in the Green-<br>house, where she repeats the same tasks over and over <br>again. Without her careful oversight, many of the plants <br>have grown beyond control, and the ecosystem of the place <br>has become mixed with the witch’s out-of-control magic. <br>Moving inside the Greenhouse activates the Threat - Magic <br>Greenhouse. Flora is in the center of it and will not move <br>under any circumstances.<br>Threat - Magic Greenhouse<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: A greenhouse filled with strange plants im-<br>bued with Flora’s magical powers. <br>Gift - Wild Plants:  The Greenhouse plants will identify <br>anyone other than Flora as a threat. The plants rely on smell <br>to detect intruders, so they can be fooled. If a person enters <br>the Greenhouse, roll 1 die:<br>1-2: A carnivorous plant attempts to bite the target to in-<br>flict 1 Wound. <br>3-4: A colored pollen covers the target, which takes 1 <br>Penalty on all actions while in the Greenhouse. A Defense <br>Check is needed to avoid the pollen.<br>5-6: A large flower emits a sharp hissing sound that stuns <br>the target and causes them to lose 1 Soma (1 Wound, in the <br>case of an NPC).</p><p>207<br>Flora the Witch<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a powerful witch who has dedicated her <br>life to the study of nature-based magic. I wish to be admired <br>and recognized for my abilities as a witch.    <br>Agenda: To gain the respect of others through my powers <br>and live a comfortable life. <br>Shard Descriptor: I am a clumsy witch who loves <br>plants, but unfortunately I have forgotten how to take care <br>of my beloved greenhouse. I am humble and don’t care what <br>others think of me, because all I want is to speak to the hearts <br>of plants. <br>Shard Agenda: Take care of my greenhouse and keep <br>away any pests that come after me. <br>Gift - Power of the Shard:  The Shard of the Mirror of <br>the Other Self reverses the Descriptor and Agenda of the <br>person it injured. The holder increases their OL by 1 if they <br>act in accordance with the altered part of their Descriptor <br>or Agenda.    <br>Gift - Plant Witch:  Flora can manipulate nearby plants <br>by animating them, and thanks to this power, she can per-<br>form up to 2 actions in the Exchange with a range equal to <br>the ground covered by the plants themselves. Through the <br>plants, Flora can attempt to injure, immobilize, or manip-<br>ulate a target. <br>Information: If the Hunters succeed in removing the <br>Shard from Flora’s eye, the old witch will come to her <br>senses, but the effects of the Shard will have permanent <br>consequences for her. Drained of all magical power, the <br>old woman will try to bargain with the Hunters for the in-<br>formation she possesses in exchange for being exonerated <br>of all charges. Flora will then talk about Gerda and Kay’s <br>plan, as described in The story that led us here. Flora will <br>not know the location of Lady Storm’s castle, as its entrance <br>is protected by powerful magic. However, she will tell the <br>Hunters that if they continue along the river bordering <br>Bergen, they can reach the small White Hospital: a facility <br>where Gerda and Kay reside when they leave the castle. To <br>get there, Flora will tell the Hunters to look for the Black <br>Feather boat in the small river port of Bergen.<br>End of Scene:  The Hunters decide to meet the Black <br>Feathers through Lene. Go to SECOND SCENE OPTION <br>B - Lene’s House. If they decide to leave directly instead, go <br>to the THIRD SCENE - The Ambush of the Black Feathers.</p><p>208</p><p>SECOND SCENE OPTION B –  <br>Lene’s House<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  In the slums of Bergen you <br>will find a small, seemingly abandoned house. Only the lights <br>inside indicate someone’s presence. You feel several eyes on <br>you and realize that hooded figures are keeping watch on the <br>street. There is no doubt that you have entered the territory <br>of a gang...<br>Place: Lene’s little abandoned house in the slums of Ber-<br>gen. <br>Time: The sun has now set and the only source of illumi-<br>nation is the many lights coming from the houses in town.<br>Information: Lene welcomes every visitor to the house <br>and offers herself as a contact for the two famous healers. <br>For this service, the old woman demands an outrageous <br>amount of money that only the truly wealthy can afford. <br>Lene’s arguments are especially persuasive because of the <br>numerous cutthroats who lurk around her home, ready to <br>strike at the slightest sign of trouble.  <br>Lene the Old Mobster<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am the ruthless queen of Bergen’s under -<br>world, and I have no qualms about conducting my shady <br>business. Everyone in the city fears me, and I use my repu-<br>tation to intimidate those foolish enough to turn against me. <br>Agenda: Making money by taking advantage of people’s <br>desperation, taking what they have to offer without really <br>leading them to Gerda and Kay. <br>Information: When the Hunters confront Lene, the old <br>woman will reveal that Gerda and Kay are staying at the <br>small White Hospital, a medical facility that can be reached <br>by sailing north along the river. Lene will give the Hunters <br>a pass that the Black Feathers will recognize as valid for <br>boarding their boat to make the journey.<br>Lene will try hard to hide the fact that she is Gerda’s moth-<br>er, fearing that this information will get her into even more <br>trouble than her daughter’s scheme. When this connection <br>is made and Lene is cornered, she will reveal some infor -<br>mation about her daughter to the Hunters. At this point, <br>the Storyteller can decide what to reveal about Gerda by <br>consulting her profile on page 223.<br>Lene’s Cutthroat<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC <br>(1 Wound - 12 Gang Members)<br>Descriptor: We are ruthless scoundrels and protect our ter-<br>ritory from any intruder.<br>Gift - Neighborhood Gang: A Cutthroat increases their <br>OL by 1 when they act to wound or capture a target they <br>consider an intruder on their territory. <br>End of Scene:  The Hunters decide to meet the Black <br>Feathers. Go to the THIRD SCENE - The Ambush of the <br>Black Feathers. If they decide to meet Flora instead, go to</p><p>SECOND SCENE OPTION A - Flora’s Greenhouse.<br>2b</p><p>209</p>"},"sort":200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513746054,"modifiedTime":1781513746054,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"oqyUxa4W7ju4dsJH","name":"Scene 3","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>A Frozen Reflection - Scene 3</h2><p>THIRD SCENE –  The Ambush <br>of the Black Feathers<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: After a night of prepara-<br>tions, you arrive at the small river port on the eastern side of <br>the city, the sun is rising as the port activities have already <br>begun. You recognize the small, black boat that has been <br>pointed out to you, and as you approach, a young woman <br>with clear skin and long raven hair looks at you with suspi-<br>cious eyes and then nods at you. <br>Place: Bergen’s river port. <br>Time: It dawns as the city awakens to a new day of work. <br>Information: The woman will introduce herself as Kråke <br>and ask the Hunters for a pass. If they took one from Lene, <br>the boatwoman will wave them aboard. If the Hunters are <br>coming on Flora’s instructions, Kråke will instead ask them <br>to pay a fare in exchange for her services. <br>On the ship, the Hunters will notice a second black-haired <br>boatman, Ravn, busy making preparations for departure. <br>Regardless of how they got on board, the Black Feath-<br>ers know the Hunters are unwelcome guests: Lene’s pass <br>is marked, a sign the woman leaves specifically to let the <br>crewmembers know who should meet a bad end along the <br>way because they have not paid enough. If, on the other <br>hand, they were sent by Flora, the Black Feathers know that <br>the witch has been struck by a Shard and should no longer <br>be able to provide this information. Shortly after leaving, <br>the Hunters notice a flock of crows that seems to be follow-<br>ing the boat. Eventually, many birds will rest on the boat, <br>and that is when Ravn and Kråke will start their attack. Af-<br>ter defeating the enemies on the boat, the Hunters will find <br>a map to the White Hospital. <br>Ravn<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a skilled assassin, and my throwing <br>knives can hit a target even in total darkness.    <br>Agenda: Escort those who have paid the correct amount to <br>the White Hospital / Eliminate any potential threat to Gerda <br>and Kay’s business.    <br>Gift - The Raven:  Once per Scene, Ravn can transform <br>into a raven and escape by flying away. If he makes a sur -<br>prise attack, Ravn inflicts 1 Additional Wound.<br>Kråke<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a skilled assassin, and I can corner any <br>opponent with my saber. My swordsmanship is such that I <br>can deflect any weapon. <br>Agenda: Escort those who have paid the correct amount to <br>the White Hospital / Eliminate any potential threat to Gerda <br>and Kay’s business.    <br>Gift - The Rook:  Once per Scene, Kråke can transform <br>into a rook and escape by flying away. If she makes a sur -<br>prise attack, Kråke inflicts 1 Additional Wound. <br>3</p><p>210<br>Threat - Murder of Crows<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: We are a great murder of crows and watch over <br>our beloved human brothers Ravn and Kråke.<br>Gift - The Three Feathers:  The Murder of Crows acts in <br>the service of Kråke and Ravn to protect them and treat them <br>as if they were a Crow. Once per Exchange, both Kråke and <br>Ravn can enjoy one of the following effects:<br>1. Coat of Feathers:  The Murder shields a Black Feather, <br>which increases their OL to Hard 7 against an attack.<br>2. Flight of the Crow:  The Murder lifts the Black Feather <br>off the ground and allows it to run over their feathery bodies. <br>The Black Feather can move anywhere within a thirty-foot <br>radius, and no one can block them. If they make an attack <br>after moving, the Black Feather increases their OL by 1.<br>3. Feather Storm: The Murder encircles a target while it <br>performs an action that is not a physical attack. This effect <br>can be activated when an opponent acts, but it still counts <br>against the limit of one effect per Exchange. The target must <br>pass a Defense Check or lose the action.<br>Epilogue<br>It takes two days of sailing to get to the White Hospital.<br>If a Black Feather is captured, they will not agree to talk, but <br>the Hunters can use magic or other means to force them to <br>reveal the following information:<br> ◆ The mission of the Black Feathers is to take the wealthiest <br>patients to Os, where the famous White Hospital is lo-<br>cated, but even that is a cover-up by Gerda and Kay. The <br>real goal is to get the patients into the hands of a certain <br>Reinsdyr, who will then lead them through the forest to <br>be robbed by a group of bandits.<br> ◆ The Black Feathers do not know how to get to the cas-<br>tle where Gerda and Kay live, but they have heard more <br>than once from the two fraudsters about witches who <br>help them.  <br>Storyteller’s Note: The Hunters’ journey continues in <br>PART TWO - Towards Lady Storm’s Castle. Keep track of the <br>fate of the Black Feathers, for they will be recurring enemies <br>in the next parts. <br>Scenario Events<br>There are 3 Events in this Scenario, though the Storyteller <br>should feel free to create new ones in response to the Hunter’s <br>actions.<br>If the Hunters use violence to stop Aleksander:  his <br>daughter will stand up for him, going so far as to beg the <br>Hunters to spare him. If the situation is not resolved, Fredri-<br>ka will send the Hunters away with less information to end <br>the dinner quickly. <br>If the Hunters try to destroy Flora’s Greenhouse to <br>force her out:  the old witch will use her magic to call for <br>help, causing many townspeople to rush to her defense. <br>If  the  Hunters  inflict  at  least  one  Wound  on  both <br>Black Feathers or corner them: the two will attempt to <br>escape by transforming into a rook and a raven and mingling <br>with the Murder.</p><p>211<br>Part Two – Towards Lady Storm’s <br>Castle<br>Safety keywords: Illness / Identity theft / Medical fraud<br>Note: If the Hunters eliminated one of the Black Feath-<br>ers in the previous Scenario, the other will return to the <br>attack in this Scenario to avenge their fallen comrade. A <br>new Agenda will be applied to the NPC’s profile, replacing <br>the previous one. The Black Feather will always use Murder <br>of Crows as in PART ONE - The Two Healers.<br>Agenda: Eliminate the Hunter responsible for my compan-<br>ion’s death. <br>At the beginning of each Scene, roll 1 die:<br>1-2: The Black Feather does not intervene in the current <br>Scene.<br>3-4: The Black Feather tries to get in the Hunters’ way by <br>acting from a distance, either through the use of the Mur -<br>der or by providing support to the present NPCs.<br>5-6: The Black Feather attacks the Hunters by ambushing <br>them.  <br>Once upon a time…<br>Sailing down the river, the Hunters reach the town of Os, <br>home to the famous White Hospital. The town seems to be <br>a peaceful place to live, and there is no sign of the Frozen <br>Madness.<br>The story that led us here…<br>Gerda and Kay never really stay in Os, but they <br>did leave imposters in their place: Magnus and Iselin, two <br>young upstarts who managed to get married thanks to Ger-<br>da and Kay’s intervention. Vegard, Iselin’s old father, did <br>not approve of the two lovers’ marriage because of some <br>debts that Magnus’ family never paid off. Thanks to a Shard <br>that Kay blasted into the man’s eye, Vegard was transformed <br>from a grumpy breadwinner into a gentle old man who <br>willingly accepted his daughter’s marriage. In exchange for <br>their help, Gerda and Kay have the two newlyweds pose <br>as the famous healers, sending those in need of a cure to <br>Reinsdyr. The thug poses as a guide, but instead, he takes <br>the unfortunate people in a carriage into the forest to be <br>attacked by Rikke’s gang. Magnus and Iselin are not evil, <br>but they agree to deceive people to protect their marriage.</p><p>212<br>The story at the arrival of the Hunters…<br>Magnus and Iselin are in charge of the Hospital’s activi-<br>ties, trying as much as possible to help those most in need. <br>Both have studied to become doctors, but their efforts only <br>contribute to Gerda and Kay’s reputation, giving the two <br>scoundrels an aura of competence far removed from reality. <br>Reinsdyr offers himself as a guide to the rich and needy that <br>the two doctors pass on to him, only to lead them into the <br>thick of the forest and have them attacked by a group of <br>brigands in Gerda and Kay’s service.</p>"},"sort":300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513746054,"modifiedTime":1781513746054,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"XwjL3DAZWXV7sFaI","name":"Scene 1","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>A Frozen Reflection - Scene 1</h2><p>FIRST SCENE –  The arrival at Os<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  You leave the <br>boat in the small port of Os: in front of you you <br>see a quiet little town, very different from the cha-<br>os in which Bergen, hit hard by the Frozen Mad-<br>ness, finds itself. A large sign clearly points in the <br>direction of the famous White Hospital: could it be that the <br>strange disease has really been eradicated from this town by <br>the two famous healers?<br>Place: The White Hospital, an austere and clean medical <br>facility. <br>Time: Early morning as the church bells ring. <br>Initial Situation: The Hunters will have no trouble find-<br>ing the White Hospital and getting an interview with the <br>famous healers. Magnus and Iselin are not expecting a visit <br>from the Hunters of the Order and naively introduce them-<br>selves as Gerda and Kay. Under pressure, they do not hesi-<br>tate to expose the deception of the real Gerda and Kay. The <br>following information can be gleaned from the interview <br>with the two doctors:<br> ◆ Gerda and Kay are two enterprising young people, <br>and it is easy to guess from their behavior that they are <br>accustomed to the shady dealings of the underworld. <br>Kay seems to know about magic, while Gerda shows <br>off magical and powerful objects. <br> ◆ Magnus and Iselin’s job is to refer only the wealthiest <br>patients to Reinsdyr, whose carriage will take them to <br>a mysterious woman a day’s journey from Os. Magnus <br>and Iselin do not know what will happen to the pa-<br>tients. <br> ◆ The village was once protected by a band of nomads <br>who took a liking to the locals and began a fruitful <br>partnership. After Gerda and Kay passed through, <br>young Rikke, who leads the nomads, changed dramati-<br>cally. Now, she and her companions have taken up ban-<br>1</p><p>213<br>ditry. Reinsdyr is the only one who knows the <br>safe ways through the forest, which is why his <br>customers pay him well.<br> ◆ Magnus and Iselin are aware that they are doing some-<br>thing wrong by helping Gerda and Kay, and so they <br>serve the poor and needy without asking for anything <br>in return, trying to atone for their sins. If only Vegard <br>would accept their union, there would be no problem <br>and they would stop deceiving everyone.  <br>When the interview is over, if Iselin has not been coerced <br>or threatened by the Hunters, she will say that she has spent <br>the last few months studying the Frozen Madness and dis-<br>covering its magical origins. If the Hunters wish, she will <br>teach them how to remove the Mirror Shards from those <br>affected. Unfortunately, the process also requires the use of <br>magic, which is why Iselin does not dare perform it on pa-<br>tients herself.<br>End of Scene: The Hunters decide whether to learn from <br>Iselin how to remove the Shard (go to SECOND SCENE <br>OPTION A - A Lesson in Medicine) or approach Reinsdyr <br>instead (go to SECOND SCENE OPTION B - Reinsdyr the <br>Guide.)<br>SECONDA SCENE OPTION <br>A –  A Lesson in Medicine <br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  Iselin leads you into her <br>study and unrolls a scroll of complex magical formulas, <br>saying she found the paper in her father’s great library. The <br>inscriptions reveal that the Mirror of the Other Self is an an-<br>cient and powerful object capable of completely altering the <br>souls of those reflected in it. Iselin noticed an ominous glint <br>in the eyes of those suffering from Frozen Madness, and the <br>symptoms of total behavioral change led her to believe that a <br>Shard from the Mirror might be the cause of the illness.<br>Place: Iselin’s private study.<br>Time: Late morning.    <br>Initial Situation: Iselin will help the Hunters decipher <br>the scrolls, a task that will take all day. At the end of their <br>research, all Hunters who participated will receive the Sce-<br>nario’s Exclusive Gift - Knowledge of the Mirror of the Oth-<br>er Self - without spending any XP to acquire it. <br>Gift - Knowledge of the Mirror of the Other Self:  <br>The Hunter receives 2 Additional Successes when facing <br>the Threat - Shard of the Mirror of the Other Self. <br>End of Scene: Since a whole day has passed and Reinsdyr <br>has moved away from the town, the Hunters can only fol-<br>low his trail. Go to the THIRD SCENE - The Journey.<br>2a</p><p>214</p>"},"sort":100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513746054,"modifiedTime":1781513746054,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"JbWNm0aneMryPW46","name":"Scene 2","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>A Frozen Reflection - Scene 2</h2><p>SECOND SCENE OPTION B <br>–  Reinsdyr the Guide<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: Reinsdyr can be found <br>in the large central square of Os, his reindeer-drawn <br>carriage standing out from the crowd. Reinsdyr is a <br>tall man with a thick dark beard and a reindeer skin <br>cloak that covers him from head to toe. The headdress <br>he wears is also made from a reindeer head, and the <br>large antlers above it make the man look almost monstrous.<br>Place: The central square of Os, filled with caravans and <br>merchants. <br>Time: In the early hours of the morning, baggers and mer-<br>chants are already hard at work in the marketplace.    <br>Initial Situation: Hunters will find Reinsdyr sitting in <br>his carriage, waiting for potential customers: the man has <br>a surly demeanor, but is willing to talk if money is shown. <br>If cornered, he will fight the Hunters to the death, refusing <br>to talk while free. If the Hunters manage to subdue him <br>somehow, Reinsdyr will reveal the following information:<br> ◆ He has an agreement with Gerda and Kay to lead <br>wealthy clients to the home of Pernille, an ice witch. <br>Pernille and her sister Sinikka were banished by Lady <br>Storm for an old betrayal, but the two witches know <br>the only way to the secret castle where Gerda and Kay <br>have taken refuge.<br> ◆ Along the road Reinsdyr travels, a gang of brigands <br>has taken up residence. They are led by Rikke, a young <br>woman afflicted with the Frozen Madness that has <br>turned her into an unscrupulous thief. Rikke’s gang <br>robs Reinsdyr’s passengers of all their possessions and <br>then lets the coach continue on to Pernille’s house. <br>Reinsdyr the Guide<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a very experienced guide and know all <br>the secrets of survival in the north. I can take down any en-<br>emy with ax and pistol without making too much of a fuss.        <br>Agenda: Escort wealthy Frozen Madness victims to Pernille’s <br>house and share the proceeds of the robberies with Rikke.<br>Gift – Die Hard:  Reinsdyr is resilient and a difficult op-<br>ponent even for Hunters. The guide can act twice during <br>an Exchange, using his ax to hit an enemy in melee combat <br>and his gun to hit a target at a distance. When he suffers <br>1 Wound, Reinsdyr can immediately make an additional <br>attack against the one who wounded him.<br>End of Scene:  With or without Reinsdyr, the Hunters <br>must go to Pernille’s house, go to SCENE THREE - The <br>Journey.<br>2b</p><p>215</p>"},"sort":200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513746054,"modifiedTime":1781513746054,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"oqyUxa4W7ju4dsJH","name":"Scene 3","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>A Frozen Reflection - Scene 3</h2><p>THIRD SCENE –  The Journey<br>Note: This Scene can be introduced in a number of ways, <br>depending on what the Hunters have already done.<br>The Hunters learned the cure for the Frozen <br>Madness<br>In this situation, the Hunters missed the meeting with Re-<br>insdyr, the guide has already left with a wealthy client, and <br>the Hunters must travel the road on their own. Here is a list <br>of possible contingencies:<br> ◆ Rikke and her brigands will ambush the Hunters. Al-<br>ternatively, the Hunters may arrive while the brigands <br>have stopped Reinsdyr’s carriage.<br> ◆ The Hunters reach Reinsdyr.<br> ◆ The Hunters choose an alternative route, avoiding both <br>the brigands and Reinsdyr.<br>End of Scene: The Hunters arrive at Pernille’s house, go to</p>"},"sort":300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513746054,"modifiedTime":1781513746054,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"ruR7fHWwL2qjAryJ","name":"Scene 4","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>A Frozen Reflection - Scene 4</h2><p>FOURTH SCENE - The Lapland Woman.<br>The Hunters hired Reinsdyr for the trip<br>The Hunters travel “safely” in Reinsdyr’s carriage. Here is a <br>list of possible contingencies:<br> ◆ Rikke and her brigands will ambush the Hunters.<br> ◆ The Hunters convince or force Reinsdyr to avoid brig-<br>and territory.<br>End of Scene: The Hunters arrive at Pernille’s house, go to</p><p>FOURTH SCENE - The Lapland Woman.<br>The Hunters defeated Reinsdyr in Os.<br>The Hunters travel in Reinsdyr’s carriage. Here is a list of <br>possible contingencies:<br> ◆ Rikke and her brigands will ambush them. The Hunt-<br>ers can try to fool the brigands thanks to Reinsdyr’s <br>carriage.<br> ◆ The Hunters choose an alternative route while avoiding <br>the brigands.<br>End of Scene: The Hunters arrive at Pernille’s house, go to</p><p>FOURTH SCENE - The Lapland Woman.<br>Rikke the Nomad<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a northern nomad and have always tried <br>to lead my companions on the right path. I am used to the <br>hard life of the forest and know how to move and hunt well.<br>Agenda: To make my nomadic family prosperous.    <br>Shard Descriptor: I am a nomad from the north, <br>trying to accumulate as much wealth as possible in order to <br>move to a more hospitable climate. I hate the hard life in these <br>latitudes and to survive I exploit my faithful companions.    <br>Shard Agenda: Gather as much wealth as I can <br>through banditry and then run far away, leaving my entire <br>clan to their fate. <br>Gift - Power of the Shard: The Shard of the Mirror of the <br>Other Self reverses the Descriptor and Agenda of the person <br>it injured. The holder increases their OL by 1 if they act in ac-<br>cordance with the altered part of their Descriptor or Agenda. <br>3</p><p>216<br>Nomads<br>Easy OL 3 - Minor NPC <br>(1 Wound - 12 Nomads)<br>Descriptor: We are nomads from the north and have al-<br>ways lived by hunting and trading what we find.<br>Agenda: We want to live in peace, but our loyalty to Rikke <br>drives us to follow her in her madness. We would like to find <br>a way to cure her and return to our nomadic ways.    <br>Gift - Nomad Clan:  A Nomad increases their OL by 1 <br>when they act to defend Rikke from a threat.</p><p>FOURTH SCENE –  The Lap -<br>land Woman<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: You arrive at a small house <br>in the woods, where the river widens into a small lake. Thick <br>smoke pours out of the chimney on the roof into the icy eve-<br>ning air.    <br>Place: The house of Pernille, known as The Lapland Wom-<br>an.<br>Time: The sun is setting.<br>Initial Situation: The meeting with Pernille can vary de-<br>pending on what the Hunters have done so far. The witch is <br>only loyal to Gerda and Kay because she is being rewarded <br>for her services, and she will not hesitate to betray them if <br>the Hunters corner her. Pernille’s approach to dealing with <br>the Hunters will vary depending on the possible events pre-<br>sented at the end of this Scenario.<br>Pernille The Lapland Woman<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a fearsome ice witch who learned the art <br>of magic from the famous Lady Storm.<br>Agenda: Earn as much as possible without risking my life.<br>Gift - Ice Magic: Pernille can manipulate frost to create <br>ice at a range of sixty feet. When she acts, she can choose <br>one of the following effects:<br>1. Ice Rain: The sharp fragments can hit up to 3 targets, <br>causing 1 Wound.<br>4</p><p>217<br>2. Ice Trap: Up to 3 targets are gripped in ice, preventing <br>them from moving their legs. To break free, it is necessary <br>to pass a Defense Check.<br>3. Ice Golem:  Summon an ice creature under Pernille’s <br>control. <br>Ice Golem<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a mighty creature of pure ice and live only <br>to serve my creator. <br>Information: Pernille is the only one who knows the <br>magic formula that opens the portal located in the small <br>lake, leading to the house of Sinikka, the Finland Wom-<br>an. A Hunter who understands magic can also activate the <br>portal by studying the passage. If both of these options are <br>impractical, Hunters can ask Iselin for help.<br>Threat –  The Magic Lake Portal<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: A magical portal leading close to Lady Storm’s <br>castle. Only those who know the magic formula can plunge <br>into the lake’s waters and pass through.<br>Epilogue<br>Once they plunge into the waters of the lake, the Hunters <br>are transported to the home of Sinikka the Finland Wom-<br>an, a few miles from Lady Storm’s castle. <br>Storyteller’s Note: The Hunters’ journey continues with <br>PART THREE - The Winter Castle. <br>Scenario Events<br>There are 3 Events in this Scenario, though the Storyteller <br>should feel free to create new ones in response to the Hunt-<br>er’s actions.<br>If one of the Black Feathers or Reinsdyr can still <br>act after a fight: they will have anticipated the Hunters <br>and alerted Pernille to the danger. <br>If no one has warned Pernille of the arrival of the <br>Hunters: the witch will act as usual and tell the Hunt-<br>ers that to get to Gerda and Kay’s castle, they must pass <br>through a secret passage that only she knows. However, this <br>passage is very expensive, and Pernille will ask the Hunters <br>for a large sum of money.<br>If Miss Snow and Lady Storm are among the <br>Hunters: Pernille will take refuge in the house and try to <br>intimidate the Hunters into leaving. The old witch is afraid <br>that Lady Storm will punish her for helping Gerda and Kay.</p><p>218<br>Part Three – The Winter Castle<br>Safety keywords: Illness / Identity theft  <br>Once upon a time…<br>The Hunters emerge from the lake and find themselves in <br>front of the house of the Finland Woman. It is a small build-<br>ing, equal to Pernille’s in every way. Turning their gaze to the <br>north, the imposing silhouette of a castle is a dark shadow in <br>the middle of a snowstorm.<br>The story that led us here…<br>Gerda and Kay retired to Lady Storm’s castle to en-<br>joy the fruits of their misdeeds. In a fit of boredom, Gerda <br>began to study in Lady Storm’s library. The young wom-<br>an had always had a flair for magic and found great sat-<br>isfaction in learning the arcane art. Meanwhile, Kay took <br>to the good life, using Lady Storm’s magic sleigh to travel <br>around Europe, wasting a lot of money on revelry. A week <br>ago, however, Gerda attempted a very powerful spell and <br>lost control at the climax of the ritual. The castle’s magic <br>resonated with the power generated by the unwary Gerda, <br>awakening a malevolent consciousness in the structure that <br>took the name Ice Heart. The Ice Heart then unleashed a <br>powerful blizzard, freezing Kay in an ice shrine, while Ger-<br>da was struck by a Shard from the Mirror of the Other Self, <br>the thing that made her deception possible turning against <br>her. The ice reached Sinikka’s house and mercilessly swept <br>everything away.<br>The story at the arrival of the <br>Hunters…<br>The Hunters have arrived at Sinikka’s house, but it will not <br>be easy to find out where they really are and how far they <br>have traveled thanks to the magic of the lake. The Finland <br>Woman’s house is completely covered in a blanket of ice as <br>if a blizzard has swept over everything in its fury. In Lady <br>Storm’s castle, Gerda desperately tries to save Kay: now that <br>her character has been changed by the Shard, the contempt <br>she felt for her partner in mischief has become a strong <br>love. Unable to thwart the will of the castle, Gerda has taken <br>refuge in Lady Storm’s great library in search of a solution.</p><p>219</p>"},"sort":400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513746055,"modifiedTime":1781513746055,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"XwjL3DAZWXV7sFaI","name":"Scene 1","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>A Frozen Reflection - Scene 1</h2><p>FIRST SCENE –  The Finland <br>Woman<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  As Pernille indicated, the <br>magic lake has led you to the home of Sinikka, her coven <br>partner. What puzzles you, however, is the total desolation <br>of the dwelling. Everything is covered in a thick layer of ice <br>as if a very powerful blizzard has been punishing the place <br>for years.    <br>Place: Sinikka’s completely frozen house.<br>Time: The sun rises as if the journey across the magic lake <br>had taken a whole night.<br>Initial Situation: Everything is covered in ice. Upon en-<br>tering the house, the Hunters will see the figure of Sinikka, <br>frozen as she was about to turn the ladle in a pot of soup <br>above the hearth. It is clear that the witch has been taken <br>by surprise. <br>Information: Observing the house, it will be easy to see <br>that the ice covering it is of magical origin. Sinikka may be <br>alive, but melting this ice will require a great deal of effort. If <br>the Hunters succeed in freeing Sinikka, the witch will thank <br>them and explain that a week ago she sensed the activation <br>of powerful magic, summoned by a strong and malevolent <br>presence that seemed to emanate from the castle itself. The <br>witch did not have time to understand what was happening <br>before she was struck by a blizzard. Sinikka is extremely <br>weak and will not follow the Hunters into the castle for any <br>reason. She has no useful information, other than that since <br>Gerda and Kay settled there, only a few people have come <br>from the lake to be cured of the Frozen Madness, and none <br>have ever returned. <br>Threat – Ice Layer<br>OL Hard 7<br>Descriptor: A thick layer of steel-hard ice. <br>End of Scene: The Hunters can head to Lady Storm’s cas-<br>tle, go to SECOND SCENE - Lady Storm’s Castle.</p>"},"sort":100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513746055,"modifiedTime":1781513746055,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"JbWNm0aneMryPW46","name":"Scene 2","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>A Frozen Reflection - Scene 2</h2><p>SECOND SCENE –  Lady Storm’s <br>Castle<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: In front of you is an ancient <br>castle that appears to be made entirely of ice. The large en-<br>trance door is open, and there seems to be no guard at all. As <br>you walk across the bridge, which is also frozen, a shiver runs <br>down your spine, and you know that the cold is not to blame. <br>It may sound crazy, but you feel a gaze directed at you, as if <br>the whole structure has a malevolent will of its own.    <br>Place: Lady Storm’s Castle.<br>Time: Early morning of a clear-sky day. <br>Initial Situation: The castle is open, so it will be easy for <br>the Hunters to enter. Each room is completely covered in <br>ice, and moving around the structure takes time, consider-<br>ing there are over two hundred rooms. <br>Information: Exploration of the castle is handled by <br>Encounter Rooms, each with a different challenge for the <br>Hunters. These places represent the will of the Ice Heart <br>to eliminate unwanted guests. After each Encounter Room, <br>the Hunters will wander through other neutral rooms, <br>where they will find information about Lady Storm, the <br>true owner of the castle. These rooms are important be-<br>cause they provide vital clues as to what kind of heat can <br>scratch the Ice Heart, as explained on page 224.<br>1<br>2</p><p>220<br>Roll or choose what kind of information to give for rooms <br>without an encounter.<br>1: A huge painting depicts the figure of a beautiful woman <br>with skin as icy as snow. Her eyes are ice blue and her hair is <br>light and flowing. The plaque reads, “Lady Storm, Queen of <br>Winter, everything in her is pure frost except her heart. ”<br>2: A completely frozen old book lies open on a lectern. From <br>the few lines that can be made out, it appears to be a treatise <br>on ice magic. Among the many pages, the word “friendship” <br>is underlined. <br>3: An array of gold jewelry and bracelets lies in a completely <br>frozen display case. This is jewelry of the highest value, and <br>each has a small plaque identifying it as a gift of love from a <br>powerful European ruler. <br>4: A large painting covers the entire wall, with a beautiful <br>woman wrapped in ice in the center and a coven of witches at <br>her feet, smiling and offering her gifts in gratitude. <br>5: A huge globe is painted on the vaulted ceiling of the room. <br>Under the ice covering it, routes can be seen that seem to con-<br>nect a castle to various parts of the world. A sleigh is depicted <br>on the lines of travel, and one of the routes is clearly in the <br>shape of a heart.    <br>6: An ice sculpture stands in the center of a large bedroom. <br>The figures of two children are carved in ice, embracing each <br>other in an affectionate gesture of friendship.<br>As soon as the Hunters enter the castle behind them, a wall <br>of ice will fall and the windows will turn to frozen slabs. It <br>will be clear that there is no way out. <br>The following pages contain several Encounter Rooms, and <br>you, as the Storyteller, are free to decide which ones you <br>want to use. After at least two Encounter Rooms, the Hunt-<br>ers will find the Special Room - Library, where Gerda <br>has locked herself up, and through which it will be possible <br>to access the Special Room - Heart of the Castle  and <br>end the spell. To get there, Hunters will have to go through <br>at least one other Encounter Room.   <br>Exploration will follow this order:<br> ◆ At least 2 Encounter Rooms <br> ◆ Special Room - Library<br> ◆ At least 1 more Encounter Room<br> ◆ Special Room - Heart of the Castle<br>A room with information should be inserted between each <br>room.</p><p>221<br>ENCOUNTER ROOM –  Guard Post <br>Descriptor: A large armory with a series of ice statues de-<br>picting soldiers. <br>Information: Walking through the hall will cause the ice <br>statues to activate and move to eliminate intruders. There <br>are 16 statues in total, activated in groups of 4. The activa-<br>tion of the statues is determined by the vibrations caused by <br>the Hunters walking across the icy floor of the hall. <br>Ice Soldier<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a soldier made entirely of ice and I defend <br>Lady Storm’s castle. My priority is to always focus on the tar-<br>gets that make the most noise.<br>ENCOUNTER ROOM –  Col-umns Walk<br>Descriptor: A very long corridor leads into the heart of <br>Lady Storm’s castle. A series of ice pillars divides the corridor, <br>and in them, you can see the silhouettes of trapped people.    <br>Information: The trapped people are mostly treasure <br>seekers, but if you look closely, you can see some of the <br>Bergen nobles. It will be clear to the Hunters that the sick <br>people who made it to the castle are trapped inside the col-<br>umns. The columns are difficult to melt, and the people <br>inside them are dead. Approaching a column without an <br>occupant will activate Threat - Columns of Eternal Sleep.<br> Threat – Columns  of Eternal Sleep<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: A column of magical ice capable of absorbing <br>living things and enveloping them in a deadly frost.<br>Gift - Glacial Embrace: A target that fails a Check when <br>the column tries to absorb them is wrapped in ice and takes <br>1 Wound. During each action, the encased subject can at-<br>tempt to free themselves by making a Position Check, suf-<br>fering 1 Wound if they fail. When they run out of Wounds, <br>the target is completely absorbed by the column. An NPC <br>automatically suffers 1 Wound with each of its actions un-<br>til it has consumed all of its Wounds. At the Storyteller’s <br>discretion, a particularly skilled NPC may choose to free <br>themselves with one of their actions. <br>ENCOUNTER ROOM –  Me-morial Church<br>Descriptor: A large Gothic church made entirely of ice. <br>Small snowflakes fall from the large vault in the ceiling and <br>float gently to the ground.    <br>Information: The snowflakes are imbued with Lady <br>Storm’s power and are capable of erasing the memory of <br>those they touch. If a subject does not find a way to protect <br>themselves from contact, they will suffer the effect of the <br>Threat - Snow of Memory. In the main altar is a large shrine <br>with an object inside: this is a Treasure of the Order, which <br>the Storyteller must choose at will from those presented <br>from page 19. It takes two minutes to sprint through the <br>Church.</p><p>222<br>Threat – Snow of Memory<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: Tiny snowflakes that can freeze a person’s <br>memories forever until they forget everything. <br>Gift - Ice Oblivion:  For each minute a subject is under <br>the snowfall, it is touched by a number of flakes equal to <br>the result of a die roll. The result determines the effect to be <br>applied. If the subject does nothing to protect themselves <br>from the snow, they cannot make a Defense Check against <br>the Threat. The Storyteller must evaluate, based on protec-<br>tive measures and the subject’s clothing, whether they are <br>more exposed to snowflakes (roll 2 dice and choose the <br>higher value) or are more sheltered (roll 2 dice and choose <br>the lower value). <br>1-2: A severe headache accompanies a cherished memory <br>that slowly fades, leaving the target with the perception of <br>an event lost forever. The target loses 2 Soma. An NPC re-<br>duces their OL by 1 for the remainder of the Scenario.<br>3-4: The face of a loved one appears fleetingly in the tar -<br>get’s mind before disappearing, leaving them with the feel-<br>ing of having lost the memory of a loved one. The target <br>loses the use of one of their Descriptors (except the Dark <br>Ego) until the end of the Scenario. An NPC loses their only <br>Descriptor and replaces it with this one: I’ve lost my memo-<br>ry and have no idea where I am. <br>5-6: The target hears a phrase whispered so quietly it is <br>unintelligible, leaving them with the perception that a part <br>of themselves is lost forever. The target loses the use of one <br>Gift for the rest of the Scenario (except Dark Ego). An NPC <br>who has no Gifts to lose reduces their OL by one category. If <br>they already have OL Easy 3, they suffer 1 Wound instead.  <br>ENCOUNTER ROOM –  Troll <br>Workshop<br>Descriptor: A small room with the remains of a large bro-<br>ken mirror. Twelve more mirrors are placed in each corner, <br>creating a striking play of reflections. <br>Information: A Troll stands in the small hall. It is the cre-<br>ator of the Mirror of the Other Self. After the artifact broke, <br>the craftsman went completely insane and now tries to re-<br>produce the original, failing miserably each time. The Troll <br>hates to be interrupted, and any discussion topic other than <br>the re-creation of his beloved mirror will incur his wrath. <br>Over time, the Troll has blinded himself with splinters from <br>the many mirrors he is not satisfied with and, unaware that <br>Lady Storm is no longer in the castle, he continues his mad <br>work.<br>Troll Craftsman<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (4 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a skilled craftsman and have served Lady <br>Storm for decades, creating stunning ice mirrors for her. I can <br>manipulate the reflected images as if they were real.    <br>Agenda: Rebuilding the Mirror of the Other Self for my <br>Lady Storm.    <br>Special Agenda (Prince Trollo the Innocent): I have <br>always wanted an apprentice to pass my art on to, and he <br>seems perfect. Whether he wants to or not.    <br>Gift - The Mirrored Reality:  Although blinded, the <br>Troll can see the world around it through the mirrors scat-<br>tered throughout the room, thanks to the glare of the shards <br>in his eyes. The Troll can act against a target by striking at <br>a reflected image without the target being able to make a <br>Defense Check to avoid it.</p><p>223<br>ENCOUNTER ROOM –  Guest <br>Room<br>Descriptor: A luxurious bedroom. The ice on the walls <br>seems to have no effect on the furnishings, and even the tem-<br>perature seems decidedly milder than in the rest of the castle.    <br>Information: The room is filled with valuables and com-<br>forts. Time flows differently here, which is understandable <br>since the Hunters will feel extremely rested after a few min-<br>utes. If they stay in the room for at least an hour, they will <br>be able to call an Interlude without the Scenario Agendas <br>continuing.<br>SPECIAL ROOM –  Library<br>Descriptor: A vast library carved from the ice, with walls <br>of books stretching as far as the eye can see. A magical seal, <br>pulsing with power, is clearly visible at the library’s entrance. <br>Information: The seal is a protective spell that Gerda <br>cast to prevent the Ice Heart from reaching her. As Hunters <br>wander through the Library, they will hear Gerda mutter -<br>ing as she conducts her research. The young woman has <br>retained the memory of her misdeeds, but now her priority <br>is to save Kay, and she will not hesitate to ask the Hunters <br>for help. Gerda will give them the following information:<br> ◆ The Ice Heart is a core of magical energy that sits atop <br>Lady Storm’s throne. Through her research, Gerda dis-<br>covered that the Heart is a simulacrum of Lady Storm’s <br>consciousness that the castle has assimilated over the <br>years. <br> ◆ In an old diary hidden in the Library, Gerda has read <br>that the only thing Lady Storm fears is heat, which <br>means that the Ice Heart can be defeated if it is exposed <br>to heat. Gerda has already tried this, but even when she <br>brought a flame close to the Heart, nothing happened, <br>so Gerda is racking her brain to find out what kind of <br>heat the diary is referring to.<br> ◆ The Ice Heart has total control of the castle and will <br>not allow anyone to leave. Now even the Hunters are <br>prisoners like her.<br>The warmth referred to in the diary, as can be deduced from <br>the many scenes depicted in the rooms through which the <br>Hunters pass, is that of emotional warmth. However, Ger-<br>da, who is not a good person, is unable to intuit this truth. <br>Gerda the Swindler<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a skilled trickster, my sharp mind matched <br>only by my nerve. While studying Lady Storm’s books, I dis-<br>covered that I can also dabble in magic, and I have no qualms <br>about using it to my own advantage.    <br>Agenda: Living in luxury without working and increasing <br>my power to get my hands on more wealth / Supporting Kay <br>in his whims, because even though I think he is an idiot, I <br>need a trustworthy sidekick who will always do what I say. <br>Shard Descriptor: I am a naive girl who struggles <br>to express her feelings. Thanks to the magic I have learned, I <br>can help others. <br>Shard Agenda: Save my beloved Kay from the sad <br>fate that befell him / Defeat the Ice Heart.<br>Gift - Power of the Shard:  The Shard of the Mirror of <br>the Other Self reverses the Descriptor and Agenda of the <br>person it injured. The holder increases their OL by 1 if they <br>act in accordance with the altered part of their Descriptor <br>or Agenda.</p><p>224<br>Gift - Magician’s Apprentice: Gerda has learned the <br>rudiments of magic and can choose one of the following <br>effects as an action. <br>1. Create 3 ice darts to hit up to 3 different targets. The same <br>subject cannot be the target of more than one dart at a time.<br>2. Create a blizzard that will knock down all subjects with-<br>in a sixty-foot radius of Gerda. <br>3. Manipulate memory by touching the subject’s forehead: <br>Gerda can create a false memory or remove the memory of <br>something that happened during the Scene.  <br>SPECIAL ROOM –  Heart of the <br>Castle<br>Descriptor: Lady Storm’s throne room, where a sphere of <br>pure ice floats. The magic in this place is so powerful that <br>even ordinary people can feel it.    <br>Information: Above the great throne hovers the Ice <br>Heart, which will greet the Hunters by speaking directly <br>to their minds. The Ice Heart will ask the Hunters to turn <br>Gerda over to it so it can punish her for what she did to <br>Lady Storm. If they cooperate, the Ice Heart will be willing <br>to allow the Hunters to leave the castle, delaying their end <br>until it unleashes an eternal frost upon the world. <br>In the center of the room is an ice pillar with Kay inside, <br>trapped in a fleeing position with a terrified expression <br>on his face. To free Gerda’s accomplice, you must face the <br>Threat – Ice Layer (see page 219).<br>The Ice Heart<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (6 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a fragment of pure power and live only <br>to punish all humans guilty of hurting my Lady Storm. I am <br>the castle and within it, all is in my power. I have no human <br>malice and speak my mind without a filter. <br>Agenda: Punish Gerda for what she did to Lady Storm / <br>Punish humanity and freeze it in eternal ice.    <br>Gift - I Am Winter:  The Ice Heart is a manifestation of <br>power and can manipulate anything within the castle. As <br>an action, the Heart can inflict 1Wound from cold on any <br>subject in the castle without the ability to make a Defense <br>Check. The only safe place in the castle is the Library, where <br>the Heart’s power cannot reach because of the seal Gerda <br>created. A sincere expression of love or friendship in the <br>presence of the Ice Heart can immediately shatter and de-<br>stroy it.</p><p>225<br>Scenario Events<br>There are 3 Events in this Scenario, though the Storyteller <br>should feel free to create new ones in response to the Hunt-<br>ers’ actions.<br>If the Hunters succeed in calming the Troll:  the <br>Troll will be able to teach them the Scenario’s Exclusive Gift <br>- Knowledge of the Mirror of the Other Self. <br>If the Hunters remove the Shard from Gerda: now <br>a con artist once more, she will try to escape by using her <br>magic. <br>If the Hunters free Kay:  the scoundrel will try to help <br>Gerda, but only if doing so can help him escape. Otherwise, <br>he will just try to escape to save himself. <br>Epilogue<br>Eliminating the Ice Heart will cause the castle to collapse, <br>while leaving it active will create a threat that the Hunters <br>know they will face in the future. If Miss Snow and Lady <br>Storm were among the Hunters who participated in the <br>playthrough, a choice must be made:<br> ◆ Forgetting the Past: Miss Snow’s personality takes <br>over, forever relegating Lady Storm to the role of sec-<br>ond personality. Her Hunter Sheet remains unchanged, <br>as the memory of what happened is once again erased, <br>and Miss Snow embarks on another search for her past.<br> ◆ Remembering the Past: Lady Storm regains control of <br>her body, but, feeling indebted to Miss Snow, infuses <br>some of her magic to give her life. Her Hunter Sheet is <br>replaced with the following one.</p><p>Miss Snow<br>OL Easy 3 - (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am an apprentice ice mage, although I often cause disasters with <br>my powers. I am naive and always kind to others. <br> <br>Gift – Snow Sorceress Apprentice: Miss Snow can use the Gifts of the <br>Snow Sorceress and Winter’s Kiss, but when she does, she rolls a die, and <br>if she rolls a 4 or higher, a magical disaster (determined by the Storyteller) <br>occurs, complicating the situation.<br>Descriptors and Gifts<br>I am a powerful ice sorceress and can manipulate the weather. I want <br>Snow to learn to be a Hunter, so I limit the use of my powers to solving <br>problems for her. <br>•  Snow Sorceress: Y ou can use magic to create and manipulate the cold. <br>Describe the effects of a spell that has one of the following Keywords as a con-<br>dition: Ice, Snow, or Frost. Y ou could, for example, Create an Ice Bridge <br>to cross a crevasse or Freeze an Enemy to immobilize it. Pay a cost of 1 to 2 <br>Soma, decided by the Storyteller, to activate the spell. The effects you describe <br>last until the end of the Scene. The Soma cost is increased by 1 when environ-<br>mental conditions are not compatible with cold.<br>I am impassive and know how to assert my authority, nothing can <br>shake my heart. I have a weakness for those who show true love or <br>friendship, and it comes naturally to me to help these people, although <br>I do not want anyone to notice this weakness of mine. <br>•  Winter’s Kiss: In you lies the power of winter. When you give someone <br>a chaste kiss, you can choose one of the following effects:<br>1. Erase one of their memories. It must be the memory of an event in the Scene <br>in which you use this effect. Particularly capable Hunters and NPCs may requi-<br>re a Position Check for the effect to succeed.<br>2. Make the subject immune to cold for the rest of the Scene. This will prevent <br>them from suffering Wounds from frost and make them immune to the effects <br>of the Snow Sorceress Gift. <br>3. Make an object extremely fragile. <br>Y ou can spend 1 Soma when you use this Gift to blow a kiss to the target, thus <br>avoiding physical contact.<br>I have a special insight into understanding people and their intentions, <br>and with my magic, I can quickly create help for the weak. I dislike peo-<br>ple who talk too much and social events.  <br>•  Dark Ego - Deus Ex Machina:  When all seems lost, use your magic <br>to make truth triumph. Reduce by 1 the Soma cost of spells you cast with <br>the Gift of the Snow Sorceress when your goal is to help someone. Once per <br>Exchange, you can spend 1 Soma to prevent one of your allies from taking <br>1 Wound by protecting them with a wall of icy frost. Y ou can use the Gift of <br>Winter’s Kiss as a free action once per Exchange.<br>Activator: Step in and show your power to save a good-hearted person from the <br>danger that threatens them.<br>Equipment<br>A brooch in the shape of a sleigh / A small knife with an ice blade that never <br>melts / A scarf handmade by Miss Snow / Books of magic / A mirror fragment <br>with a strange magical aura.<br>Soma<br> 5<br>PX<br>Lady Storm and <br>Miss Snow<br>Iam a powerful witch who rules over winter and frost. Because of a betrayal, I was robbed of my <br>body for a long time and a new personality was created in me: Miss Snow. As much as I hate to admit <br>it, it is thanks to Miss Snow that I have regained my full strength, and I intend to help her find her way. Thanks to my magic, I have given her a body, and now we are like twins: identical in appearance, <br>but profoundly different in character. Snow has agreed to remain in the ranks of the Order, and until she is able to fend for herself, I will watch over her. <br>Special: Miss Snow is an NPC under the complete control of the Storyteller. Lady Storm guards over her on her missions on behalf of the Order.  <br>Wounds <br>1.<br>2.<br>3.<br>Additional <br>Wound.</p>"},"sort":200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513746055,"modifiedTime":1781513746055,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}],"folder":null,"flags":{"broken-tales":{"adventureSlug":"a-frozen-reflection","collection":"Lost Stories","sourceFile":"bt-ls-book-1-ENG-SCREEN.pdf","pages":"201-227"}},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513746055,"modifiedTime":1781513746055,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}
{"_id":"9Bw5aJmcTU4bdEPR","name":"A Mother's Heart","pages":[{"_id":"biQq8xGbFvyMeYc1","name":"Summary","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h1>A Mother's Heart</h1><p><strong>Collection:</strong> Lost Stories</p><p><strong>Source:</strong> bt-ls-book-1-ENG-SCREEN.pdf, pages 97-114.</p><p><img src=\"systems/broken-tales/assets/adventures/maps/a-mothers-heart-p97-full.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto;\" /></p>"},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513738163,"modifiedTime":1781513738163,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"Z3TRHHY7ThtwB4We","name":"Setup","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>A Mother's Heart - Setup</h2><p>96<br>Once upon a time...<br>Murcia, Spain, is a large city full of opportunities but also a chaotic place where it is easy <br>to get lost, with a destiny linked to the great Segura River that divides it in half. Over <br>the years, many children have disappeared without a trace into the city. Meanwhile, <br>discontent festers among the population, in part because of the lack of work for the <br>lower classes. The city is steeped in misery and it seems easy for the ill-intentioned to <br>kidnap children, neglected by adults who spend their day earning the little money they <br>can. However, a letter written by a woman named Maria Rosa has caught the Order’s <br>attention. Apparently, a dark threat hangs over Murcia, and the disappearances may <br>not be the work of ordinary scoundrels. A group of Hunters has been sent to the city, <br>incognito, to meet the author of the letter and unravel the mystery behind Murcia’s <br>disappearances. <br>A Mother’s Heart<br>A Scenario inspired by The Wolf and the Seven Young Goats (Grimm Brothers)<br>Safety keywords: Abduction / Suicide / Environmental disasters / Child abandonment / Child murder</p><p>97<br>The story that led us here...<br>Seven years ago in Murcia, there lived a woman <br>named Blanca who, after the death of her husband Beltran, <br>was left alone to raise her seven children in a small house <br>on the banks of the Segura River. Blanca would leave early <br>in the morning to go to work and would not return until <br>late in the afternoon. Every day, she told her children not <br>to open the door to strangers while she was gone. Blanca <br>was adamant, for Beltran had died precisely because of a <br>stranger he had naively welcomed into the house. Howev-<br>er, one year torrential rains drenched the city and caused <br>the Segura River to overflow its banks. Many tried to warn <br>Blanca’s children by knocking on the door and begging <br>them to come out, but the children did as their mother had <br>told them and stayed hidden in the cellar. The Segura River, <br>with the indifference of nature, flooded every house along <br>its banks. When Blanca returned home, she realized her <br>worst fears were true. Her beloved children had drowned, <br>hidden in the death trap she had told them not to leave. <br>Destroyed by grief, Blanca threw herself into the icy waters <br>of the Segura.<br>Exactly one year after the tragedy, Blanca has been reborn <br>as a ghost and wanders the city in search of her children. <br>Mad and with no memory of what happened, Blanca wants <br>to gather her beloved children to her. Each November, she <br>appears to kidnap seven children, drag them to the cellar of <br>her old house, and drown them. After her first appearances, <br>word spread among the people of Murcia that a ghost was <br>haunting the town, and the legend of Madre Blanca de las <br>Lágrimas (White Mother of Tears) began to grow.<br>The story at the arrival of the <br>Hunters...<br>Neron Lobo is an exorcist priest who serves in an old Mon-<br>astery in the city. Always attentive to the needs of the most <br>vulnerable, Neron is actively involved in helping the many <br>working families who have little or nothing to feed their <br>children. After learning of Mother Blanca’s story, Neron <br>began to investigate and discovered to his dismay that, in <br>the past, seven children had gone missing each year when <br>the heavy rains hit the region in the month of November. <br>The young priest discovered that before disappearing, each <br>of the children had met a woman with a pale face and long <br>black hair, who had given them a loving kiss on the fore-<br>head. Neron became convinced that the spirit that took <br>the children manifested itself to them before taking them. <br>Gathering neighborhood rumors about a woman who fit <br>the ghost’s description, Neron located possible victims and <br>took them to hide in the old Monastery. The priest’s goal is <br>to keep the children safe until the end of the month when <br>the specter would cease to appear. However, his activities <br>aroused the suspicion of some of the locals, who, believing <br>that they were dealing with a gang of kidnappers, asked old <br>Maria Rosa to send a letter to the Order to put an end to <br>the criminal activity. No one knows that of Blanca’s seven <br>children, only one survived: Pepe, the youngest, had tak-<br>en refuge in the case of a large wall clock and was swept <br>away by the current that broke through the windows of the <br>house. Orphaned, Pepe took to the streets and now lives in <br>the Clock Tower of the abandoned San Felipe’s Church with <br>his gang, the Bats. The gang has seven members and serves <br>as Pepe’s attempt to rebuild his lost family.</p><p>98<br>Time Goes By<br>In this Scenario, the passage of time plays an important <br>role. Depending on when the Hunters intervene, they <br>will find a different situation in certain Places. Murcia is a <br>large city full of markets and workers, so moving from one <br>neighborhood to another can take several hours. Each time <br>the Hunters move to a different location, they may face the <br>Threat - City Chaos. Failing the Check means a significant <br>delay and arrival at a location in a later time slot.<br>There are three time slots: Morning, Afternoon, and <br>Evening. The three time slots represent the three periods <br>of the day and are not tied to a specific time. <br>Keep in mind that these rules serve as a guide and shouldn’t <br>hinder the narrative at your table. If the Hunters can find <br>a quick way to move thanks to their Gifts or help from an <br>NPC, they can ignore the obstacles caused by the City <br>Chaos. Similarly, resting to wait for a precise time slot al-<br>lows the Hunters to be present at a location for a specific <br>part of the day. <br>Threat – City Chaos<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: Murcia is a big city, full of narrow streets and <br>always full of busy people. <br>Gift - Time Waste:  By Failing a Check against this <br>Threat, the Hunters fall victim to the city’s confusion and <br>their trip takes longer than planned, so they arrive at a lat-<br>er time slot. A Positive Outcome means the Hunters arrive <br>at their goal destination one time slot after their departure <br>(e.g., leave in the Morning and arrive in the Afternoon). A <br>Failed Check delays the Hunter’s arrival by one time slot, so <br>that their journey takes two periods of the day (e.g., leave <br>in the Morning, arrive in the Evening). Failing the Check, <br>however, allows the Hunters to learn one of the rumors cir-<br>culating in the city. The Storyteller rolls a die or can choose <br>which rumor reaches the Hunters’ ears:<br>1: The Bats are a gang of street urchins who regularly steal <br>from the city’s merchants. The seven brats who make up <br>the gang live in the old Clock Tower, and though many res-<br>idents turn a blind eye to their misdeeds, it seems that some <br>nobles are planning to raid the Tower and put an <br>end to the gang.    <br>2: A new priest has recently arrived in the <br>city, but he does not seem to have taken up his <br>ministry in any of the churches open to the <br>faithful. The stranger is a burly, rude-looking <br>fellow who lives in an old Monastery that no <br>one has used in decades.<br>3: A dark rumor describes a ghost that <br>haunts Murcia during November. Parents <br>must be very careful with their children <br>because the Madre Blanca de las Lágrimas <br>wanders among the living in the guise of a</p><p>1<br>99<br>sad woman searching for her lost children. But beneath her <br>maternal appearance lurks the face of death. <br>4: The Segura River is a great resource for the city, but ev-<br>eryone fears a repeat of the disaster that occurred seven <br>years ago when heavy rains caused the river to overflow, <br>taking the lives of eight innocent people. The deaths includ-<br>ed a young mother named Blanca and her seven children, <br>all of whom drowned in their home.<br>5: Murcia’s slums are home to a disproportionate number <br>of people, but this is normal considering the work that the <br>city has to offer. In the chaos of the streets, it is easy to get <br>lost and almost every day a young person does not return <br>home. What happens to them is unknown, though it’s as-<br>sumed some decided to flee to try their luck elsewhere and <br>others attracted the interest of some criminal gang. <br>6: The Segura Riverbed is busy during the day, but at night <br>everyone is afraid to go near it. It is said that during No-<br>vember, a mother’s cry and children’s laughter can be heard <br>from the dark waters.</p>"},"sort":50000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513738164,"modifiedTime":1781513738164,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"qJQTP3Ws6kAXoxlU","name":"Scene 1","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>A Mother's Heart - Scene 1</h2><p>First Scene<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: Y ou have arrived in the city <br>as the sun is setting. The letter delivered to the Order men-<br>tions the Old Mill Tavern in the slums, so that is where you <br>have decided to begin your inquiries. As soon as you enter, <br>you are greeted by a quiet and comfortable atmosphere. <br>Among the patrons, you see only humble people warming <br>themselves with a bowl of onion soup to ward off the No-<br>vember chill. At the center table of the tavern sits an elderly <br>lady who seems to be waiting for you.<br>Place: The Old Mill Tavern, a small tavern made out of <br>what was once a real mill for grinding grain. <br>Time: The sun has set as the citizens return from a hard <br>day’s work.<br>Initial Situation: The elderly woman introduces herself <br>as Maria Rosa, the letter’s author. In the city, she cares for <br>many families that crowd the slums. Maria Rosa comes <br>from humble beginnings but was fortunate enough to mar-<br>ry a wealthy industrialist who allowed her to live in com-<br>fort. After a walk through the slums of Murcia, Maria Rosa <br>was struck by the plight of the city’s poor and decided to <br>provide comfort to those less fortunate by helping work-<br>ing families. Maria Rosa wrote to the Order because she <br>was concerned about the disappearance of children in re-<br>cent years, which began after the so-called Murcia Tragedy. <br>Maria Rosa will give the Hunters all the information she <br>knows, but she will ask them to leave her out of the inves-<br>tigation. After the interview is over, a room will be booked <br>for the Hunters at the Tavern so they can rest after their <br>trip. If the Hunters agree, they will begin the investigation <br>at dawn the next day and can find their first location before</p><p>100<br>the city wakes up, avoiding the Threat City Chaos and ar -<br>riving in the Morning time slot.<br>Information: Talking to Maria Rosa will provide the fol-<br>lowing information.<br> ◆ Most of Murcia’s population is made up of poor fam-<br>ilies who are constantly looking for work. As a result, <br>many children are neglected and crime thrives. <br> ◆ The Murcia Tragedy took place seven years ago when <br>an entire family was wiped out by the flooding of the <br>Segura. Blanca, a young worker who was the sole pro-<br>vider for her seven children, was at work when the <br>flood swept through her home. Some residents tried <br>to rescue the children, but they refused to go outside, <br>following their mother’s advice not to open the door to <br>strangers for any reason. When Blanca learned of her <br>children’s drowning, she committed suicide by throw-<br>ing herself into the River.<br> ◆ A year after these events, a number of children have <br>disappeared, and most superstitious people immedi-<br>ately point to Blanca’s spirit as the culprit. Maria Rosa, <br>on the other hand, fears that the reason for the disap-<br>pearances is much more mundane and has to do with <br>the poor living conditions in the slums, which drive <br>many young people directly into the hands of criminal <br>gangs. <br> ◆ A strange figure has been seen prowling the large River <br>Market, a commercial area in the low-lying neighbor -<br>hoods where the disappearances have occurred. The <br>suspicious man is very tall and stocky, with a thick <br>beard and pitch-black hair. Due to his sinister appear-<br>ance, no one has ever dared to approach him, but many <br>believe he may be a slave trader in the service of the <br>underworld.<br> ◆ Martyr’s Square, the largest of the lower districts, has <br>also been the site of several disappearances.<br> ◆ As for the underworld, a very aggressive gang is said to <br>reside in the Clock Tower of the old deconsecrated San <br>Felipe’s Church: the Gang of Bats.<br>Only if specifically asked will Maria Rosa tell the Hunters <br>the location of Blanca’s House. The place was abandoned <br>after the tragedy and no one had the courage to live there <br>anymore.<br>The Old Mill Tavern<br>Descriptor: A small tavern in an old mill. Simple food and <br>cheap wine are the main offerings. <br>Morning: There are few patrons, but by spending time <br>chatting, Hunters can learn a rumor (page 98). <br>Afternoon: In the hall, Rufio and Soledad (page 105) are <br>trying to scrape together some change with a music and <br>dance show.    <br>Evening: Alvaro, the old drunkard, tells everyone that <br>he saw a pale, ghostly woman wandering near the Segura <br>Riverbed during the afternoon hours. Alvaro says he fled <br>because when he met the woman’s gaze, his blood froze in <br>his veins with fear. No one seems to believe the old man, <br>but the drunkard stubbornly refuses to return to the place <br>where he saw the spirit, instead giving directions to the Se-<br>gura Riverbed for some change.</p><p>101<br>The River Market<br>Descriptor: The center of commerce for the poor of Murcia <br>is an expanse of tents, carts, and blankets where all kinds of <br>goods are displayed. <br>Morning: Father Neron can easily be seen chatting with <br>some of the children, asking them if they have seen a pale, <br>ghostly woman. After the discussion, he will walk away <br>holding the hands of those who have confirmed that they <br>have seen Blanca.    <br>Afternoon: Market activity is at its peak. By spending <br>time searching for information, Hunters can learn a rumor <br>(page 98).<br>Evening: A couple wanders among the closing stalls, <br>looking for their son who seems to have disappeared. It is <br>one of the boys Father Neron brought to the Monastery. <br>Father Neron Lobo<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am an exorcist priest who fights evil with the <br>power of faith. Because of my rough and wild appearance, I <br>often inspire fear, but I am a gentle and good-hearted person.    <br>Agenda: Save the children of Murcia from the threat of the <br>Madre Blanca de las Lágrimas.    <br>Gift - Exorcist Priest:  Father Neron has the ability to <br>perceive damned souls, which allows him to see and inter-act with all spiritual creatures. He can perform an exorcism <br>and inflict 1 Wound on a target with the word Spirit in its <br>profile. No Defense Check can be made against this attack.</p><p>102<br>Martyr’s Square<br>Descriptor: The largest square in the slums of Murcia. Va-<br>grants and the unemployed crowd here, waiting for the city’s <br>gendarmes to bring scraps of food discarded by the wealthy.    <br>Morning: Amidst the general hustle and bustle of people in <br>need, there are also many children running free without adult <br>supervision. Blanca walks through the crowd, approaches the <br>children, and asks them if they want a mother. To the first one <br>who answers yes, Blanca gives a kiss on the forehead, marking <br>them as the intended victim for the evening. <br>Afternoon: Square activity is at its peak. By spending <br>time searching for information, Hunters can learn a rumor <br>(page 98).<br>Evening: Blanca returns to the square to reunite with the <br>child she branded, taking advantage of the quiet of the eve-<br>ning to take them to the Segura Riverbed.<br>Madre Blanca de las <br>Lágrimas <br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a spirit without peace and I wander the city of Mur-<br>cia in search of my beloved children. My skin is cold and I feel no pain. <br>The lullaby I used to sing to my children is the only thing that gives me <br>a moment of peace. <br>Agenda: I will bring seven children into the water. They will become <br>my children.<br>Gift - Spirit of Tears: Blanca’s body does not follow the laws of life <br>and death, and until her heart is at peace, she cannot be permanent-<br>ly eliminated. When Blanca’s Wounds are all marked, she crumbles <br>to dust and her spirit returns to Blanca’s House, summoned by the <br>Mother’s Heart (page 107). At the beginning of the next Scene, Blan-<br>ca heals all her Wounds. She starts each Scene as Intangible . If she <br>acts to harm a living subject (inflicting 1 Wound, grabbing them, and <br>similar actions), she becomes Tangible for the rest of the Scene. Once <br>per Scene, Blanca can choose to become Intangible again.</p><p>103<br>Intangible: Blanca can move through solid objects and <br>living creatures. When she passes through a living being, <br>she forces the target to make a Defense Check. If the target <br>fails, they will burst into tears for 1 minute and be unable to <br>act. While crying, the target will see one of Blanca’s memo-<br>ries (see Gift - A Mother’s Love).<br>Tangible: Blanca can interact with the physical world like <br>a normal creature. Once per Scene, Blanca can cry and all <br>who hear her cry will suffer the following effect:<br> ◆ Minor NPC: Must run from Blanca as fast as possible <br>until they can no longer hear her cries. If unable to do <br>so, they will faint.<br> ◆ Main NPC/Dark Presence: Reduces their OL by one <br>while in Blanca’s presence. If they already have OL Easy <br>3, they suffer the effect of Minor NPCs.<br> ◆ Hunter: Loses 2 Soma. If they cannot pay this cost, <br>they suffer 1 Wound. <br>Gift - A Mother’s Love: Blanca can only be permanent-<br>ly eliminated by confronting her with her terrible deeds, <br>by awakening the love she feels for her son Pepe, and by <br>making her realize that the young man has created a new <br>family for himself thanks to the Bats. Alternatively, it is <br>necessary to destroy the Mother’s Heart in Blanca’s House.  <br>If Blanca is Intangible and passes through a living being, <br>roll a die or choose which memory is shared:<br>1: Blanca embraces two newborns. They are twins and she <br>looks at them with love. She calls them by their names: Abel <br>and Annita.<br>2: Blanca prepares hot soup and gives a bowl to a child <br>huddled in the cold under a large blanket. She approached <br>him and said softly, “Cristóbal, the soup is ready. ”<br>3: Blanca returns home with a book in her arms. As soon as <br>she opens the door, a little girl hangs around her neck. “Did <br>you get it, Mommy?” she asks impatiently. “Of course, my <br>little Lola. Here is your new book. ” The little girl’s eyes light <br>up as she takes the book. <br>4: Blanca finishes sewing an old shoe while a barefoot child <br>stares at her. “I’m sorry, mama, if I broke the shoe, ” the child <br>says in a soft voice. Blanca smiles and strokes her son’s head, <br>“Don’t worry, Ricardo, everything will be fine. ” <br>5: Blanca teaches a young girl the art of sewing. The young <br>girl tries hard but ends up pricking her finger. She bursts <br>into tears, but Blanca takes her injured finger and kisses it. <br>“Don’t cry, Julia, ” she tells her lovingly. “The pain will pass <br>before you know it, but the knowledge that you felt it will <br>make you stronger. ”<br>6: Blanca is running down the street, holding the hand of <br>a little boy who is jumping up and down, when suddenly <br>the little boy stumbles and falls, injuring his knee. The child <br>bursts into tears, so Blanca kisses him on the forehead and <br>embraces him. “It’s nothing, little Pepe, ” she reassures him.<br>Gift - My Beloved Children:  Once per Scene, Blanca <br>can summon 6 Lost Children (page 105) to appear at her <br>side.</p><p>104<br>The Clock Tower<br>Descriptor: A crumbling tower with a large clock that no <br>longer works. The building is part of the Church of San Felipe, <br>now abandoned and devastated by the Segura flood.<br>Morning: The Gang of Bats is out to steal, leaving only <br>Benedicto and Inez to guard the cave.    <br>Afternoon: The Gang is in the Clock Tower except for Ru-<br>fio and Soledad who are at the Old Mill Tavern.<br>Evening: The entire Gang is present in the den. <br>Pepe<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am the leader of the Bats and responsible for the sur -<br>vival of my companions. I am brave and skilled with knives, and I like <br>to whistle my mother’s lullaby, a happy memory from my childhood.<br>Agenda: Robbing the people of Murcia as revenge for their indiffer -<br>ence to those who have nothing / Taking care of the Bats, whom I con-<br>sider my new family.    <br>Gift - Big Brother:  Pepe will not allow anyone to harm his com-<br>rades. Against a target that threatens a Bat, Pepe inflicts 1 Additional <br>Wound. All Bats increase their OL by 1 when Pepe is present. <br>The Gang of Bats<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are street urchins, used to stealing to survive. <br>With Pepe at our head, we are not afraid of anything.      <br>Agenda: Help Pepe make the Gang prosper / Help Pepe overcome <br>the trauma of his family’s death. <br>Gift - United Gang: Each member of the Gang possesses a trait <br>that is identified by an addition to their Descriptor. <br>Benedicto: I am the oldest in the Gang, and my strength is feared <br>even by adults.<br>Carmina: I am agile, fast, and a good climber. <br>Felix: I am the smallest of the Gang and can squeeze into any hole. <br>Inez: I am the smartest of the Gang and have read many books.</p><p>105<br>Rufio: I am a big talker and know everyone in town. <br>Soledad: I am a good dancer and know how to draw atten-<br>tion to myself. <br>The Segura Riverbed<br>Descriptor: The river that runs through all of Murcia <br>brings many job opportunities to the poor, but also the threat <br>of its murky, deep waters.    <br>Morning: The River is crossed by many boats, and plenty <br>of people work along its riverbed. By spending time talking <br>to the townspeople, Hunters can learn a rumor (page 98). <br>Afternoon: Blanca wanders the Segura River, waiting for <br>nightfall to return to the child she branded at the Martyr’s <br>Plaza. When the spirit is cornered, it throws itself into the <br>waters of the River to disappear. <br>Evening: Staying too long near the water of the River will <br>attract 6 Lost Children. <br>Lost Children<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are restless spirits spawned by Blanca’s <br>madness. We hate living things and try to take them with us <br>to the waters of the Segura River to drown them, just as we <br>were. <br>Agenda: Choose a target and drag it to the Segura River to <br>drown it.    <br>Gift - Suffering Spirit: As an action, a Lost Child will <br>always attempt to snatch a target. In the event of a Defense <br>Check Failure, apply the result based on where the action <br>takes place.<br>Within 100 feet of the Segura River:  The Lost <br>Child jumps into the river, taking the target with it. <br>The Lost Child suffers 1 Wound while the target is in <br>the depths of the River, see Threat - The Segura River <br>on page 106.<br>Anywhere else: The Lost Child envelops the target</p><p>106<br>and turns into river water, suffering 1 Wound. The tar<br>-get gains 3 Drowning Tokens. The Storyteller gains 3 <br>Drowning Tokens, which can be spent each time the <br>Storyteller wishes to apply one of the following effects <br>to the target. The same Lost Child cannot generate <br>more than 3 Drowning Tokens to be spent on a single <br>target.<br>1. Confer 1 Penalty on a Check.<br>2. Automatically drop the target into the Segura <br>River if the action takes place near its banks.<br>3. Force the target to pay 1 Soma to activate one of <br>their Gifts, with the exception of the Dark Ego. <br>Threat - The Segura River<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: Strong currents and icy waters make the Segu-<br>ra River dangerous even for experienced swimmers. <br>The Monastery<br>Descriptor: An old monastery that once housed a group <br>of monks. Now only a few rooms and the large courtyard are <br>usable.<br>Morning: From the Monastery garden comes the cackle <br>of children playing. With them is Sister Esperanza, a nun <br>who helps Father Neron keep the little marked ones safe <br>from Blanca’s sight. There are a total of six children in the <br>Monastery (all reported missing from the River Market). <br>When questioned, Sister Esperanza will not hesitate to <br>stand up for Father Neron. The nun will say that the priest <br>wanders around the Market in the morning, while in the af-<br>ternoon he worries about finding the children’s families to <br>tell them that their little ones are safe under the protection <br>of the Church. Father Neron makes donations to the chil-<br>dren’s families to ensure their cooperation, with the prom-<br>ise of a reunion on the first day of December. <br>Afternoon: Father Neron is present as he prepares dona-<br>tions for the families of the children who live in the Monas-<br>tery. Sister Esperanza takes care of the children.<br>Evening: Father Neron is the small library of the Monas-<br>tery, studying books on exorcism. Sister Esperanza sleeps <br>in the underground rooms with the children.<br>Sister Esperanza<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a young nun who has dedicated her life <br>to helping others. I follow Father Neron in his crusade against <br>evil and am willing to give my life to save the innocent.    <br>Agenda: Helping Father Neron and taking care of the chil-<br>dren in the Monastery.</p><p>107<br>Blanca’s House<br>Descriptor: A destroyed house that still bears the marks of <br>the Segura River’s fury. In the wood of the door and its frame <br>are religious symbols, roughly carved by the inhabitants in a <br>superstitious attempt to keep evil away.    <br>Morning, Afternoon, and Evening: The House is un-<br>occupied, but a search of the interior will reveal the bare <br>footprints of a woman who appears to be descending into <br>the basement, which is impractical as it appears to be com-<br>pletely underwater. Diving in is extremely risky and acti-<br>vates the Dark Water Threat. The layer of water actually <br>hides the Dungeon from prying eyes: once the Threat is <br>overcome, the Dungeon containing the Mother’s Heart can <br>be accessed. <br>Threat - Dark Waters<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: Frigid waters, animated by Blanca’s resent-<br>ment of all living things, form a barrier to keep the Mother’s <br>Heart safe.<br>Gift - The Frigid Embrace of Death:  When a subject <br>plunges into the Dark Waters, they are attacked by the <br>water, which will try to enter their nose and mouth. If the <br>subject fails the Defense Check, they suffer 1 Wound from <br>the cold and lack of oxygen and become stuck in the water, <br>unable to move. A successful Defense Check is required to <br>get free and return to the surface or to descend into the <br>Dungeon. Singing the lullaby that Pepe knows causes the <br>waters to recede for one hour, allowing safe access. <br>The Dungeon<br>Descriptor: A bare dungeon where the remains of six small <br>bodies are huddled together. In the center of the room, a mass <br>of plants, seabed debris, and animal bodies are formed into a <br>heart that pulsates with malevolent energy.<br>Morning, Afternoon, and Evening:  The Mother’s <br>Heart is the fulcrum that gives life to Blanca’s spirit and to <br>destroy it is to put an end to Mother Blanca de las Lágrimas.<br>The Mother’s Heart<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (6 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: An agglomeration of floating garbage, pulsat-<br>ing like a rotting heart. <br>Gift - A Mother’s Fury:  As soon as the Heart suffers <br>1 Wound, Blanca will appear to defend it. The call of the <br>Heart cannot be prevented in any way.</p><p>108<br>Scenario Gifts<br>These Gifts represent special abilities related to the Mother <br>Heart Scenario and can be acquired once conditions are <br>met. A Hunter can only acquire one Scenario Gift. If they <br>buy a new one during an Interlude, they will have to forgo <br>the previous one.<br>Exorcism<br>Requirement: To be taught the rites of exorcism <br>by Father Neron Lobo. <br>Y ou are able to sense damned souls, and this <br>allows you to see and interact with all spiritu-<br>al beings. The Storyteller will alert you when <br>a spirit is present, a feeling that manifests as a <br>chill down your spine. Y ou can spend 1 Soma <br>to open your mind to the spirits. If you do, you <br>can communicate with them and perform ritu-<br>als and prayers to harm them for the rest of the <br>Scene.<br>City Guide<br>Requirement: Succeed at least twice against <br>the Threat - City Chaos.   <br>Y ou have figured out how to navigate the alleys <br>of the chaotic city of Murcia. When you move <br>from one Place to another, you automatically <br>get a Standard Outcome on Threat Checks for <br>City Chaos.</p><p>109<br>Scenario Events<br>In this Scenario, there are six Events. As Storyteller, feel free <br>to create new ones in response to the actions of the Hunt-<br>ers.<br>If Blanca sees Pepe or someone describes the <br>boy to her:  she will recognize her lost son and become <br>obsessed with him, and the spirit’s only goal will be to take <br>Pepe to the basement to kill him.<br>If the Hunters arrive at the Clock Tower on the <br>Morning of the second day:  they will find the gen-<br>darmes capturing Inez and Benedicto. <br>If the Hunters arrive at the Clock Tower after the <br>Afternoon on the second day: the gendarmes have cap-<br>tured Benedicto and Inez. Pepe’s only goal will be to free his <br>comrades, but it will be obvious to the Hunters that the Bats <br>are no match for the city guards. <br>If the Hunters attempt to capture Father Neron:  <br>the priest will try to escape and seek refuge in the Monas-<br>tery. If captured, he will try to use his position to obtain his <br>release. Only when he has no other option will he speak of <br>his doubts about the Madre Blanca de las Lágrimas and the <br>threat she poses to Murcia. <br>If the Hunters confront Blanca in public:  panic will <br>break out in the city and everyone will start talking about <br>the existence of the Madre Blanca de las Lágrimas. From <br>that moment on, the chaos in the city will increase and the <br>Hunters will be slowed by citizens asking for their help. In-<br>crease the OL of the Threat - City Chaos by 1. <br>Whether the Hunters describe Blanca to Pepe or <br>the boy sees the spirit directly:  the young man will <br>fall to his knees in tears, overwhelmed by memories. When <br>he calms down, he will tell of the end of his family and how <br>he was saved. Pepe will teach the Hunters the lullaby he <br>always whistles, telling them that the tune is of great value <br>to Blanca.</p><p>1<br>2a<br>110<br>A Mother’s Heart in Scenes</p><p>FIRST SCENE – The Old Mill <br>Tavern<br>It is the same one you find on page 99. Talking to Ma-<br>ria Rosa will reveal the information provided in that Scene <br>to the Hunters, except for the information about the Bat <br>Gang, the Clock Tower, and the location of Blanca’s House.  <br>Note: Since the Scene Tree does not provide the freedom <br>of action of the normal Scenario, Hunters do not have to <br>face the Threat - City Chaos every time they move from one <br>area to another.  <br>End of Scene: The next morning the Hunters can investi-<br>gate the River Market, go to SECOND SCENE OPTION A <br>- The River Market, or the Martyr’s Square, go to SECOND <br>SCENE OPTION B - Martyr’s Square.</p>"},"sort":100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513738165,"modifiedTime":1781513738165,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"Dyq9DOwJ2I2LkD7H","name":"Scene 2","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>A Mother's Heart - Scene 2</h2><p>SECOND SCENE OPTION A  <br>– The River Market<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  The market in the slums <br>of Murcia is a crossroads of makeshift vendors and hawk-<br>ers who crowd the roadsides trying to attract the attention <br>of passersby. Lost in the crowd is a group of children running <br>barefoot behind the horse of a wealthy nobleman, haughtily <br>passing between the stalls. Chaos reigns, and no one seems <br>to be paying the slightest attention to anything but their own <br>interests. <br>Place: The chaotic River Market that stretches for more <br>than a mile. <br>Time: Early morning, while the people of Murcia are al-<br>ready in full swing. <br>Information: Father Neron can easily be seen talking to <br>some children, asking them if they have seen a pale, ghostly <br>woman. After talking to the children, he will leave, followed <br>by a child. If the Hunters approach, the priest will try to run <br>away and, once caught, will try to use his position as a cleric <br>as a shield. After several hesitations (and at least one suc-<br>cessful Position Check to convince Father Neron of their <br>good intentions), the priest will tell the Hunters what he <br>is doing to save the children of Murcia. Neron will say that <br>one of the little ones at the market told him a strange story. <br>It seems that the leader of the Bats often brags about sur -<br>viving the flood that hit Murcia seven years ago. This date <br>corresponds to the first appearances of the Madre Blanca de <br>las Lágrimas, and Neron wants to question the Bats to see if <br>there is any connection. <br>End of Scene: The Hunters accompany Father Neron to <br>meet the Bats, go to SCENE THREE - The Clock Tower.</p><p>2b<br>111</p><p>SECOND SCENE OPTION B <br>– Martyr’s Square<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  You arrive at the larg-<br>est slum square in Murcia. Ragamuffins and the unemployed <br>huddle together, waiting for the city’s gendarmes to bring <br>some leftover food from the wealthy uptowners. Through the <br>confusion and shouting, you catch a glimpse of a pale woman <br>shuffling slowly through the crowd. Her eyes are swollen with <br>tears, and she has the expression of someone who has seen <br>death up close. A few children pass by, and the somber figure <br>beckons them to her for a moment, a sad smile on her face.<br>Place: The large Martyr’s Square where all the city’s poor <br>flock. <br>Time: Early morning, the sun shines high in the sky but <br>fails to dispel the November chill.<br>Information: If the Hunters simply observe Blanca, she <br>will kiss a child on the forehead and then walk off into the <br>crowd, after which the Hunters will see her vanish as if she <br>were a ghost. On the other hand, if the Hunters approach <br>Blanca, the ghost will attempt to escape, and once cornered, <br>she will use her power to walk through the walls of houses <br>and shake them off her trail. If the Hunters trap her, Blan-<br>ca will summon the Lost Children before disappearing. <br>However the encounter with Blanca is resolved, the Hunt-<br>ers will be approached by the boy Blanca kissed: he is Felix, <br>the youngest of the Gang of    Bats. The little boy will say <br>that Pepe told him to stay away from a strange lady who <br>looks like a ghost, but without realizing it, he ended up <br>right in her presence. Now Felix is very afraid because the <br>lips of the woman who kissed him were as cold as those of <br>a dead person. Felix will gladly accept an offer of help from <br>the Hunters. <br>End of Scene: The Hunters follow Felix to meet Pepe, go <br>to SCENE THREE - The Clock Tower.</p><p>3<br>4<br>112</p>"},"sort":200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513738165,"modifiedTime":1781513738165,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"JDwYGZgvkNwF34DJ","name":"Scene 3","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>A Mother's Heart - Scene 3</h2><p>THIRD SCENE – The Clock <br>Tower<br>This Scene varies depending on who accompanies the <br>Hunters to the Clock Tower.<br>If the Hunters arrive with Father Neron, read <br>aloud to the Hunters: Father Neron leads you to a large, <br>abandoned church and tells you that when the city was <br>founded, this was the main place of worship. Murcia’s steady <br>growth, however, soon relegated the church of San Felipe to a <br>mere Clock Tower. When that stopped working, the mainte-<br>nance expense led the Curia to close the entire building. <br>If the Hunters arrive with Felix, read aloud to the <br>Hunters: Felix leads you to a large abandoned church and <br>tells you that this is the headquarters of the Gang of Bats. <br>Pepe is the undisputed leader of the gang, and it is because <br>of him that everyone can live free from the strict rules of the <br>town’s adults. <br>Place: The Clock Tower of San Felipe’s Church. <br>Time: In the afternoon, clouds have covered the sunshine <br>and there is a whiff of rain. <br>Information: Pepe will treat all visitors badly and scold <br>Felix when he is with them. The young man seems very <br>anxious and is unwilling to trust adults. If the Hunters are <br>aggressive, the Gang of Bats will not hesitate to get physical, <br>while a more diplomatic approach may lead to a brief <br>discussion. At Blanca’s description, Pepe will fall into a crying <br>fit and tell his sad story. The boy will then tell the Hunters that <br>the first year after his family’s death, he returned to his old <br>home, where Blanca’s ghost tried to pull him into the river. <br>Pepe will then reveal the location of Blanca’s house.  <br>If the Hunters can handle the situation without getting <br>physical, Pepe will teach them his mother’s lullaby, <br>saying that when he encountered the ghost of his <br>mother, the song saved him from being captured.  <br>At the end of the Scene, Father Neron (if not present) <br>or Sister Esperanza will arrive to seek help. Blanca has <br>appeared at the Monastery to kidnap the children that <br>Father Neron was trying to protect. Pepe will be terrified <br>to face his mother’s ghost and will ask the Hunters to do it <br>for him. <br>End of Scene: The Hunters rush to the Monastery to res-<br>cue the children from Blanca’s clutches, unaware that it is a <br>trap, go to SCENE FOUR - The Monastery.</p>"},"sort":300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513738165,"modifiedTime":1781513738165,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"CAhyXGLxaDxfEJfm","name":"Scene 4","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>A Mother's Heart - Scene 4</h2><p>FOURTH SCENE – The Monastery<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  As you rush to the gate of <br>the Monastery, you can clearly hear the cries of the children <br>inside. Y ou then rush into the courtyard, and before you are <br>ghostly-faced children trying to drag others away. <br>Place: The abandoned Monastery that houses the children <br>protected by Father Neron. <br>Time: The sun is setting. <br>Information: There are 6 Lost Children trying to take the <br>children from the Monastery. In reality, the ghosts are stall-<br>ing to distract Father Neron and the Hunters while Blanca <br>goes to the Clock Tower to kidnap Pepe. The Lost Children <br>fight to the last. At the end of the battle, Felix arrives, dazed, <br>and tells them that Madre Blanca de las Lágrimas has ap-<br>peared and kidnapped Pepe.</p><p>5<br>113<br>End of Scene: The Hunters must run to Blanca’s House to <br>stop the spirit before it kills Pepe, go to FIFTH SCENE - A <br>Mother’s Heart.</p>"},"sort":400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513738165,"modifiedTime":1781513738165,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"OLXq2LLPE4ABsELC","name":"Scene 5","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>A Mother's Heart - Scene 5</h2><p>FIFTH SCENE – A Mother’s <br>Heart<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: Y ou find the broken door in <br>the small house that was once the safe haven of Pepe’s fam-<br>ily. A faint cry comes from the basement, but it is not easy <br>to get to, as the river water is quickly flowing into the house.<br>Place: Blanca’s House, which floods very quickly.<br>Time: The sun has now set, while a heavy rain has begun <br>to fall on Murcia. <br>Information: To access the Dungeon, it is necessary to <br>go through the basement and face the Dark Water Threat <br>(page 107), unless the Hunters have learned the lullaby <br>from Pepe. In the Dungeon, the Hunters find Pepe kneeling <br>in shock, while Blanca promises that he will soon be reunit-<br>ed with his beloved brothers. The Mother’s Heart throbs <br>rottenly, punctuating the passage of time. <br>End of Scene:  If the Hunters succeed in rescuing Pepe <br>and destroying the Mother’s Heart, they will be able to give <br>peace to Blanca’s damned soul.</p>"},"sort":500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513738166,"modifiedTime":1781513738166,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}],"folder":null,"flags":{"broken-tales":{"adventureSlug":"a-mothers-heart","collection":"Lost Stories","sourceFile":"bt-ls-book-1-ENG-SCREEN.pdf","pages":"97-114"}},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513738166,"modifiedTime":1781513738166,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}
{"_id":"CgQnxqfbq2x5GOBM","name":"Isolde the Singer of Lost Love","pages":[{"_id":"v6OZhgDoIjLDeOYz","name":"Summary","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h1>Isolde the Singer of Lost Love</h1><p><strong>Collection:</strong> Lost Stories</p><p><strong>Source:</strong> bt-ls-book-1-ENG-SCREEN.pdf, pages 169-174.</p><p><img src=\"systems/broken-tales/assets/adventures/maps/isolde-the-singer-of-lost-love-p169-full.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto;\" /></p>"},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513742280,"modifiedTime":1781513742280,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"3UVybz0Xo2vu6nEy","name":"Scenario Text","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>Isolde the Singer of Lost Love - Scenario Text</h2><p>168<br>Isolde the Singer of <br>Lost Love<br>A Special Scenario inspired by Tristan and Isolde<br>Once upon a time...<br>The restless spirit of a young woman killed by injustice reclaims her lost love. Reborn as an emissary of the One Who Plots <br>in the Shadows, Isolde, the Singer of Lost Love, stalks the Hunters of the Order, convinced that it was the Order itself that <br>helped her rival in love plot the deception that led to the death of her beloved Tristan. But even the One Who Plots in the <br>Shadows has forgotten that the power of love can work true miracles and that one of his most trusted agents can become the <br>greatest threat.  <br>Safety keywords: Persecution / Depression / Possession</p><p>169<br>How to use Isolde <br>the Singer of Lost <br>Love<br>Isolde the Singer of Lost Love is a special Scenario <br>that can be used during the course of a Campaign. Once <br>introduced into the game, Isolde will become a recurring <br>NPC in Encounters during the Hunter’s travels, holding <br>a growing grudge against them. Isolde begins the game <br>as an agent of the One Who Plots in the Shadows, but <br>she can become a loyal Ally Dark Presence if the Hunters <br>show her that they value love.<br>Isolde may be introduced into the Campaign as an addi-<br>tion to an Encounter (page 253 of the Core Book) during <br>Hunter journeys. Alternatively, Isolde can appear during <br>an Encounter in Rome (page 60 of this book). Isolde <br>will never appear during Scenarios. <br>Isolde the Singer of <br>Lost Love <br>(Dark Presence Opponent)<br>Once upon a time, there was a couple united by an impossi-<br>ble love. His name was Tristan, and he was a distinguished <br>knight. Her name was Isolde, and she was the daughter of an <br>important Welsh nobleman. They first met by chance when <br>Isolde was tending to the wounds Tristan had received from <br>killing a terrible monster. An overwhelming bond of love <br>formed between them, even though they were both already <br>married. For many years there were secret meetings to con-<br>summate a forbidden love, increasingly tested by the suspi-<br>cions of their respective spouses. Finally, Tristan’s wife discov-<br>ered the betrayal. Furious and humiliated, the wife arranged <br>a diplomatic voyage to the kingdom where Isolde resided, <br>knowing Tristan would be excited to accompany her. The ship <br>fell into a planned ambush. Tristan fought bravely but even-<br>tually perished under the blades of the enemy. Isolde waited a <br>long time for her beloved’s arrival. When the messengers sent <br>in search of the ship returned, the young lover learned the <br>sad truth and fell into a deep depression. She stopped smiling, <br>stopped eating, and finally stopped breathing. As she fell into <br>her death sleep, she dreamed of her beloved Tristan... When <br>she opened her eyes again, the world had changed: she could <br>go anywhere she wanted and bend people to her will. She had <br>been reborn as a wraith, thanks to the power of the One Who <br>Plots in the Shadows. Her savior gave her the chance to take <br>revenge on Tristan’s wife, and Isolde didn’t hesitate, stalking <br>her until she went mad.</p><p>170<br>OL Medium 5 - (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am an invisible spirit born of death and love, <br>and I watch the Hunters to judge them. When I manifest my <br>power, my body becomes tangible.<br>Agenda: Spy on Hunters and report their weaknesses to the <br>One Who Plots in the Shadows / Test Hunters to understand <br>their relationship with love.<br>Gift - Immortal Soul:  Isolde is an intangible, invis-<br>ible presence that cannot be seen or harmed in any way. <br>Once per Scene, Isolde can possess an NPC by completely <br>controlling them. The possession is nearly undetectable, <br>though there is an unconscious “attitude” that Isolde adopts <br>regardless of who she is possessing. If the possessed NPC <br>suffers 1 Wound, Isolde is ejected from their body and <br>leaves the Scene. Note: For tips and advice on managing <br>this Gift, see page 171.<br>Gift - Punish Those Who Despise Love:  When the <br>rage against the Hunters reaches its peak, Isolde takes hu-<br>man form, loses her damage immunity, and lashes out at <br>the guilty. When this Gift is activated, Tristan, the Knight <br>who Conquers Death for Love, rises from the ground, <br>ready to assist Isolde. Isolde gains 2 Betrayed Love Tokens, <br>which she can add to those she has accumulated from pre-<br>vious Encounters. After acting in the Exchange, Isolde can <br>spend 1 or more Betrayed Love Tokens as an extra action <br>to activate the following effects, each of which can only be <br>triggered once during the same Exchange. <br>1. Blades for Traitors: A blade of light appears to strike <br>a target within thirty feet. Avoiding the attack requires a <br>Defense Check against OL Hard 7 to avoid 1 Wound. <br>2. Exile for the Hater:  Chains of light emerge from the <br>ground to immobilize a target, who can make a Defense <br>Check against OL Hard 7 to avoid them. A blocked target <br>cannot act and must use their entire Exchange action to <br>free themselves from the chains.<br>3. Freedom for the Lover: Isolde and Tristan disappear <br>and reappear at a maximum distance of thirty feet from <br>where they were. No one can stop this movement.</p><p>171<br>Tristan, the Knight who <br>Conquers Death for Love<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a knight devoted to my beloved Isolde <br>and have returned from the dead to protect her. <br>Agenda: Defend Isolde from those who would harm her.<br>Gift - Immortal Love: Tristan is immune to all Wounds <br>as long as Isolde has at least 1 Wound. The only way to <br>eliminate the Knight is to reduce Isolde to 0 Wounds, caus-<br>ing Tristan’s immediate destruction. When Tristan attacks <br>a target that has wounded Isolde, he increases his OL by 1 <br>and inflicts 2 Wounds. <br>•<br>How to handle Isolde the Singer of <br>Lost Love<br>When Isolde enters the Scene, the Storyteller decides or <br>rolls a die to see which NPC she possesses. Using this ad-<br>vantage, Isolde will deliberately try to create problems, us-<br>ing any hurt feelings caused by the actions of the NPCs or <br>Hunters involved in the Encounter. At the end of the En-<br>counter, Isolde will evaluate how the Hunters acted based <br>on two parameters:<br> ◆ If the Hunters take feelings into consideration and help <br>those in need even at the expense of their personal <br>goals, Isolde will not report them to the One Who Plots <br>in the Shadows. <br> ◆ If the Hunters did not care about the feelings of oth-<br>ers, Isolde will punish them by reporting information <br>about them to The One Who Plots in the Shadows, <br>which the Storyteller can use in the final confrontation <br>of the Campaign or to better prepare a future Assassin <br>(page 249 of the Broken Tales Core Book). Isolde re-<br>ceives Betrayed Love Tokens equal to half the number <br>of Hunters directly involved (rounded down). She can <br>use the Tokens in the confrontation with the Hunters <br>when she activates the Gift - Punish Those Who De-<br>spise Love. <br>Hunters can recognize Isolde’s presence by certain details <br>that the spirit includes when she possesses an NPC or ap-<br>pears as herself. She should have a certain way of speaking <br>or an attitude that will be characteristic of any possessed <br>NPC, regardless of their background or social status. When <br>the Hunters ask questions about the strange behavior, Isol-<br>de will either play dumb or try to shift the focus to the <br>problems she is creating for the Hunters to solve. <br>If the Hunters decide to corner the NPC because they real-<br>ize something is wrong, Isolde will appear suddenly to acti-<br>vate her Gift - Punish Those Who Despise Love. <br>Note: Introducing Isolde during an Encounter may require <br>a small amount of planning on the part of the Storyteller; <br>we have included a series of tables that can provide useful <br>hooks for Isolde’s management.</p><p>172<br>Who is possessed<br>1-2: An NPC not directly involved in the Encounter.<br>3-4: One of the Main NPCs involved in the Encounter.<br>5: A passing Dark Presence where the Encounter takes place. <br>6: An Agent of the Order (see page 59) present where the Encounter takes place.<br>How she tries to test the Hunters <br>1: Shows the Hunters the love felt by one of the NPCs in the Encounter.<br>2: Puts an innocent NPC at risk.<br>3: Helps an NPC express their feelings.<br>4: Highlights an injustice in front of everyone. <br>5: Reveals to everyone who the Hunters are.<br>6: Introduces a tense situation, for example, something about a Hunter’s past. <br>Attitude she repeats for every possession<br>1: Very low tone of voice and always speaks gently. <br>2: When she hears the word Love, she cannot hold back a tear.<br>3: When she talks about feelings she always puts her hand over her heart. <br>4: When she makes a request, she always ends her sentence with, “Please, in the name of <br>l o v e .”<br>5: She always carries a heart-shaped pendant, a gift from her beloved Tristan. <br>6: She speaks with a distinct Welsh accent.<br>Note: The attitudes in the list are in descending order of difficulty for Hunters. <br>Numbers 1 and 2 are attitudes that Players may not pick up on within a few <br>Encounters. Attitudes 3 and 4 are easy to identify but only occur in certain <br>situations. Attitudes 5 and 6 are highlighted by the Storyteller when the <br>Hunters talk to or observe the NPC in front of them.</p><p>173<br>Isolde the Spirit of Love<br>(Dark Presence Ally)<br>A spirit that fights for love, ready to punish those who trample <br>on the feelings of the innocent. <br>OL Medium 5 - (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am an invisible spirit who watches and judges <br>those who do not respect love. I can take control of ordinary <br>people by entering their bodies and using them to interact with <br>the world.                          <br>Agenda: To help all those who believe in love. <br>Gift - Possession: Once per Session, Isolde can take con-<br>trol of an NPC’s body to interact with the material world. <br>Isolde maintains a recurring behavior with each possession, <br>as explained on page 172. Isolde does not learn what her <br>victim knows. Upon awakening, the victim will be aware of <br>having been controlled by a spirit entity, but will not be able <br>to describe the experience. The possession ends when the <br>NPC suffers 1 Wound or at the end of the Scene following <br>the one in which this Gift was activated. <br>Gift - Love Triumphs:  At the beginning of the Scenar -<br>io, Isolde receives 3 Poltergeist Tokens, which she can use to <br>intervene in the material world and manipulate objects. A <br>Hunter may request Isolde’s help to manipulate an object or <br>to gain 1 Additional Success during a Check. The Storytell-<br>er evaluates the Hunter’s objective, and if it is in accordance <br>with Isolde’s Agenda, help is granted. If a Hunter’s actions <br>are in blatant conflict with Isolde’s Agenda, the spirit uses 1 <br>Poltergeist Token to get in the Hunter’s way by moving an <br>object or giving the Hunter 1 Penalty. Once per Scene, if the <br>Hunter’s actions help an NPC manifest or protect their feel-<br>ings, Isolde gains 1 Poltergeist Token.<br>Isolde the Singer of Lost Love in a <br>Broken Tales Campaign<br>By her very nature, Isolde, the Singer of Lost Love, is an ex-<br>cellent addition to a Broken Tales Campaign, as she brings a <br>great deal of variety to make the Encounters and non-Sce-<br>nario phases more interesting. Isolde is an emissary of the <br>One Who Plots in the Shadows, but if the Hunters can con-<br>vince her of their good intentions, she will become Isolde the <br>Spirit of Love, an allied Dark Presence, and will be able to aid <br>the Hunters in their endeavors.</p>"},"sort":100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513742280,"modifiedTime":1781513742280,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}],"folder":null,"flags":{"broken-tales":{"adventureSlug":"isolde-the-singer-of-lost-love","collection":"Lost Stories","sourceFile":"bt-ls-book-1-ENG-SCREEN.pdf","pages":"169-174"}},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513742280,"modifiedTime":1781513742280,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}
{"_id":"X7cKdbuHCbC1VjWc","name":"Nemesis","pages":[{"_id":"r6u31Qrwh7Qxm3Pz","name":"Summary","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h1>Nemesis</h1><p><strong>Collection:</strong> Lost Stories</p><p><strong>Source:</strong> bt-ls-book-1-ENG-SCREEN.pdf, pages 72-96.</p><p><img src=\"systems/broken-tales/assets/adventures/maps/nemesis-p72-full.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto;\" /></p>"},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513737045,"modifiedTime":1781513737045,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"oOdWZh6Nk0yvgN9d","name":"Scenario Text","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>Nemesis - Scenario Text</h2><p>NEMESI<br>71<br>Once upon a time...<br>Once upon a time, there was a mad writer who created his <br>own reality to escape a world that could not understand him. <br>In his strange creation, good and evil had swapped places: <br>villains were heroes, and heroes indulged in the worst sort of <br>wickedness.<br>The One Who Plots in the Shadows, as the writer called <br>himself, weaved the threads of all the characters’ destinies, <br>creating stories that were dark and bloody, but where justice <br>ultimately triumphed. But in the process, his own hands were <br>left dripping with blood.<br>As the years passed, the new world was filled with life, pop-<br>ulating itself with dark and bizarre characters created by the <br>twisted mind of the One Who Plots in the Shadows.<br>Then it happened: the villains he had given a chance at re-<br>demption joined the Order, an organized group serving man-<br>kind. Investigation after investigation they sought to unravel <br>the great deception, to reveal the identity of the One Who <br>Plots in the Shadows himself.<br>And, after the abandonment of childhood, after the rejection <br>and mockery of adulthood, a new emotion found its <br>way into the heart of the One Who Plots in the Shadows: <br>disappointment that his children didn’t recognize all he <br>had done for them.<br>Once again, he had dedicated his life to someone, and once <br>again, he had been repaid with betrayal. First, the readers <br>who mocked his stories, and now the Hunters who had be-<br>come evil in his vision of the world.<br>Desperate and in pain, the One Who Plots in the Shadows <br>wept inky tears that stained his hands until they turned black <br>as night.<br>And at the height of his despair, he realized what he had to <br>do. <br>If no one would be on his side, if no one could understand <br>him, he would create his own companions: a group of loyal <br>allies united by the same disappointment that had broken <br>his heart. <br>Each would be a Nemesis for the Hunters, extensions of his <br>work so that the whole world would remain locked forever in <br>his perverted vision. <br>In the emptiness of his vast mansion, by the light of a few <br>faint candles, the One Who Plots in the Shadows laughed out <br>loud as he had not in a long time. All he had to do was what <br>he was born to do: create stories, create characters, create <br>someone who could understand him.<br>And as he laughed, he began to write, and the more the <br>words took shape, the more each Nemesis formed from the <br>ink-stained pages.<br>And as he wrote, tears began to fall. <br>Bitter, cold tears. Tears of loneliness.<br>Nemesis</p><p>72<br>The Nemeses<br>Nemeses are a new category of NPC that can be <br>introduced in the Broken Tales Campaign or in a single <br>Scenario to increase its difficulty. Nemeses are special <br>Dark Presences, always linked to the One Who Plots in <br>the Shadows, ready to unfold his mad plans to control <br>Broken Europe.<br>The Nemeses will add depth to the world of Broken Tales, <br>introducing a group of recurring enemies that will creep <br>into the Hunters’ stories. Unified by their hatred for the <br>Hunters of the Order, a Nemesis is also a good way to <br>continue a Broken Tales Campaign after the confronta-<br>tion with the One Who Plots in the Shadows, as they are <br>extremely powerful NPCs and have all the makings of the <br>Hunters’ new “epic enemies. ” <br>Nemesis creation follows the pattern of Dark Presences <br>but with some significant differences.  <br>Step 1 Bring the character to their Breaking <br>Point<br>Nemeses follows the method for creating Dark Presenc-<br>es presented on page 42 of the Broken Tales Core Book, <br>the only difference being the Nemesis’ motive for acting <br>against the Order. In breaking their story, we must con-<br>sider how to include an event that deeply disappointed the <br>Nemesis and caused them to hate the world and every-<br>thing the Hunters protect.<br>The five Nemeses presented in this chapter are good ex-<br>amples of what we mean.<br>Step 2 Assign the characteristics<br>All Nemeses have a Descriptor that outlines their primary <br>abilities, which should be on par with Dark Presences. Since <br>these are characters created with the specific intention of be-<br>ing champions of the One Who Plots in the Shadows, the <br>composition of the Descriptor can be very powerful and <br>more effective than that of normal NPCs.<br>A Nemesis must have a minimum of 4 Wounds and a max-<br>imum of 6. On average, 5 Wounds is best to give the Neme-<br>sis the proper narrative resilience to the actions of an entire <br>group of Hunters. <br>The Opposition Level of a Nemesis is always Medium 5.  It <br>should be noted that thanks to the Nemesis Gift (common to <br>all Nemeses), the Opposition Level against the Hunter whom <br>the Nemesis has marked as a sworn enemy increases to Hard <br>7. This dynamic is important to encourage teamwork among <br>the Hunters, as it makes it easier for that Hunter’s compan-<br>ions to succeed in Checks against the Nemesis.</p><p>73<br>Step 3 Create the Gifts<br>Each Nemesis possesses three Gifts:<br> ◆ The first Gift represents their abilities, powers, or special <br>talents. Follow the Core Book rules for this Gift.<br> ◆ The second Gift is always called “Nemesis, ” and is the <br>same for all Nemeses. This Gift confers a number of spe-<br>cial powers that the Nemesis can use as an NPC of great <br>power and ability.<br> ◆ The third Gift is always the “Investiture” , a powerful spe-<br>cial item given to the Nemesis by the One Who Plots in <br>the Shadows to fight the Hunters.<br>Gift - Nemesis: When the Nemesis enters the game, they <br>choose a Hunter as their sworn enemy. Against them, the <br>Nemesis is always considered OL Hard 7. The Nemesis has 3 <br>Nemesis Tokens, which can be spent during the Scenario to <br>activate one of the following effects. Each effect can only be <br>used once per Scenario. These Tokens do not regenerate at <br>any point. <br>1. Reinforcements: New Nemesis Minions will appear in <br>the Scene, overcoming any obstacle. 2 Minions per Hunter <br>will appear in the Scene.<br>2. Hostage: The Nemesis reveals that they are holding hos-<br>tage an NPC that the Hunters encountered during the cur -<br>rent Scenario or a past Scenario. The NPC is being held cap-<br>tive by some of the Nemesis’ Minions at one of the Places in <br>the current Scenario.    <br>3. Sacrifice: When a Hunter targets the Nemesis with one <br>of their Gifts, a Minion makes an extreme gesture to save <br>their master or mistress’s life. Eliminate the NPC to nullify <br>the effect of the Gift.<br>4. Trap: The Scene changes drastically because of a trap set <br>by the Nemesis. “The floor collapses, ” “ A flood comes, ” or <br>“The room is hit by a toxic cloud that spreads through the <br>air” are all good examples of traps. The Hunters involved <br>must make a Defense Check against the Nemesis’ OL to <br>avoid falling into the trap. In addition to being in a new zone <br>with different narrative conditions, each Hunter who fails the <br>Check suffers 1 Penalty on their next action. After the trap is <br>triggered, the Exchange is interrupted and a new one begins, <br>with the Nemesis faction taking the first action. <br>5. Concealed Truth:  The Nemesis knows some informa-<br>tion that is crucial to the Scenario or very important to one of <br>the Hunters, and will try to use it as a bargaining chip to gain <br>an escape route or safe passage.<br>6. You Won the Battle, not the War: The Nemesis leaves <br>the Scene immediately. No one can prevent this escape, and <br>it will be up to the Storyteller to stage it. Even if the Hunters <br>see the Nemesis die before their eyes, they will find a way to <br>escape. <br>Gift - Investiture:  This Gift represents a powerful magi-<br>cal object that the Nemesis receives from the One Who Plots <br>in the Shadows. The object is not a Treasure of the Order, <br>nor does it need to be inspired by an object from a fairytale. <br>Instead, it must represent an important characteristic of the <br>Nemesis. All items tied to an Investiture Gift lose their power <br>when the Nemesis is defeated: when the Nemesis is no longer <br>a threat to the Hunters, the meaning of the investiture is lost, <br>and so is the power that animates the object.</p><p>DELUSION<br>74<br>Step 4 Agenda<br>Each Nemesis must have 4 Agendas, one for each possible <br>story phase in which they act. As with the common Agen-<br>das, these are a general indication of the Nemesis’ goals and <br>must be updated based on the Hunters’ actions during the <br>Scenarios. <br>The Agendas for the five Nemeses presented in this guide <br>can be used as guidelines for creating Agendas for other <br>Nemeses.<br>The first Agenda represents why the Nemesis <br>is interested in the Hunters<br>This is the initial Agenda of the Nemesis and is the most <br>“passive” , meaning that it represents what the Nemesis does <br>in Broken Europe when they are unaware of the Hunters’ <br>actions. This Agenda establishes the focus of the Nemesis <br>and what triggers their interest in the Hunters. The first <br>Agenda is the main way to determine when the Nemesis <br>comes into play.<br>Example: <br>The first Agenda of the Relentless Beastslayer is: “Track down <br>and eliminate any monster that threatens humanity. ” This <br>Agenda can trigger in any Scenario where monsters are pres-<br>ent (including Hunters with monstrous traits!) and pique the <br>interest of the Relentless Beastslayer, which will intervene to <br>investigate and stop anything that he perceives as monstrous.<br>The use of this Agenda can be direct, with the Nemesis ap-<br>pearing during the adventure to oppose the Hunters (or even <br>temporarily help them if it makes sense to accomplish the <br>Nemesis’ goals). The use of the Agenda can also be indirect, <br>with the Nemesis appearing earlier or later to influence loca-<br>tions and NPCs, or to gather information about the Hunters’ <br>actions. <br>The goal of the first Agenda is to introduce the Nemesis into <br>the Scenario and show what makes them unique.<br>The second Agenda represents how the <br>Nemesis helps the One Who Plots in the <br>Shadows<br>This Agenda characterizes how the Nemesis operates be-<br>hind the scenes and how they use their resources to help <br>the One Who Plots in the Shadows. This Agenda is respon-<br>sible for leaving traces of the Nemesis in the game world <br>and introducing related resources and NPCs that can pro-<br>vide important information to the Hunters.<br>Example: <br>One of the two items in the Wise Fairy’s second Agenda is <br>to “Donate power at a dear price, always reminding us <br>that good for its own sake does not exist. ” This Agenda can <br>be implemented through NPCs connected to the Wise Fairy, <br>who become more skilled and dangerous by receiving power <br>from her. However, they will forever after be tied to the Fairy <br>and may be forced to do her bidding.<br>The use of this Agenda can be direct, with the Nemesis sup-<br>porting other NPCs against the Hunters, or indirect, with <br>the Nemesis approaching NPCs defeated by the Hunters <br>after a Scenario to bring them into the ranks of their Min-<br>ions. <br>The goal of the second Agenda is to leave traces of the Nem-<br>esis in Broken Europe for the Hunters to stumble upon and <br>see the effects of their machinations.</p><p>75<br>The third Agenda represents how the <br>Nemesis fights against the Hunters<br>This Agenda characterizes the overt actions of the Nemesis <br>and outlines how they fight and confront the Hunters. This <br>Agenda is meant to guide their actions in the Scene as they <br>confront the Hunters.<br>Example: <br>The two items in the third Agenda of the King of Crime are: <br>“Use my resources and Minions to attack the Hunters <br>without exposing myself on the front lines / Use deception <br>and blackmail to corner the Hunters. ” These items outline <br>a talent for manipulation, which the Nemesis can use when <br>attempting to turn the Hunters against each other through <br>deception and social power. <br>This Agenda is always direct, meaning it requires the pres-<br>ence of the Nemesis in the Scenario or during Encounters <br>and Events. <br>The goal of the third Agenda is to provide the Storytell-<br>er with good guidance for pitting the Nemesis against the <br>Hunters.   <br>The fourth Agenda represents the goal of <br>the Nemesis after the One Who Plots in the <br>Shadows falls<br>This Agenda sets out a long-term goal that the Nemesis will <br>seek to achieve as they replace the One Who Plots in the <br>Shadows, while trying to remain true to his vision: to create <br>dark stories featuring the many characters created over the <br>years by the mad writer. Once he’s out of business, the Nem-<br>esis will attempt to turn the tables by involving the Hunters <br>and Dark Presences scattered throughout the world.<br>Example: <br>The two items in the fourth Agenda of the Valiant Princess <br>are to: “Unite the weak and marginalized to create a net-<br>work to help others / Accumulate wealth to gain power in <br>society and impose more just laws and rules, disrupting <br>secret societies like the Order. ” The items in this Agenda <br>define a long-term goal of the Valiant Princess, who deeply <br>hates those who are able to decide the fate of others due to <br>their privileged status and will seek to fight everything she <br>deems wrong. The Order included.<br>This Agenda acts first in an indirect way, as a driving force <br>behind the events that will involve the Hunters, and only <br>later in a direct way, as the Nemesis lashes out at their ene-<br>mies to achieve their goal. <br>The purpose of the fourth Agenda is to introduce a new <br>main plot that will continue the Hunters’ adventure after <br>the final confrontation with the One Who Plots in the <br>Shadows.</p><p>77<br>Step 5 Minions<br>Each Nemesis may have Minions, which are related NPCs <br>who help the Nemesis fulfill their Agenda. Minions must be <br>created using the rules for various types of NPCs presented <br>in the Broken Tales Core Book on page 31, with the addition <br>of an Agenda that defines why they are in the service of the <br>Nemesis.<br>For convenience, it is useful to define Minions in two cate-<br>gories:<br>The Followers: Represented by NPCs and Dark Presences <br>drawn from the background of the Nemesis. These charac-<br>ters have been present since the creation of the Nemesis and <br>represent the relationships and social fabric in which the <br>Nemesis moves. These Minions should be characterized by <br>Agendas and Descriptors that represent their history with <br>the Nemesis. <br>The Minions must be created along with the Nemesis, al-<br>though it is possible to update the members of the group to <br>be consistent with what happens in the Hunters’ adventures.<br>The New Recruits: These are all the NPCs and Dark Pres-<br>ences that come under the influence of the Nemesis during <br>the course of the game. Their motivations will often be a re-<br>sult of the Hunter’s actions in their Scenario.<br>New Recruits must be created between Scenarios, reflecting <br>on what has happened and looking for points of connection <br>with the Nemesis.    <br>Step 6 Connections<br>This step is not mandatory, but preparing for it can be a tre-<br>mendous help to the Storyteller. It involves making a list of <br>Keywords related to the Nemesis, in order to more easily <br>note possible connections with the Scenarios and Scenes that <br>will be played out. <br>Another step is to identify the most thematic Scenarios for <br>the Nemesis and, in accordance with the main storyline, <br>sketch out a range of useful information about how the Nem-<br>esis might be grafted onto the events presented. This step <br>may take a lot of work, but it will provide a very useful set of <br>information and new gameplay hints that will be valuable to <br>the Storyteller. At the same time, these clues should address <br>both what the Nemesis can do during the Scenario and what <br>attracts the Nemesis to the Campaign after the Hunters re-<br>solve the Scenario.<br>Example:<br>The Connections of the Relentless Beastslayer for the Scenario <br>Bloodwhite’s Heart, available in The Broken Ones expansion, <br>are: “Finding a way to cure Bianca of her condition / Help-<br>ing Svenn preserve the Karenmann family secret. ” Bianca <br>has the traits of a monster, but she does not act like one: she <br>has a pure heart and would never hurt anyone. When outlin-<br>ing Connections, we also incorporate a reference to the orig-<br>inal fairytale, where the Huntsman is ordered to kill Snow <br>White, but cannot find the courage to do so. <br>In memory of the young woman he killed in the past, the Re-<br>lentless Beastslayer wants to find a way to save Bianca from <br>her monstrous condition. Connections tell us how he would <br>act during the Scenario, but with some interpretation, they <br>will also tell us what happens if the Nemesis comes to Lohr <br>before or after the Hunters.</p><p>78<br>If he arrives first: He could provide Svenn with resources and <br>Followers to help him keep Bianca’s secret. He could even wait <br>for the Hunters to arrive, and once they have the upper hand <br>over the Hessian Mercenaries, he could kidnap Bianca and <br>take her to safety. Finally, he could lurk by the river to am-<br>bush the Hunters before they reach the mine.<br>If he comes later: He could hire Svenn as a Minion and learn <br>everything the man knows about the Hunters. The same <br>strategy could apply to the Hessian Mercenaries. He could <br>also track down Bianca and snatch her from the clutches of <br>the Order. Finally, he could ambush the Hunters on one of <br>their journeys (Event) to punish those who harmed Bianca. <br>Each of the five Nemeses presented in Lost Stories has an <br>extensive list of Connections that make their usefulness <br>very clear. <br>Introducing Nemeses into the game<br>Nemeses are not simply NPCs to be added as opposition to <br>the Hunters, there are already Opponent Dark Presences <br>NPCs for that. Each Nemesis will have a consistent impact <br>on the Campaign or Scenario. It is a good idea to introduce <br>the Nemesis gradually, starting with simple clues and small <br>events that will evolve into more or less direct actions. The <br>Nemesis Agendas, especially the first two, serve as a long-<br>term guide to the Nemesis’ behavior.    <br>Some tips to ease the introduction of a Nemesis:<br> ◆ The first Agenda of each Nemesis gives important clues <br>as to what the Nemesis is interested in. Linking it to the <br>Scenarios already played gives consistency to their ap-<br>pearance in the game. It is better to delay the arrival of a <br>Nemesis in order to integrate it well into the Campaign <br>plot, rather than to drop them in as an opponent who has <br>no real reason to resent the Hunters.<br> ◆ Each Nemesis will eventually decide which Hunter is their <br>sworn enemy, so it makes sense to have as many Nemeses <br>in the Campaign as there are Hunters. Alternating the ap-<br>pearance of the Nemeses will make it easier to keep them <br>from wearing out their welcome too quickly.<br> ◆ A good alternative method of introducing the Nemesis <br>can be through chance encounters. The Nemesis is pres-<br>ent in the Scenario, but with an Agenda that does not con-<br>cern the Hunters, and only tangentially touches on events. <br>This will leave a trace of their passage for the Hunters to <br>discover, which will then serve as a link in their future ap-<br>pearances. <br> ◆ Nemeses have great power even when they are behind the <br>scenes. Gifts and Minions allow the Nemesis to influence <br>the world around the Hunters without directly appearing <br>on the Scene. These links should be outlined in Nemesis <br>Connections. <br>Don’t make the Nemeses the primary <br>antagonist of a Scenario<br>The Nemesis’ job is to hinder the Hunters, but future con-<br>frontations will be more interesting if you don’t unleash all <br>of their power against the Hunters right away. Nemeses can <br>be really scary thanks to the Gifts of Nemesis and Inves-<br>titure, but they will lose their appeal if they play all their <br>cards too soon. Each Scenario already has a plot and a cast <br>of main NPCs that animate it, and replacing them with a <br>Nemesis will only distract from the story. Therefore, do not <br>make Nemeses the antagonist of a Scenario unless it is the <br>final confrontation against them (see page 79).<br>Keep in mind that:<br> ◆ The Nemesis must be a valuable aid to the Scenario’s <br>NPCs, without replacing them in the main plot.<br> ◆ Thanks to the Y ou Won the Battle, not the War Gift, <br>a Nemesis can always make a run for it if the situation</p><p>79<br>takes a turn for the worse. For this reason, Nemeses <br>can be useful as surprises that appear briefly during a <br>Scene to add some excitement, then escape.<br> ◆ Not every appearance of the Nemesis has to be a con-<br>flict. Clues, verbal confrontations, and Minions brag-<br>ging about their masters’ power are good systems for <br>building up Hunters’ expectations for the arrival of <br>these new adversaries.<br> ◆ Encounters and Events are great ways to bring the <br>Nemesis into the game. In these moments, the Nemesis <br>can be the true antagonist, using Gifts and Minions to <br>put the Hunters at risk.<br> ◆ The Nemesis’ Gifts are meant to make them versatile, <br>not overly powerful. Each encounter should bring out a <br>different ability of the Nemesis so that their true threat <br>level is gradually revealed to the Hunters.  <br>Defeating a Nemesis<br>Each Nemesis requires a unique approach to defeat, as-<br>suming that is the ultimate goal of the Hunters. As with <br>all Broken Tales stories, it is the Player’s choices that create <br>turning points in the plot. Like the NPCs presented in the <br>Scenarios, the Nemesis isn’t a puppet with the sole purpose <br>of harming the Hunters, but a well-rounded character who, <br>if approached in the right way, may even understand and <br>help the Order.<br>There are several ways to present the final confrontation <br>with a Nemesis:<br> ◆ Create a Scenario dedicated to the Nemesis, starting <br>with the story in which they appear. If a Scenario based <br>on that story already exists among the official Scenar -<br>ios, it is recommended that you don’t propose it to the <br>Players and instead save it for the grand finale. Alter -<br>natively, it is possible to rewrite the Scenario, adapt it to <br>what the Hunters have already done, and put the Nem-<br>esis in the role of the main antagonist.<br> ◆ If the Hunters arrive at the final confrontation with <br>the One Who Plots in the Shadows and the Nemeses <br>are still in action, it is recommended that they be used <br>during the Epilogue. One or more Nemesis could use <br>Y ou Won the Battle, not the War during the con-<br>frontation, paving the way for the continuation of the <br>game’s Campaign.<br> ◆ If the Hunters are actively engaged in finding the Nem-<br>esis, it is only fair to reward them by creating a Sce-<br>nario that represents a confrontation with their enemy. <br>However, in order to reach this Scenario, they should <br>go through a series of encounters and a collection of <br>useful clues to uncover the location of the Nemesis.<br>Nemeses in Single Scenarios<br>Although a Nemesis reaches their full potential during <br>a Campaign, it is possible to include them when playing <br>individual Scenarios. Before embarking on the adventure, <br>the Storyteller should broadly introduce the Nemesis to <br>the Hunters, specifying why they are on their trail. The first <br>Nemesis Agenda provides good narrative hooks in this re-<br>gard. The Hunters will then be aware that an enemy is on <br>their trail and could complicate their plans any moment.<br>Example:<br>The Storyteller has prepared the House of Roses Scenario, in-<br>spired by Beauty and the Beast and included in the Broken <br>Ones expansion. The Hunter party consists of Garou the Old <br>Wolf, James the Swordsman, Baba Yaga the Child Witch, and <br>Niklaus von Krampus. With as many as three Hunters tied to <br>something monstrous, and a main NPC with the character -<br>istics of a monster (Dionysus Gonsalva), the Storyteller iden-<br>tifies the Relentless Beastslayer as an excellent Nemesis for <br>the game. The first Nemesis Agenda reads: “Track down and <br>eliminate any monster that threatens humanity. ”</p><p>80<br>The Storyteller then introduces the Nemesis to the group of <br>Hunters: They had previously encountered a strange figure <br>cloaked in black who had tried to kill Garou and Niklaus sev-<br>eral times because of their “monstrous” appearance. This is a <br>dangerous, merciless, and ruthless individual, a beast-killer <br>who seems to be obsessed with monsters. <br> <br>Players are unaware that there is a monstrous NPC in <br>the Scenario, and this combination of characters will <br>certainly lead to interesting situations.<br>Even if introduced at the beginning, a Nemesis may need <br>further hooks to the narrative:<br> ◆ The Nemesis has allied themselves with an NPC in the <br>Scenario to whom they provide support. They will not <br>act directly except to help that NPC achieve their goals.<br> ◆ Nemeses will come into play as the price for an Inter -<br>lude, giving players the distinct feeling that they have <br>made things more difficult by wasting time. <br> ◆ The Nemesis waits for the right moment to strike with <br>a direct attack. They will do so at a transitional mo-<br>ment in the Scenario’s plot when their appearance can <br>seamlessly fit into events and will not interfere with the <br>actions of the Main NPCs or even the events of the Sce-<br>nario itself. The Nemesis attacks the Hunters and will <br>be able to escape through the Gift Y ou Won the Battle, <br>not the War.<br>The Five Nemeses<br>Below are the five Nemeses created by the One Who Plots <br>in the Shadows to fight the Hunters. Each Nemesis is de-<br>rived from a fairytale archetype:<br> ◆ The Huntsman, on which the Relentless Beastslayer is <br>based, represents the deus ex machina that intervenes <br>to save the protagonists, a force of nature that punishes <br>monsters and villains.<br> ◆ The Lady of the Lake, the inspiration for the Wise <br>Fairy, is the powerful fairy whose gifts give the heroes <br>the power to win.<br> ◆ Thumbling (inspiring the King of Crime) and Viola  <br>(the archetypal Valiant Princess) represent the young <br>protagonists who manage to defeat the villains with <br>cunning and courage.<br> ◆ The Naked Emperor, a direct reference for the Mad <br>Emperor, represents truth overcoming lies, which, <br>when revealed, exposes deception.</p><p>81<br>The Relentless <br>Beastslayer  <br>Inspired by the Huntsman of many fairytales<br>Once upon a time, there was a skilled Beastslayer with a good <br>heart who traveled the world, offering his skills to small vil-<br>lages. The Beastslayer feared nothing, and more than once his <br>courage had saved helpless people from the threat of monsters <br>and wild beasts. One day, the Beastslayer was summoned to <br>a mission by the queen. Rumor had it that the queen was <br>actually a witch, but all the subjects were happy under her <br>leadership, and the Beastslayer decided to trust her anyway. <br>The queen had a very special request for him: to escort her <br>stepdaughter into the forest and remove her heart, for she <br>was actually a demon hiding in the guise of a maiden. The <br>Beastslayer refused to believe the queen, but she cast a spell <br>to deceive his eyes, and what the man saw was exactly what <br>the witch wanted. Bewitched and unable to object, the Beast-<br>slayer took the young woman into the woods and cut out her <br>heart with a precise stroke of his blade. When he came to <br>his senses, he tried to take revenge, only to discover that he <br>was wanted throughout the kingdom for the murder of the <br>young princess. The queen witch had used him as a scapegoat <br>so she could appear blameless before the king. Disappoint-<br>ed at his helplessness in the face of such evil , the <br>Beastslayer fled far away to the shelter of the great forest, and <br>with his hands still stained with blood, he finally came to a <br>small cottage. Finding the door open, he entered to see who <br>lived there, just in time to see a huge wolf devouring an old <br>grandmother and her young granddaughter. The Beastslay-<br>er attacked the monster, which was still intent on chewing <br>the little girl’s bones between its sharp fangs. After a furious <br>struggle, the wolf prevailed, leaving the Beastslayer on the <br>ground in the small yard of the house. With his belly ripped <br>open, but still alive, the Beastslayer found himself cursing all <br>monsters, in body and soul, who mercilessly slaughtered in-<br>nocent souls. And as his tears mingled with the rain that be-<br>gan to fall, he made an oath: he would become the scourge of <br>every aberration, the shadow that would appear to mete out <br>just punishment to every monster. Without mercy. <br>Descriptor: I am a skilled huntsman and have all the <br>means to kill any monster. I never say a word and try to keep <br>myself aloof from everyone.<br>5 Wounds<br>Opposition Level: Medium 5 <br>Agenda 1:  Track down and eliminate any monster that <br>threatens humanity.<br>Agenda 2: Set traps to kill monsters/Teach others how to <br>kill monsters. <br>Agenda 3: Kill the Hunters by taking them by surprise / <br>Challenge the Hunters on the battleground most advanta-<br>geous to me.<br>Agenda 4:  Form the Beast Slayer Guild and recruit the <br>most skilled individuals into its ranks / Capture and train <br>monsters to use as weapons against other monsters. <br>Gift - Hunt Master:  Once per Scenario, the Beastslayer <br>can appear in the Scene from a shadowy area or patch of <br>vegetation and act immediately in the Exchange. The Beast-<br>slayer is completely immune to all fear-inducing effects and <br>any manipulation (magical or otherwise) that would dis-<br>tract him from his goal: killing monsters.    <br>Gift - Nemesis:  See page 73. Sworn Enemies: Hunters <br>with monstrous traits or monsters.<br>Gift of Investiture - The Blade of Punishment:  <br>When the Beastslayer attacks a target with monstrous traits,</p><p>82<br>the blow always hits, with no chance to make a Defense Check. <br>Wounds inflicted with this weapon are conspicuous and impossible <br>to conceal, and cannot be healed in any way until the end of the <br>Scenario.  <br>Minions:<br>Hounds<br>The Relentless Beastslayer has trained many hounds, teaching <br>them to face monsters without fear.<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am an agile hunting dog, ready to carry out any <br>command of my master. <br>Agenda: Follow my master on hunting trips and serve him <br>even at the cost of my life. <br>Gift - Perfect Training: As long as the dog is focused on <br>its master, it cannot be distracted in any way. The NPC is <br>immune to all fear and mind control effects. When focus-<br>ing on a target to restrain it and prevent it from escaping, <br>the Hound uses OL Hard 7.</p><p>83<br>The Twelve Poachers <br>Inspired by the Twelve Huntsmen [Opponent)<br>Once upon a time, there was a princess who was deeply in <br>love with a prince. The two longed to marry, but the young <br>man’s father had already promised him to another noble <br>maiden. Unable to resist the last wishes of his dying father, <br>the prince abandoned the princess and went through with <br>the arranged marriage. Destroyed by grief, the abandoned <br>princess hatched a terrible deception. Together with eleven <br>other girls who closely resembled her, she pretended to be a <br>huntsman in the service of the prince and accompanied him <br>on every hunting trip. During one of these trips, the princess <br>staged an accident and pierced the new queen’s heart with <br>an arrow. That same night, she presented herself to her lov-<br>er and revealed what she had done, confident that he would <br>understand. But he did not: he was horrified and ordered the <br>guards to kill the princess who had posed as a huntsman. The <br>young woman managed to escape with her companions and, <br>convinced that she was in the right, took up poaching, wait-<br>ing for a new love to understand her heart.<br>OL Medium 5 <br>(1 Wound - 12 Gang Members)<br>Descriptor: We are skilled hunters and we disguise our -<br>selves as ordinary girls. We have no qualms about achieving <br>our goal. <br>Agenda: Serving the Relentless Beastslayer and dispensing <br>punishment in the name of our warped sense of justice.<br>Gift - A Delicate Maiden:  Unless a Poacher unleashes <br>her hunting weapons, she will look just like a normal vil-<br>lager. No NPC will consider her a threat. When a Poacher <br>reveals her true nature, her OL increases by 1 for the first <br>action she participates in.  <br>•<br>Connections: Monsters / Villagers in danger / Vicious <br>beasts / Hunting / Traps / Defending a location.<br>Red-Hood Iskra: Assist Vincent Arn, an old hunting com-<br>panion / Help Elizaveta get rid of her monstrous daughter.<br>Hunger Island: Retrieve the Stone that Came from the Sky <br>so that it cannot spawn new monsters / Prevent the inhabi-<br>tants and any visitors from leaving the island, as they may <br>be infected.<br>Bloodwhite’s Heart: Finding a way to cure Bianca of her <br>condition / Helping Svenn preserve the Karenmann family <br>secret.<br>Nikola’s Pledge: Capture the fearsome Badalisk for later <br>training. Use the village of Rovaniemi as bait to lure the crea-<br>ture / Help Nikola defend himself from intruders in exchange <br>for his monstrous Reindeer, which could be trained for mon-<br>ster hunting.</p><p>84<br>The Valiant Princess <br>Inspired by Tale of Tales<br>Once upon a time, there was a noble regent of Altomonte who became morbidly attached <br>to a flea. The old man cared for the flea as if it were a daughter and allowed it to grow to <br>the size of a large dog. The regent treated the flea like a member of his family, even going <br>so far as to neglect Viola, his only real daughter. The young girl suffered the humiliation <br>of being second in importance in her father’s eyes, and when a rich and ill-mannered <br>suitor came to ask for the princess’ hand, the Regent of Altomonte gave his consent to the <br>marriage, ignoring his daughter’s protests. The prospective bridegroom was a lecherous <br>old man, and there were ugly rumors that he had been involved in the deaths of his <br>previous brides. Disappointed by her father’s insensitivity and her suitor’s <br>wickedness, Viola left for her new home with her future husband, despairing of the <br>fate that awaited her because of men’s power games. But in the young princess’ heart <br>burned the fire of courage, and when she arrived at her destination, Viola refused to <br>participate in the marriage ceremony. As punishment, the old man locked her in the <br>dungeon of his castle, where she lived on bread and water until she agreed to marry <br>him. It was in the dungeons that Viola met seven brothers dedicated to smuggling <br>and the use of magic so feared by the Church. With the help of the seven, Viola <br>escaped from prison and that very night, she stabbed the old man in the heart <br>as he lay in bed with two concubines. The seven brothers were so impressed by <br>Viola’s courage that they swore allegiance to her. They had always lived to do <br>wrong, but now they had an example of justice to follow. The young prin-<br>cess then returned to her father, hoping that he would come to his senses. <br>Instead, he accused Viola of treason for breaking the sacred traditions <br>of the nobility: a woman like her could not afford to decide for herself <br>what was right or wrong.<br>With tears of grief in her eyes, Viola tried to leave, but the flea, <br>as if sensing her pain, acted for her. The insect leaped to her <br>father’s neck and cut his throat cleanly. The dying man <br>waved his arms at Viola for help, but the girl had <br>dried her tears and had no more words for her fa-<br>ther.</p><p>85<br>From that day on, Viola took charge, and with her trusty flea <br>at her side, she rewrote all the laws of Altomonte so that no <br>young woman would ever again have to endure the torment <br>of a society run by the will of men alone.<br>Descriptor: I am a brave princess who fights for the free-<br>dom of all oppressed youth. The passion that drives me allows <br>me to overcome any obstacle and ignore any pain.    <br>4 Wounds<br>Opposition Level: Medium 5<br>Agenda 1: Liberate all young people who are oppressed by <br>society. <br>Agenda 2: Support those who rise up against oppression / <br>Make the evil of the oppressors known to all.<br>Agenda 3: Use good-hearted people to oppose the Hunters / <br>Challenge the Hunters openly and boldly. <br>Agenda 4: Unite the weak and marginalized to create a <br>network to help others / Accumulate wealth to gain power in <br>society and impose more just laws and rules, disrupting secret <br>societies like the Order. <br>Gift - Porziella the Flea: The Valiant Princess is always <br>accompanied by her trusty flea, who guards her like a faith-<br>ful dog. Porziella is not considered an NPC but will act on <br>Viola’s behalf a second time in the Exchange. Porziella’s <br>skin is as hard as stone, so the bug cannot be removed by <br>normal means.<br>Gift - Nemesis:  See page 73. Sworn Enemies: Hunters <br>with malicious intent and men who represent authority.<br>Gift of Investiture - The Heart of Courage:  The Val-<br>iant Princess is considered to have OL Hard 7 against all <br>actions designed to frighten her or restrain her. Once per <br>Scene, the Heart of Courage can negate the effect of any <br>Gift used against the Valiant Princess.<br>Minions:<br>The Seven Shady Brothers <br>Inspired by The Flea (Opponent)<br>Once upon a time, there were seven brothers who dedicated <br>themselves to a life of banditry and the reckless use of mag-<br>ic. After a robbery gone wrong, the seven were arrested and <br>sentenced to the gallows. In prison, they met a brave prin-<br>cess who had been imprisoned not for a crime, but simply <br>for wanting the freedom to choose her own life. Impressed by <br>such courage, the seven brothers helped the princess escape, <br>and once free, they swore allegiance to her. In her service, <br>they would finally do something good to redeem themselves <br>from a life of causing misery. <br>OL Medium 5 <br>(1 Wound - 7 Gang Members)<br>Descriptor: We are young brigands who learned magic <br>from our late mother, a witch. We hate law and religion, in-<br>stitutions that have always persecuted what they do not un-<br>derstand. <br>Agenda: Help the Valiant Princess subvert the order and <br>dogmas of society.    <br>Gift - Scoundrel Magic: Each of the Seven Shady Broth-<br>ers has a magical power they can use during the course of <br>a Scene.<br>Mase: He has extraordinary hearing and can hear a <br>speech even through a wall. All Checks performed to <br>avoid him hearing something are done with 2 Penal-<br>ties.<br>Nardo: He can excrete soap from his skin and slip <br>through any crevice. He can also automatically free <br>himself from any physical obstacle.</p><p>86<br>Cola: He has a razor-sharp right hand and inflicts 2 <br>Wounds with all his attacks.<br>Micco: He can make the old wooden stick he always <br>carries grow at will. The weapon can stretch up to sixty <br>feet or expand to the size of a door.<br>Petrullo: He can create a water jet from his hands that <br>can hit enemies and objects up to ten meters away. <br>Ascadeo: He can throw one of the many rocks in his <br>bag, always hitting the target. When he throws a stone, <br>Ascadeo acts at OL Hard 7. <br>Ceccone: He can magically guide the arrows he shoots <br>with his crossbow, sending them on impossible trajec-<br>tories.      <br>•<br>Connections: Youth in danger / Men abusing authority / <br>Rebellion / Prisons / Marriages / Help. <br>I Don’t Believe: Help the Lost Children and Pietrik subvert <br>authority in London / Eliminate Gwendolyn’s family to give <br>the young girl a chance to emancipate herself and assert her <br>independence.<br>The House of Roses: Help Bellina make the island indepen-<br>dent of the Church by providing her with alliances and mil-<br>itary support / Rescue Francesca and train her as a ruthless <br>assassin to be unleashed against the Order.<br>Stegeborg’s Quiet: Save Talia’s life by preventing any threat <br>from entering the castle / Capture and torture Accursio until <br>he begs for a quick death.<br>A Mother’s Heart: Help the Bats find their place in the world, <br>even if it means conquering it by force / Punish the Church <br>and the townspeople for not doing anything to save Blanca’s <br>children.</p><p>87<br>The King of Crime <br>Inspired by Thumbling<br>Once upon a time, a terrible famine struck a remote village, so that a woodcutter and his wife could not feed <br>their seven children. They made a fateful decision: to abandon the children in the forest. The youngest of them <br>all was named Thumbling, and though he was tiny in stature, he possessed a cunning that would make the <br>sliest of brigands envious. Once alone in the forest, Thumbling’s six siblings despaired, but the little one took <br>charge and led them all to a small house whose light illuminated the darkness of the night. Throughout <br>the journey, the brothers and sisters complained and lamented every misfortune, but Thumbling was <br>undaunted. When they arrived at the house, the seven children were greeted by a kind woman who <br>made them comfortable and served them a hot meal. All the siblings were happy to have found a new <br>home, but Thumbling was wary of trusting such kindness. He warned his brothers and sisters, who <br>mocked him. Tired and with full bellies, the siblings went to sleep, ignoring the doubts of Thumbling, <br>who decided to stay awake to keep watch. At the stroke of midnight, a fearsome ogre returned to <br>the house. Thumbling overheard him talking to his wife, complimenting her for providing him with <br>juicy children to devour the next day. Hearing of the terrible deception, Thumbling devised a plan <br>to save his brothers and sisters: at night, taking advantage of his diminutive size, he slipped out of <br>the room and slit the throat of the ogre and his wife as they slept. Stained with blood and shaken <br>by what he had done, Thumbling clung to the happiness of having saved his beloved brothers and <br>sisters. When they awoke, they saw what Thumbling had done and immediately chased him out <br>of the house, accusing him of killing out of spite the only people who had cared for them. Hurt <br>by these words, Thumbling ran far away. Ten years passed, and Thumbling had become im-<br>mensely wealthy. Using his brilliant mind, the young man had risen through the ranks of the <br>underworld to become one of the most powerful criminals in all of Europe. Loaded with coins <br>and jewels, Thumbling returned to the ogre’s home, where he knew his siblings had settled. <br>Confident that he would surprise everyone with the gifts he had brought, he approached <br>the window...<br>In the festively decorated hall, he saw his six siblings toasting with their parents, gathered <br>together like a real family, enjoying the riches found in the ogre’s house. A family por<br>-<br>trait towered over the richly decorated hall: father, mother, and six children. <br>Thumbling’s eyes narrowed to a slit: they had forgotten him, after all he had done <br>for them.</p><p>88<br>Disappointed at the abandonment of the only peo-<br>ple he had ever loved , Thumbling dropped a large dia -<br>mond on the doorstep, knocked, and left. He heard his father’s <br>agitated voice when he opened the door and saw such a beau-<br>tiful gift abandoned. <br>Returning to his hiding place, Thumbling wrote an open let-<br>ter to all the criminals of Europe: the famous Ogre’s Eye, the <br>largest diamond ever seen in Europe, was in a small house in <br>the woods, guarded by a gang of petty thieves. <br>It took less than a day for the news to reach him: an entire <br>family, father, mother, and six siblings, had been mercilessly <br>slaughtered by an army of criminals who had come from far <br>and wide. Almost nothing was left of the poor people’s bodies, <br>dismembered in the course of the most unspeakable torture. <br>As the most skilled of his assassins returned to the lair with <br>the Ogre’s Eye, Thumbling sighed and then smiled at another <br>successful plan.<br>Descriptor: I am a major criminal and pull the strings of <br>the underworld throughout Europe. I have wealth and ser -<br>vants ready to carry out my every order. Thanks to my cun-<br>ning, I make perfect plans to always get what I want.  <br>3 Wounds<br>Opposition Level: Medium 5  <br>Agenda 1: To have all the criminals in the world at my ser-<br>vice. <br>Agenda 2: Finding criminals and scoundrels to increase my <br>sphere of influence and favors / Gathering benefits and infor-<br>mation from the misfortunes of others.       <br>Agenda 3:  Use my resources and Minions to attack the <br>Hunters without exposing myself on the front lines / Use de-<br>ception and blackmail to corner the Hunters.     <br>Agenda 4: Create a shadow government to guide the desti-<br>ny of a Europe under my control / Take the reins of the Order <br>and restore the balance dictated by the One Who Plots in the <br>Shadows. <br>Gift - Diabolical Plan:  The King of Crime always has a <br>cunning plan to unleash on his enemies. He can use each of <br>these effects once per Scenario.<br>1. Receive a compromising item found on an NPC or <br>Hunter. It is not possible to avoid this effect.<br>2. Rewrite the Agenda of a Minor NPC who turns out to <br>be a servant of the King of Crime.<br>3. Introduce a Treasure of the Order and use it for the rest <br>of the Scene. <br>Gift - Nemesis:  See page 73. Sworn Enemies: Hunters <br>who engage in crime and Hunters who fight crime.   <br>Gift of Investiture - The Bag of Wealth:  Once per <br>Scene, the King of Crime can flaunt his wealth to make any-<br>one who sees his bag greedy. Anyone who sees the Bag of <br>Wealth will have to make a Defense Check against OL Hard <br>7 or remain spellbound for about ten seconds, unable to do <br>anything but fantasize about this incredible wealth. NPCs <br>automatically fall victim to this Gift. Suffering 1 Wound in-<br>terrupts the effect of the Bag. The King of Crime can decide <br>who does not suffer the effects of the Bag, such as his own <br>Minions.</p><p>89<br>Minions:<br>Scoundrel<br>The dregs of society, always ready to serve the King of <br>Crime.<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a lowlife who lives off theft and extortion. <br>I draw strength from my fellow gang members and am not <br>stupid enough to go at it alone.    <br>Agenda: Carry out the boss’s orders without asking too <br>many questions. <br>Gift - Band:  Those who possess this Gift increase their <br>Opposition Level by 1 when acting against a target with the <br>support of one or more companions.<br>Sicario<br>Ruthless assassin in the pay of the King of Crime.<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a capable killer and always act in cold <br>blood. <br>Agenda: Eliminate the Boss’ designated targets by striking <br>from the shadows. <br>Gift - Assassin:  Those who possess this Gift increase <br>their Opposition Level by 1 when acting from the shadows <br>or in low light. When the NPC makes an attack that catches <br>the target by surprise, they inflict 1 Additional Wound. <br>The Raven Clan <br>Inspired by the Seven Ravens [Opponent)<br>Once upon a time, there was a family in which only sons <br>were born. The father and mother longed for a daughter <br>and prayed for a long time to receive this grace. When the <br>baby girl finally arrived, the family’s enthusiasm quickly fad-<br>ed. The newborn was extremely weak and the doctor made <br>it clear that she would not be saved without a miracle. The <br>father then sent the seven sons in search of a powerful witch <br>who lived not far from the village. When they arrived at the <br>witch’s house, the seven brothers were given a jar of magic <br>water that could give strength and vitality. The seven began <br>to argue over who should carry the jar, as they all wanted to <br>receive compliments from their father. In the struggle, the jar <br>fell to the ground and shattered into a thousand pieces, scat-<br>tering the precious water. When they returned home, there <br>was nothing to do for their little sister. The father, in despair, <br>cursed his children for fighting over the jar like greedy ravens <br>over a piece of meat. The witch heard the man’s grief and, <br>as punishment, turned the seven brothers into seven ravens, <br>forever condemned to a life as watchers, never to be shown <br>affection again. <br>OL Medium 5 - (1 Wound - 7 Ravens)<br>Descriptor: We are big black ravens but with the soul and <br>mind of a human being. <br>Agenda: Observe the world and report back to the King of <br>Crime, who has promised us a cure for the curse that plagues us. <br>Gift - Curse of the Raven:  Each of the seven Ravens <br>is mentally connected to the others. They all immediately <br>learn everything one hears and sees. Although the body is <br>that of a Raven, their mind remains that of a human, so a <br>Raven can write while holding a pen in its beak or open a <br>door, and perform other actions that are too complex for a</p><p>90<br>normal animal. Realizing that the NPC is not a com-<br>mon animal is very difficult, so the observer must <br>make a Defense Check versus OL Hard 7 to realize <br>who is really in front of them. <br>•<br>Connections: Criminals / Pacts and secrets / Money <br>and treasure / Information / Escape / Murder.  <br>The Smile in the Darkness: Offer protection to Father <br>Adrien so that he can continue to provide me with ex-<br>cellent absinthe / Kidnap Alizée, and then use her as a <br>bargaining chip with the Church.<br>The City of Pigs: Deceive both Bardolf Greed and the <br>Pig Heads, promising them help in exchange for deeds <br>to houses and factories / Establish an exclusive trade <br>in the prized flesh of the God Under the Mine.<br>A Frozen Reflection: Support Gerda and Kay’s deceit <br>and get into the business of Frozen Madness / Help all <br>gangs of criminals and outlaws by donating resources <br>to them to expand their network of followers.<br>In Y our Eyes, With Y our Feet: Helping Cinder main-tain control of the city and slowly making her my <br>pawn to exploit / Using the situation to have old busi-<br>ness enemies I have in the city killed, taking advantage <br>of the chaos created by the deaths of young girls.<br>The Wise Fairy  <br>Inspired by the Lady of the Lake from the Arthurian Myth<br>Once upon a time, there was a powerful fairy whose birth was <br>lost in the mists of time. Always driven by a kind heart and <br>an altruistic spirit, the fairy gave her help to those in need <br>without ever asking for anything in return. Soon, people from <br>every land came to the lake where the fairy lived to ask for <br>her help. No matter how much good she did, the pilgrims <br>kept coming. So the fairy decided to give some of her magic <br>to chosen people to travel the world and bring help to all who <br>needed it. The fairy forged objects of great power, raised little <br>orphans to become heroes, and taught her spells to wise old <br>men so they could help humanity. After more than a hundred <br>years of effort, the fairy found herself exhausted and almost <br>completely drained of power. Weary but content, she let her-<br>self fall to the bottom of her lake and fell into a restful sleep. <br>More than a decade passed before she awoke: she had slept <br>peacefully, knowing that her chosen ones had fulfilled their <br>mission to help others. But when she looked out at the world <br>again, she was dismayed by what she saw. The champions she <br>had armed, the heroes she had raised, and the wizards she <br>had taught had all abandoned the path of benevolence to pur-<br>sue selfish personal gain. Disappointed by the darkness <br>of the human soul , the fairy vowed that she would never <br>again use her power to do good, but only to increase her own <br>power and judge the world from the heights of her superiority.</p><p>91<br>Descriptor: I am the most powerful fairy that has ever walked this earth and I master the <br>magic of creation. Whatever I wish comes true, but I don’t like to flaunt my power without reason.    <br>4 Wounds<br>Opposition Level: Medium 5<br>Agenda 1: Find wizards and heroes and expose their weaknesses. <br>Agenda 2: Provide power at a dear price, as a reminder that good <br>for its own sake does not exist / Always cast a shadow over what <br>good is done, to show that darkness can never be completely erad-<br>icated. <br>Agenda 3: Use my power to weaken the Hunters and turn <br>them against my heroes / Separate those who use magic from <br>those who protect them, confronting each with their weak-<br>ness.<br>Agenda 4: Create an army of champions who yearn for <br>the destruction of the world / Create cursed objects and <br>rituals to send panic through humanity. <br>Gift - Water Fairy:  The Wise Fairy is a spirit of <br>great power born of water. As an additional action to <br>any Exchange, she can command the water around her <br>to perform one of these actions:<br>1. Hit a target up to thirty feet away with a water whip.<br>2. Move instantly to any place in her line of sight where <br>there is water.<br>3. Create a wave to send all nearby targets to the ground.</p><p>92<br>Gift - Nemesis:  See page 73. Sworn Enemies: Hunters <br>who use magic or act heroically.<br>Gift of Investiture - The Wand of Creation: The Wise <br>Fairy can give or take power from a person, creature, ob-<br>ject, or place. <br>1. If she takes away power: A person or creature loses <br>the use of all Gifts, including Dark Ego, for the rest of the <br>Scene. An object loses all special qualities for the rest of <br>the Scene, and if it has no special abilities, it simply turns <br>to ash. A Place loses one of its features, e.g. a stone house <br>becomes brittle.<br>2. If she donates power:  A person, creature, or object <br>receives a magical ability, which must be specified with a <br>Descriptor. The power is permanent, but the same recipient <br>cannot have more than one imparted power. A Place gains <br>a new property that must be detailed with a Descriptor, e.g. <br>a street can be flooded. <br>Minions:<br>Lancelot the Courteous  <br>Inspired by Lancelot of the Arthurian Myth <br>[Opponent)<br>Once upon a time, there was a young orphan who was raised <br>by the powerful Wise Fairy. His name was Lancelot, and as <br>he grew up, he became a bold and handsome young man, <br>gifted with all kinds of skills. The fairy intended Lancelot to <br>be an example of how a hero should behave, but in the young <br>man’s soul grew an unhealthy attraction to forbidden love, <br>which drove him to long for hearts that could not be his. And <br>so Lancelot served many nobles, each time ruining those he <br>was sworn to protect and consummating forbidden loves with <br>the wives, daughters, and sons of the lords to whom he had <br>sworn an oath. Heartbroken by his perversions, the Wise <br>Fairy called Lancelot back to her so that he could do no more <br>harm, but soon the boy’s amorous attentions turned to the <br>one he could call his own mother... <br>OL Medium 5 - 3 Wounds<br>Descriptor: I am a capable and bold man of action and <br>excel in every challenge I set myself to. I feel an unhealthy <br>attraction to those who have already given their hearts to an-<br>other love. <br>Agenda: To serve the Wise Fairy to the best of my ability <br>and to make her fall in love with me / To strive to conquer <br>any potential impossible love.<br>Gift - Courteous Knight:  Lancelot excels at any chal-<br>lenge, and when a Check is made for an action against him, <br>only an Outcome with a Cost can be obtained, regardless of <br>the total Successes. <br>Chosen Heroes<br>Subjects of great skill who serve the Wise Fairy to up-<br>hold justice. <br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a hero, always ready to fight for the Wise <br>Fairy. I have a one-sided view of the truth and only believe <br>what my lady says.    <br>Agenda: Fulfilling every wish of the Wise Fairy. <br>Gift - Heroic Soul:  The NPC will even ignore death to <br>satisfy the Wise Fairy. When they suffer their final Wound, <br>they can act one last time before leaving the battle. When <br>they enter the Scene, they can use a power granted by the <br>Wand of Creation, complete with a Descriptor created by <br>the Storyteller.</p><p>93<br>•<br>Connections: Magic items / Heroes / Justice / Good deeds <br>/ Chosen ones / Magic.<br>Of Flesh and Wood: Give Geppetto and Antonio Ciliegia a <br>chance to realize their ambitions / Help bring Azzurra back <br>to life and then make her a disciple.<br>A Soldier’s Duty: Enable Andersen’s gang to face Enar on <br>equal terms / Prove to the Sea Fairy that I am the best at <br>creating champions.<br>The King’s Awakening: Rebuild the old house in the lake <br>and give it to the Fairies, driving out all the pesky humans <br>/ Promise to choose a champion from among the island <br>knights; the honor will go to the one who eliminates the most <br>Hunters of the Order.<br>The Last Wish: Make Bastian live up to the hogwash he <br>tells (at least once) / Retrieve the three enchanted items and <br>bring Britta back to life to win her devotion. <br>The Mad Emperor  <br>Inspired By The Emperor’s New Clothes<br>Once upon a time, there was a vain Emperor who loved <br>to adorn himself with fine jewelry and dress in the latest <br>fashions. The Emperor had little interest in governing his <br>lands, leaving that task to his trusted advisors. This allowed <br>him to devote his full attention to festivals and receptions, <br>all good occasions to show off his best clothes. The Emperor <br>was not an evil person, he simply preferred to entrust tasks <br>to the most competent rather than the highest ranking. The <br>Emperor was also fond of the arts, and under his reign, all <br>people, even the poorest, had the opportunity to indulge <br>their passions, receiving substantial donations from the Em-<br>peror himself. Happy to be able to give beautiful creations <br>to the world, the Emperor did not notice that his advisors <br>and subjects soon began to take advantage of his generos-<br>ity. Everyone complimented the Emperor: “What graceful <br>movements His Majesty makes”, “What elegant clothes Your <br>Grace wears”... even when he was barely awake and wearing <br>only simple pajamas. Doubt began to creep into the naive <br>ruler’s heart, and when he summoned the kingdom’s trea-<br>surer, the harsh reality gave shape to the prison of deception <br>and self-satisfaction in which he had been caught. While the <br>Emperor was preoccupied with beauty and art, his minis-<br>ters, with the consent of all the citizens, had plundered every <br>resource. Disappointed by the lies and false compli-<br>ments, the Emperor summoned the general of the army <br>and his soldiers. All the townspeople and ministers were <br>herded into the main square, where, one by one, they were <br>blinded by the soldiers’ blades. Naked, with only the crown <br>on his head, the Emperor walked among the desperate and <br>suffering people and asked, “How do you find me today? Do <br>you like my elegant attire?” and everyone nodded, seeing <br>nothing, in fear of losing their lives as well as their eyes.</p><p>94<br>Descriptor: I am an elegant nobleman who many people <br>think is mad. The truth is that I can see things as they really <br>are, beyond all masks and illusions. <br>4 Wounds<br>Opposition Level: Medium 5<br>Agenda 1: Expose secrets and lies for what they really are.<br>Agenda 2: Make people conscious of the truth, even when <br>dangerous and unpleasant / Drive people mad, for only in <br>madness can one be rid of bad feelings.     <br>Agenda 3:  Act recklessly by doing things the Hunters <br>would never expect / Secretly follow the Hunters and drive <br>the world around them crazy.  <br>Agenda 4: Create an army of madmen ready to strike at <br>the Order and all that it stands for / Capture and make the <br>Hunters insane, causing them to turn on their own com-<br>rades.<br>Gift - The Seed of Madness: By mumbling gibberish, <br>the Mad Emperor can use his action to plant the seed of <br>madness in a target. The target will receive a Descriptor’s <br>Downside representing an obsession or irrational attitude <br>they will have to act out as much as possible. This effect <br>is automatic on Minor NPCs and discretionary on Main <br>NPCs, while a Hunter can make a Defense Check against <br>OL Hard 7 to close their mind at the last second. The De-<br>scriptor created lasts for the duration of the Scene: a Hunt-<br>er who has not marked the Downside by the end of the <br>Scene loses 3 Soma due to the effort required to resist the <br>madness raging in his mind.<br>Gift - Nemesis:  See page 73. Sworn Enemies: Hunters <br>with crazy traits or related to art.    <br>Gift of Investiture - The Crown of Illusion: Because <br>of the power of the Crown, the Emperor can use each of <br>these effects once per Scene. An effect that has already <br>been used in the Scene can only be reactivated at the cost <br>of 1 Wound.<br>1. Your Eyes are Mine: The eyes of all subjects who see <br>the Mad Emperor explode. All targets take 1 Wound, this <br>effect is automatic on Minor NPCs and discretionary on <br>Main NPCs, while a Hunter can make a Defense Check <br>against OL Hard 7 to look away at the last second. The <br>Wound inflicted by this effect is not fatal, but almost com-<br>pletely limits the sufferer’s ability to see.<br>2. Don’t Look at Me: The Mad Emperor becomes invis-<br>ible to the human eye. When he speaks or acts, all actions <br>taken against him suffer 2 Penalties. This effect ends when <br>the Mad Emperor takes 1 Wound or uses a Gift.</p><p>95<br>Minions:<br>The Mad Emperor does not like to have Minions around. <br>He will occasionally use subjects he has driven mad with <br>his words, but only for the time it takes to get them to per<br>-<br>form a specific task.<br>•<br>Connections: Madness / Truth and lies / Conspiracy / Lux-<br>ury / Art / Solitude.<br>Wonderbedlam: Force those recovering from madness to re-<br>lapse, keeping the level of madness in the world unchanged / <br>Make a deal with the Director to turn Wonder into a factory <br>of mad subjects.<br>OZena the Suffering and Desperate: Help Norman Hen-<br>kle retrieve the Compass Rose and wreak havoc / Punish all <br>those who judge the residents of the three villages - Yellow, <br>Red, and Smaragd.<br>I Will Stay with Y ou Always: Help the Swallow take revenge <br>and ridicule the regent of Prague / Give the prince freedom <br>to find his own way, probably one of death and destruction...<br>Journey of a Thousand and One Nights: Travel hidden in <br>Sinbad’s ship and complicate the Hunters’ lives by driving <br>those they meet mad / Save Sherazade from the Hunters, <br>then drive her mad so she becomes my queen.</p>"},"sort":100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513737048,"modifiedTime":1781513737048,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}],"folder":null,"flags":{"broken-tales":{"adventureSlug":"nemesis","collection":"Lost Stories","sourceFile":"bt-ls-book-1-ENG-SCREEN.pdf","pages":"72-96"}},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513737048,"modifiedTime":1781513737048,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}
{"_id":"eehcUufOV29mGQnf","name":"The King's Awakening","pages":[{"_id":"hcphCf8116JRZGjT","name":"Summary","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h1>The King's Awakening</h1><p><strong>Collection:</strong> Lost Stories</p><p><strong>Source:</strong> bt-ls-book-1-ENG-SCREEN.pdf, pages 175-200.</p><p><img src=\"systems/broken-tales/assets/adventures/maps/the-kings-awakening-p175-full.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto;\" /></p>"},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513743951,"modifiedTime":1781513743951,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"Emx6OOYY6QjtuCjx","name":"Setup","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>The King's Awakening - Setup</h2><p>174<br>The King’s <br>Awakening<br>A Scenario inspired by the Arthurian Myth<br>Once upon a time...<br>A mysterious island shrouded with mist appeared off  <br>the coast of England in the North Sea. According to the <br>tales of superstitious sailors, the strange island could <br>only be the legendary Camelot. The English Crown, <br>concerned about the growing unrest among the people, <br>sent a ship to understand the nature of this dark place, <br>but the expedition was swallowed by the mists and never <br>heard from again. The trusted royal advisor Merlin, <br>who had a history of working for the good of the Crown, <br>returned to London claiming to know the secret of the <br>mysterious island. Merlin’s tale prompted the Crown to <br>request the Order’s intervention to avert a threat that, <br>as the envelope reads, “could not be matched by all the <br>armies of the world. ”  <br>Security keywords: Desecration of graves / Coercion <br>through the use of force / Persecution</p><p>175<br>The story that led us here...<br>Throughout his millennia-long existence, Am-<br>brose the Sorcerer, known as Old Merlin, has controlled <br>the destinies of kingdoms and empires. He has used his <br>arcane powers to determine their glorious beginnings <br>and miserable ends, with the long list of beneficiaries <br>including the legendary Camelot. Merlin manipulat-<br>ed the ruler Arthur from an early age, prompting the <br>pure-hearted young man to unite many peoples under <br>his leadership. But in time, each of Arthur’s successes an-<br>gered Merlin, who grew resentful that, even ignorant of <br>the fact that he was merely a puppet, the king could turn <br>the Sorcerer’s every trick to the benefit of those most in <br>need despite Merlin’s selfish goals.<br>Blinded by envy, Merlin used his magic to strip Arthur of <br>all his Virtues, one by one, gradually transforming a just <br>and benevolent king into a bloodthirsty tyrant. Arthur’s <br>reign began to unravel as the actions of the now-mad rul-<br>er incited the populace to rebellion.<br>One of the many quests undertaken by Percival, a knight <br>in the service of Camelot, had led to the discovery of the <br>Holy Grail, an artifact that could guarantee eternal life. <br>Arthur had drunk from the magic cup, becoming im-<br>mortal and destined to rule forever. Backed into a corner, <br>Merlin realized that control was slipping out of his grasp. <br>Invoking the power of magic, he engaged in a battle with <br>the king. After a grueling battle that lasted more than a <br>hundred days, Merlin succeeded in sending Arthur into <br>a deep sleep, plunging all of Camelot into the cold waters <br>of the North Sea.<br>Tired and weak, Merlin took a long rest, leaving the <br>world safe from his machinations for several centuries. <br>The story at the arrival of the <br>Hunter...<br>Merlin has ignored or forgotten that the one who found <br>the Holy Grail, Percival the Seeker, also drank from the cup <br>before delivering it to Arthur. By the time Camelot sank, <br>Percival was on dry land, immortal in a world unknown to <br>him. After hundreds of years of revelry, the Seeker began <br>to go mad, until he decided to resurrect his old lord and <br>reclaim his “life as a noble knight. ”<br>Percival threw the now-empty Grail into the water, awak-<br>ening Arthur and enabling the lord to break Merlin’s spell. <br>Camelot then emerged from the water, along with the is-<br>land and all its people, unaware that they had been frozen <br>in time for centuries. <br>The awakening of the entire island has brought great up-<br>heaval: Arthur has given orders to prepare an army for the <br>conquest of Europe. The mad king’s idea is to gather all the <br>people of Avalon, turn them into undead, and march them <br>to the mainland. Guinevere, always an innocent victim of <br>Merlin’s machinations, has never accepted her husband’s <br>madness and has fled in search of help. Hiding among the <br>commoners of Camelot, the queen desperately seeks a way <br>to cure her beloved Arthur, who has mobilized the Knights <br>of the Round Table to find her and force her back to court.<br>Merlin, for his part, is determined to leave the dirty work <br>in the hands of the Hunters. While the latter will go to great <br>lengths to find Virtues to weaken Arthur, the old Sorcer -<br>er plans to recover and escape with the Virtue of Wisdom. <br>Only by returning the quality of wisdom to Arthur can his <br>senses be restored, turning him into a just and benevolent <br>king to the people once more, perhaps willing to make a <br>deal with the Hunters.</p><p>176<br>How to manage the Scenario<br>This Scenario unfolds as a long exploration of the island of <br>Avalon, with the Hunters moving from Zone to Zone, ini-<br>tially knowing only the location of Camelot Castle, which is <br>located in the center of the island. The Storyteller will then <br>place the map of the island in the center of the table, show-<br>ing the Zone that includes the beach where the Hunters’ <br>ships have landed.<br>Y ou can photocopy or print the map of the island on page <br>187.<br>Moving along the map<br>During the Scenario, Hunters move from one Zone to <br>another in an orthogonal way, so diagonal movement is <br>prohibited. Each Zone presents situations and possible En-<br>counters to be dealt with. At the beginning of the Scenario, <br>the Hunters are unfamiliar with the island and will learn <br>what each Zone contains simply by moving around. How-<br>ever, interaction with some NPCs may lead the Hunters to <br>information about a particular Zone and its contents. The <br>Storyteller decides what information will be revealed as the <br>Scenario progresses, keeping the narrative consistent and <br>updating the map accordingly.<br>When Hunters call for an Interlude, the usual rules apply, <br>with the exception that the NPC Agenda advances only for <br>Merlin, as explained on page 179.<br>The Zones<br>Each Zone is detailed with a Description and some infor -<br>mation about what can be found there. The Description <br>also includes NPCs and Threats that Hunters may choose <br>to face. When Hunters arrive in a Zone, the Storyteller rolls <br>on the Encounter Table (page 180) to determine if anyone <br>is present. This process adds NPCs with their own Agendas, <br>creating a random mix that can lead to fresh situations. The <br>Storyteller is free to add NPCs to the Scene as they see fit, <br>and is not obligated to introduce them immediately. <br>The Storyteller is then free to develop the events as they <br>wish. Some of the unique aspects of this Scenario may re-<br>quire a strong dose of improvisation, as each Zone provides <br>a number of clues and potential situations, but does not go <br>into too much detail compared to more classic Scenarios. <br>Therefore, there are several ways to approach the Scenario:<br>With prior preparation<br>The Storyteller describes all the Zones, adds details that <br>they find interesting, and completely sets up the Scenario <br>before proposing it for the Session. In this way, the explo-<br>ration can be planned in detail, and locations and NPCs of <br>Encounters can be added as needed in the chosen Zones, <br>rather than being randomly generated. <br>Improvising<br>The Storyteller does not prepare anything and details things <br>on the fly, relying on the information provided by the Zone <br>and the Encounter Table to determine which NPCs will be <br>present.</p><p>1<br>177<br>Playing the Scenario with Village <br>Rules<br>Because of its highly exploratory and survivalist nature, <br>this Scenario lends itself well to being played using the Vil-<br>lage rules presented in The Broken Ones. Only a few mod-<br>ifications are required.<br> ◆ The Villagers were part of the first expedition sent by <br>the Crown and suffered the unfortunate fate of Cap-<br>tain Boyce’s crew. Zone 2 - Beach (page 188) becomes <br>the initial Zone, while Zone 1 - Landing (page 188) is <br>nothing more than an empty beach where the Hunters’ <br>ship will land at the end of the Scenario.<br> ◆ The Storyteller integrates information from Zone 2 - <br>Beach (page 188) and Boyce’s journal to tell the story <br>of Glatisant’s attack and the ensuing massacre. Boyce’s <br>last wishes will guide the actions of the Villagers, who <br>must gather as much information about the island as <br>possible and await the arrival of the ship carrying the <br>Order’s Hunters.<br> ◆ The purpose of the Scenario for the Villagers is to ex-<br>plore the island and survive for at least 15 days. The <br>Storyteller accumulates 1 Day Token to keep track of <br>the time that elapses.<br> ◆ The other survivors will also settle in Zone 2 - Beach, <br>allowing a Player to use a possible Bond in case their <br>Villagers die. If the group is far from Zone 2 - Beach <br>(page 188), the Storyteller should consider introduc-<br>ing an Encounter with Survivors (page 180) to re-<br>plenish the ranks of the Villagers.</p>"},"sort":50000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513743952,"modifiedTime":1781513743952,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"ehy7k0CfQv8oulZF","name":"Scene 1","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>The King's Awakening - Scene 1</h2><p>First Scene<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: After two days of sailing, the <br>silhouette of a large island appears before your eyes. Thick <br>blankets of fog shroud the coast, making it almost impossible <br>to discern its details. All you know is that all traces of the <br>previous expedition on behalf of the Crown have been lost. <br>“Hunters!” Old Merlin’s voice calls your attention. “We are <br>about to enter a land of great and ancient magic that has lain <br>dormant at the bottom of the sea for centuries. In Camelot, <br>time has stood still, and what you will see is beyond the com-<br>mon concept of reality as you know it. ” You know that Merlin <br>is a sorcerer of great skill, and even the Order seeks his advice <br>when their affairs are muddled by magic and spells. He will <br>therefore be your guide in this strange land as you attempt to <br>defeat the great threat it poses. <br>Place: A small uninhabited beach. A long promontory of <br>rocks forms a natural jetty to the mainland. <br>Time: Early in the morning, a thick blanket of fog makes it <br>difficult to see much.<br>Initial Situation: The crew, led by Captain Bennett, pre-<br>pares the ship for its stay, while Merlin summons the Hunt-<br>ers to the beach to instruct them.<br>Information: Merlin appears willing to dispel the Hunt-<br>ers’ doubts, but will omit any details that might reveal his <br>true intentions. Mainly, he will share with the Hunters what <br>he sees fit about the following.<br> ◆ In the center of the island stands the Castle of Camelot, <br>where a king named Arthur resides. He is a legendary <br>hero who became immortal after drinking from the <br>cup of the Holy Grail. Long ago, Merlin was able to seal <br>Arthur and the entire island in a magical sleep, pre-</p><p>178<br>venting the mad ruler from invading Europe. Arthur’s <br>goal is to turn all the island’s inhabitants into the living <br>dead and march with this army across the bottom of <br>the sea to the mainland.<br> ◆ Merlin will not reveal that he was the one who drove <br>Arthur mad by taking away his Virtues. He will say, <br>however, that Arthur’s old personality is kept in var -<br>ious objects hidden on the island as part of the spell <br>needed to seal the place under the sea. Retrieving them <br>and summoning their power in Arthur’s presence <br>will gradually bring him to his senses and weaken his <br>current tyrannical form. Facing Arthur without the <br>Virtues is an impossible challenge, and Merlin rec-<br>ommends finding at least three of them. From the in-<br>formation Merlin has gathered, it appears that Arthur <br>has no intention of leaving the castle, allowing plenty <br>of freedom for the search.<br> ◆ Merlin talks to the Hunters about 4 Virtues: Courage, <br>Faith, Innocence, and Love. The old wizard deliberately <br>omits mentioning Wisdom, as his secret goal is to re-<br>trieve it and escape from the island.<br> ◆ Camelot has been affected by the most powerful magic <br>ever cast: it has disrupted space and time, making this <br>place unique and sometimes maddening. The Hunters <br>must be prepared for anything and keep the inhabi-<br>tants in the dark about what has happened in the past. <br>Many villagers are unaware that they have been frozen <br>in time for hundreds of years, and causing panic would <br>only make the investigation more difficult.<br> ◆ Camelot is a land from a time when monsters and <br>magic were not hidden and feared by mankind, and <br>the Hunters must remember that.<br> ◆ Merlin gives the Hunters a small ocarina. When he <br>hears its sound, he will know that they need his help <br>and will manifest as soon as possible (see Gift - Wise <br>Advice, page 179).</p><p>179<br>Ambrose the Sorcerer known <br>as Old Merlin<br>Inspired by Merlin from the Arthurian Myth <br>(Neutral)<br>Descriptor: I am an ancient sorcerer, my body is weak, but <br>my magical power is unmatched.<br>1 Wound<br>Opposition Level: Hard 7<br>Agenda: Pretending to be a wise old man who is always <br>ready to help others with the proper advice / Gaining person-<br>al advantage by manipulating others.<br>Special Agenda (This Agenda replaces the one in <br>the Core Book): Recover the Virtue of Wisdom and flee so <br>that Arthur cannot come to his senses and the Hunters are <br>forced to eliminate him. <br>Gift - Ancient Sorcerer:  Merlin’s power is incredible, <br>achieving practically anything he can think of through the <br>use of magic. Those who rely on his advice will be able, once <br>per Session, to activate the magic power that the wizard has <br>infused within them. The magical effects must be decided <br>at the time that Merlin blesses the character by defining an <br>appropriate Descriptor such as: Taking flight like a bird or <br>Having skin as hard as a stone. Whoever carries Merlin’s <br>magic can activate its power once, obtaining the Descriptor <br>for the entire Scene. Once the Scene resolves the magic is <br>drained from the player and cannot be activated again.<br>Gift - Wise Advice: Merlin will never intervene person-<br>ally but can appear in a dream or vision to his protégés. <br>Once per Scenario, a Hunter can spend 1 Soma to summon <br>Merlin’s help. The sorcerer will appear with helpful infor-<br>mation or to bless the character with one of his spells.<br>How Merlin Acts in the Scenario<br>Merlin is the only NPC with an Agenda that advances re-<br>gardless of the Hunter’s actions. In general, the Storyteller <br>must move Merlin to maintain his facade as an ally who <br>will manifest when summoned. Merlin will also provide <br>information and support to the Hunters as long as they do <br>not interfere with his plans. The one thing Merlin always <br>leaves out is the location of Zone 13 - Lake (page 198), <br>where the Virtue of Wisdom can be retrieved. <br>The progression of Merlin’s actions will be as follows:<br>Scene One: Merlin is in Zone 1 - Landing (page 188), <br>briefing the Hunters on the island’s peculiarities.<br>Within  the  first  two  Interludes: Merlin will be in <br>Zone 13 - Lake (page 198) with his servant Mordred to <br>retrieve the Virtue of Wisdom (page 194).<br>By the third Interlude:  Merlin moves along the island <br>to get to Zone 15 - Secret Landing (page 199). <br>After the third Interlude: Merlin is on the boat in Zone <br>15 - Secret Landing (page 199), trying to find a cure for <br>the crew members.</p><p>180<br>Encounter Table<br>When Hunters arrive in a Zone, roll 1 die:<br>1-3: There are no Encounters, and normal exploration of <br>the Zone continues. <br>4-6: An Encounter occurs. Roll a die: if it comes up odd, <br>it is a Group Encounter; if it comes up even, it is a Single <br>Encounter. <br>All Encounter profiles are introduced from this page. En-<br>counters provide additional NPCs that connect with sto-<br>rylines already present in the Zones. The Storyteller freely <br>decides what kind of interaction is created between all the <br>elements of the Scene, evaluating the NPCs’ Agendas in re-<br>lation to the Zone in which they are encountered. In the <br>case of a repeated Encounter, the Storyteller must decide if <br>it is still interesting and useful for the narrative. If not, the <br>previous or next result in the table should be chosen. <br>Odd / Group Even / Single<br>1: Survivors of the First <br>Expedition<br>1: Sir Dagonet the Madman<br>2: Saxon Marauders 2: The Red Knight <br>3: Knights on a Quest 3: The Scarred Knight<br>4: Villagers 4: Merlin's Shadow<br>5: Restless Knights 5: Guinevere the Fugitive <br>6: Twrch Trwyth 6: Percival the Seeker <br>Survivors of the First Expedition<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are Crown agents on the run, terrified by <br>the danger of the island.<br>Agenda: To be able to escape from this cursed island.<br>Information: At each encounter, 1d6 Survivors will be <br>available to talk about an adjacent Zone from which they <br>are fleeing. The Storyteller decides what information the <br>Survivors have. When talking about the previous expedi-<br>tion, the Survivors will tell you that as soon as they docked <br>on the beach (Zone 2 - Beach page 188), the ship was at-<br>tacked by a huge creature that they describe as a collection <br>of different animals. The crew fled in all directions, scat-<br>tering across the island as the ship was destroyed. Captain <br>Boyce, who was in command of the ship, heroically stayed <br>behind to wrestle with the creature so that everyone could <br>escape.<br>Saxon Marauders<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are fierce marauders who have come to <br>Avalon to conquer the island. We are experts in group com-<br>bat and support each other. <br>Agenda: Attack and capture anyone we meet along the way.<br>Gift - Marauders: When attacking an enemy, Marauders <br>increase their OL by 1 if they have numerical superiority.</p><p>181<br>Information: There are 2d6 Saxon Marauders per En-<br>counter. They speak an ancient Germanic language that can <br>only be understood with a very specific Gift or Descriptor. <br>Upon closer inspection, it becomes clear that the Maraud-<br>ers are from a bygone era. When a group of Marauders is <br>eliminated, the Storyteller sets aside 1 Battle Token: these <br>Tokens reduce the danger in Zone 7 - Battlefield (page <br>193).<br>Knights on a Quest<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are knights in the service of Arthur, travel-<br>ing through Avalon on the orders of our king.<br>Agenda: Recruit every man and woman for the army that <br>will march to conquer the world. No one can refuse to enlist.<br>Information: 1d6 Knights will attempt to recruit any <br>NPC or Hunter present in the Zone, using force if neces-<br>sary. When a group of Knights is eliminated, the Story-<br>teller sets aside 1 Empty Seat Token: these Tokens reduce <br>the number of Knights present in Zone 8 - Camelot Castle <br>(page 193).<br>Villagers<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are poor villagers who sell vegetables and <br>livestock.<br>Agenda: Travel between island settlements to conduct busi-<br>ness.<br>Information: Upon encountering them, the Storyteller <br>rolls 1 die to determine which settlement the Villagers are <br>from. The table below lists the information they can give <br>the Hunters, and in parentheses, who can give the informa-<br>tion because they are from a particular settlement.</p><p>182<br>1-3: Village of Corrinton <br>4-6: Town of Stow<br> ◆ King Arthur has called for a general recruitment to <br>form an army to invade Europe. Many Villagers are <br>afraid to go to battle, but the Knights couldn’t care less <br>and take everyone by force. (Corrinton/Stow)<br> ◆ A fearsome creature has made its lair on the coast. It is <br>a huge monster, hungry for flesh. Knights once hunted <br>Twrch Trwyth, particularly tasty wild boars, and used <br>their meat to satisfy the monster’s hunger. (Corrinton)<br> ◆ Many Knights visit the settlements in search of queen <br>Guinevere, who is rumored to have fled the palace <br>without telling the king. Arthur is furious, and until <br>the queen is found, the war against Europe cannot be-<br>gin. (Corrinton/Stow)<br> ◆ Many people who do not want to go to war seek refuge <br>in the town of Stow, which is located in the farthest <br>part of the island from Camelot Castle. But it is only a <br>matter of time before the Knights arrive there as well. <br>(Stow)<br>Restless Knights<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are the souls of restless knights, resurrected <br>at the behest of our king. Our decaying bodies advance cease-<br>lessly, waiting to march to war. <br>Agenda: Kill all humans we come across to strengthen the <br>ranks of our king’s army. <br>Information: When encountered, the Storyteller rolls <br>2d6 to determine the number of Restless Knights. Their <br>horde attacks all living creatures, making no distinction be-<br>tween Hunters and NPCs. If the horde is not destroyed, it <br>moves one Zone by attacking those it encounters. The Sto-<br>ryteller secretly decides which Zone the horde has moved <br>to and does not make the Encounter roll when the Hunt-<br>ers arrive there. Any other damage done by the Peaceless <br>Knights is at the discretion of the Storyteller.<br>Twrch Trwyth <br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a strong and fast boar, I know every cor-<br>ner of the island and all the secret paths.<br>Agenda: Find food without getting caught.<br>Gift - Magic Boar: Whenever the Twrch Trwyth avoids <br>an action by someone who is hunting him, he gets 1 Es-<br>cape Token. As an action, and by spending 2 Escape To-<br>kens, the Twrch Trwyth can leave the Scene without any-<br>one being able to stop it. Even when dead, the body of the <br>Twrch Trwyth continues to give off an inviting scent and <br>glow with an intense magical light. Processing the Twrch <br>Trwyth’s flesh can yield 1 Delightful Flesh token. Whoever <br>consumes it will recover 1 Wound and 2 Soma.</p><p>183<br>Sir Dagonet the Madman<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor:  I am a crazy, violent knight and I will not hes-<br>itate to use my sword to get what I want. No one can afford <br>to ignore me.    <br>Agenda: Eliminate any possible threat to my king / Find <br>Guinevere, but instead of leading her back to Arthur, I plan <br>to kill her and pass off her death as a tragic accident.    <br>Gift - Don’t Underestimate the Buffoon: Dagonet is <br>a true master of foul play. During a battle, Dagonet can at-<br>tempt a low blow in addition to his action and choose one <br>of the following effects:<br>1. Blade in the Boot:  Dagonet draws it after attacking a <br>target and inflicts 1 Additional Wound. Only a Hunter with <br>a dueling ability Descriptor can make a Defense Check to <br>avoid it.<br>2. Sand in the Eyes: Activated before a Dagonet attack, <br>the target cannot use any of their Gifts during the Exchange.<br>3. Find a Shield: When Dagonet is attacked, he can avoid <br>1 Wound by having another closeby target hit instead. <br>Dagonet cannot use the same effect on the same target <br>more than once during the Scenario.<br>Information: Dagonet is a lunatic and will never reveal <br>what he knows, even if he is defeated or tortured. However, <br>being a true madman, it is possible to make him talk by <br>provoking him during combat. Dagonet is on a mission for <br>Arthur to find Guinevere, who has escaped from the castle. <br>The king has a soft spot for his queen and will not start the <br>war until she returns to his side. Dagonet also knows the <br>whereabouts of Percival, whom he now considers useless <br>to the cause. He has even tried to kill him, but one way or <br>another, the knight always comes back to life (Zone 12 - <br>Cliff, page 197).<br>The Red Knight<br>OL Hard 7 - Main NPC (4 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am an immortal spirit in a knight’s armor, <br>and with my skeletal steed I travel all over Avalon in search <br>of the one who killed me.<br>Agenda: Death has clouded my consciousness, and in every <br>person I meet I see my hated enemy, Percival. <br>Gift - Eternal Vengeance:  When Percival the Seeker <br>appears on the Scene, if he is present, the Red Knight will <br>attack, ignoring all other risks. If Percival is not present, <br>the Red Knight will see the face of the hated opponent in <br>the most skilled subject in combat among those present, <br>activating this Gift as well. As long as the Red Knight has <br>his target in sight, no effect can block or prevent him from <br>attacking. In the heat of vengeance, the Red Knight ignores <br>all other enemies and reduces his OL against them to Easy <br>3. <br>Information: The Red Knight is unable to communicate, <br>and the only words he utters are vengeful epithets direct-<br>ed at Percival the Seeker. If the Hunters eliminate the Red <br>Knight, he will not appear in Zone 12 - Cliff (page 197).</p><p>184<br>The Scarred Knight<br>OL Hard 7 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a former knight of the Round Table, dishon-<br>orably banished by my king for falling in love with his queen. <br>My fighting skills are unparalleled, and my face is completely <br>scarred as punishment for my sins.<br>Agenda: To find my beloved Guinevere and escape Avalon <br>with her.    <br>Information: The Scarred Knight is wandering in search <br>of his beloved Guinevere and will make himself available to <br>speak to the Hunters. The man will say that his beloved is <br>disguised as a common Villager, but can be recognized by the <br>feather-shaped brooch he gave her as a token of his love. The <br>Scarred Knight will not reveal his face or name, but he prom-<br>ises incredible riches to Hunters who help him. If a Hunter <br>has a Descriptor related to madness or understanding the be-<br>havior of others, they will clearly understand that the Scarred <br>Knight is insane, and an endless obsession burns in his eyes. <br>If the Hunters eliminate the Scarred Knight, he will not ap-<br>pear in Zone 11 - Town of Stow (page 197).<br> Merlin’s Shadow<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am the shadow of the mighty sorcerer Merlin, <br>and with my touch, I can freeze anything. I constantly receive <br>visions of what my former master is doing.    <br>Agenda: Kill the precious Hunters Merlin has sent as a way <br>of taking revenge on him for leaving me alone to guard Avalon. <br>Gift - Shadow Body:  In semi- or total darkness, Merlin’s <br>Shadow is considered OL Hard 7 when defending against an <br>attack or magic. The icy touch is capable of destroying living <br>creatures. Those who suffer 1 Wound from Merlin’s Shadow <br>receive 1 Consumption Token. The Wound tied to the Token <br>cannot be healed in any way. During an Interlude, a Hunter <br>can use the Recover 1 Wound option to discard 1 Consump-<br>tion Token instead of healing the Wound. <br>Information: Merlin’s Shadow cannot communicate with <br>words. When defeated, it drops the Tower Key, which can be <br>used in Zone 5 - Merlin’s Tower (page 190).</p><p>185<br>Guinevere the Fugitive<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am the queen of Camelot, and my good heart <br>is matched only by my beauty.<br>Agenda: To find a cure for the madness that has taken hold <br>of my beloved Arthur. <br>Gift - Virtue of Love: Imbued with the power of the Vir-<br>tue of Love, Guinevere cannot be killed: when she reaches <br>0 Wounds, she will fall into a state of apparent death, wak-<br>ing up fully healed at the end of the Scene. Guinevere will <br>give the power of her Virtue to those who show a sincere <br>interest in stopping Arthur’s madness: when this happens, <br>the Virtue transforms into a heart-shaped pendant. While <br>imbued with the power of Virtue, Guinevere cannot be de-<br>ceived in any way and will see everything for what it really <br>is, breaking all magic and deception.<br>Information: Guinevere poses as a common Villager, <br>though her noble features are hard to hide. Guinevere is <br>aware that Arthur has gone mad because he has lost his <br>Virtues. Indeed, the woman is seeking help and will not <br>hesitate to reveal herself to the Hunters if they prove trust-<br>worthy.</p><p>186<br>Percival the Seeker<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a disgraced knight. My body is immortal, <br>but my mind has lost bits of memory over the centuries. <br>Agenda: Remember why I am on this strange island. <br>Gift - Virtue of Faith: Imbued with the power of the Vir-<br>tue of Faith, Percival cannot be killed. When he reaches 0 <br>Wounds, he will fall into a state of apparent death and will <br>awake at the end of the Scene fully healed. Percival’s Virtue <br>cannot be granted because it is inside the Grail chalice that <br>the Knight remembers throwing between the rocks and <br>shoals in Zone 12 - Cliff (page 197).<br>Information: Percival only remembers things when he <br>is in his little house on the Cliff: he cycles back to Camelot, <br>but on the way he loses his memory and remembers only <br>the place he left from. Upon his return, Percival remembers <br>his mission and the cycle begins again.<br> <br>The Map of Camelot<br>Zone 1 - Landing Zone 2 - Beach Zone 3 - Glatisant's <br>Lair <br>Zone 4 - Village of <br>Corrinton<br>Zone 5 -Merlin’s <br>Tower<br>Zone 6 - Forest Zone 7 - Battlefield Zone 8 - Camelot <br>Castle Zone 9 - Fairy Falls Zone 10 - Circle of <br>Stones<br>Zone 11 - Town of <br>Stow Zone 12 - Cliff Zone 13 - Lake Zone 14 - Aban-<br>doned House<br>Zone 15 - Secret <br>Landing</p><p>187<br>The Map of Camelot<br>N</p><p>188<br>Zone 1 – Landing <br>Description: The disembarkation point for the Hunters <br>expedition, where all the sailors are guarding the two ships <br>that have arrived on the island.    <br>Information: The sailors are led by Captain Bennett, <br>who is always attentive to the Hunter’s needs. The crew is <br>unwilling to leave their ship for any reason other than to <br>recover survivors from the First Expedition.<br>Note: In this Zone, you never roll on the Encounter Table.<br>Zone 2 – Beach <br>Description: A large Beach filled with ruins of what were <br>once fishermen’s homes. The wreck of the Wavecrest (the <br>ship of the First Expedition) is surrounded by the mangled <br>bodies of torn sailors.    <br>Information: Investigating near the wreck, it will be easy <br>to notice the footprints of a huge creature, and the damage <br>done to the ship also seems to indicate an unequal battle <br>between a monster and a ship of unfortunate men. Going <br>deeper into the wreck, it is possible to find Captain Boyce’s <br>diary. However, there is a risk of falling overboard because <br>of the rotten wooden planks.<br>Threat – Rotten Wreck<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: Rotten wood can give way even under light <br>weight. <br>Gift - Splinters and Scrap: If a Defense Check fails, the <br>target falls overboard and suffers 1 Wound, and the Sto-<br>ryteller gets 1 Wreck Token. When the number of Wreck <br>Tokens reaches 3, the ship collapses in on itself, burying <br>everything inside.<br>Hidden among diary pages filled with uninteresting travel <br>notes are entries about the island.<br>Note 1: Boyce followed the creature that destroyed his ship <br>and discovered that its lair was east of the beach. <br>Note 2: With a group of trusted sailors, Boyce headed to the <br>castle that towers in the center of the island in search of help. <br>Note 3: The only survivor of the journey to the castle, Boyce <br>writes in shaky handwriting, asking God’s forgiveness for his <br>sins and for the companions he had to leave behind to escape.<br>Note 4: A knight in strange red armor roams the beach. Now <br>lonely and desperate, Boyce decides to try his best to get his <br>attention.</p><p>189<br>Zone 3 – Glatisant’s <br>Lair<br>Description: A wide expanse of rocks and bushes stretch-<br>es as far as the eye can see. The terrain drops sharply, lead-<br>ing to what appears to be a chasm. An old and worn sign <br>warns, “Steer clear, lair of Glatisant the Beast. ” <br>Information: At the bottom of the chasm lies Glatisant, a <br>giant flesh-eating monster. When potential prey approach-<br>es the chasm, the Storyteller rolls a die:<br>1-3: Glatisant is dormant. If someone descends into the <br>lair, a Defense Check is required to prevent the beast from <br>waking.    <br>4-6: Glatisant awakens in hunger. Pretending to be asleep, <br>it waits for prey to approach the edge of the chasm, then <br>leaps out and devours it. <br>Glatisant <br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (6 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a giant snake-headed monster with a de-<br>formed body, the result of the union of more than ten different <br>animals. I have an insatiable appetite for flesh.<br>Agenda: I devour every delicious human I meet, though my <br>favorite prey is the tasty Twrch Trwyth.<br>Gift - Monstrous Abomination:  Glatisant can act 2 <br>times during an Exchange, but not back to back. Its long <br>neck allows it to snatch prey up to thirty feet away, and <br>when it moves, it can make great leaps, ignoring enemies <br>and terrain in its path. Glatisant is obsessed with the flesh of <br>the Twrch Trwyth and, if given the opportunity, will spend <br>the entire Exchange devouring it, ignoring even potential <br>enemies.<br>Gift - Virtue of Courage: Glatisant unknowingly carries <br>the Virtue of Courage, encased in a sword embedded in his <br>right side. Defeating the beast will allow the Hunters to re-<br>cover the power of Courage. <br>Zone 4 – Village of <br>Corrinton <br>Description: A fishing village buzzing with activity. The <br>people are friendly and hospitable, though it is clear from <br>their faces that something is troubling the community. <br>Information: Chatting with the locals is another way to <br>get the information revealed in the Encounter with the Vil-<br>lagers (page 181). At the explicit request of the Hunters, <br>some fishermen will take them by boat along the coast but <br>will ask for payment. This arrangement allows the Hunters <br>to choose any coastal Zone as their destination (i.e., all ex-<br>cept 7, 8, and 9). Unless special arrangements are made, the <br>fishermen are in a hurry to return to their activities, and <br>once they have unloaded the Hunters, they will not wait for <br>them to return.</p><p>190<br>Zone 5 – Merlin’s <br>Tower <br>Description: An old, seemingly abandoned tower stands <br>on a headland overlooking the sea. The building appears to <br>have no windows, and the only entrance is an old wooden <br>door engraved with strange runes. <br>Information: If the Hunters have not removed Merlin’s <br>Shadow, the Storyteller rolls a die.<br>1-3: Merlin’s Shadow is not in the Tower, but if someone <br>opens the door, it will be there within half an hour to drive <br>out any intruders. <br>4-6: Merlin’s Shadow is in the Tower, and if anyone forces <br>the door open, it will attack without hesitation. <br>If the Hunters have not retrieved the Tower Key from Mer-<br>lin’s Shadow, any attempt to open the door will unleash the <br>power of the Haunted Door. <br>Threat – Haunted Door<br>OL Hard 7<br>Descriptor: A creaking old door imbued with all of Merlin’s <br>magical power.<br>Gift - Away with the Harassers:  Attempting to open <br>the door without the Tower Key triggers the magical effects <br>below. If the Defense Check fails, the Storyteller rolls a die <br>to determine the consequences. <br>1-2: Loses all remaining Soma.<br>3-4: Suffers 2 Wounds. <br>5-6: Ends with the whole group in another Zone. <br>Inside the Tower, the Hunters will find all manner of mag-<br>ical devilry, as well as clear evidence in books and scrolls <br>that the place belongs to a Sorcerer named Merlin. With <br>time, the Hunters can uncover Merlin’s diary and, at the <br>Storyteller’s discretion, a Treasure of the Order.<br>The diary is mostly written in an incomprehensible lan-<br>guage, but there are notes written in red ink that are in <br>common English.<br>Note 1: An overly righteous and beloved king is more danger-<br>ous than the worst of tyrants, for when raising a hand against <br>him an entire people will rise to shield him.<br>Note 2: Virtue is like a weed, it grows despite all efforts to <br>pull it up.<br>Note 3: It may not be handy, but the bottom of a lake is al-<br>ways a good place to hide. <br>Note 4: White beach, safe harbor.</p><p>191<br>Zone 6 – Forest<br>Description: An intricate Forest stretches in all directions <br>and a light layer of fog that seems to have no regard for the <br>weather or the time of day envelops everything. An unnat-<br>ural silence hangs in the air, broken only by the cries of a <br>few animals.<br>Information: Traversing the Forest without getting lost <br>takes time and skill. While exploring the Forest, Hunters <br>can find two locations: the Magic Glade and the Green Gar-<br>den.<br>Threat – Intricate Maze<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: The great forest of Camelot is a tangle of vege-<br>tation perpetually shrouded in mist.<br>In case of Failure, the Storyteller decides which Zone the <br>Hunters will land in.<br>The Magic Glade<br>Descriptor: A small clearing within a circle formed by an-<br>cient oaks. Inside, one can clearly feel the magic hovering in <br>the air, tickling the skin.<br>Gift - Place of Peace and Magic:  The Magic Glade is <br>a place of peace and serenity. Those who rest in it for a few <br>minutes recover 1 Soma. The same subject cannot bene-<br>fit from this effect more than once per Scene. Invoking an <br>Interlude within the Magic Glade does not generate an ad-<br>vancement in Merlin’s Agenda. <br>The Green Garden<br>Descriptor: A lush field of flowers, in the center of which <br>stands a small stone altar engraved with pagan symbols. <br>Information: As soon as a subject enters the flowery <br>field, a figure covered in ancient armor and foliage stands <br>threateningly. The Green Knight will never leave the flower <br>field, remaining to defend the altar. The only way to avoid <br>the wrath of the Green Knight is to show respect to the an-<br>cient gods. By eliminating the Green Knight, the Hunters <br>can get their hands on the Treasure of the Order, the Ax of <br>Retribution (page 192). <br>The Green Knight<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am the spirit of a knight sworn to protect the <br>ancient cults. My armor is old now, but the plants and flow-<br>ers that have grown on it protect me. With my big ax, I can <br>chop off a head with ease. <br>Agenda: Protect the altar and allow those who worship the <br>old gods to have a place to worship. <br>Gift - The Just Punishment:  The Green Knight starts <br>each Scene with 3 Retaliation Tokens, each time he suffers <br>1 Wound he can spend 1 Token to inflict 1 Wound on who-<br>ever hit him.</p><p>192<br>The Ax of Retribution<br>Inspired by the Green Knight of the Arthurian <br>Myth<br>Once upon a time, there was a knight who had made justice <br>his calling. He was respected by all the commoners and had <br>married a beautiful princess with whom he shared a rich and <br>prosperous life. The knight had not always been upright in <br>spirit. In the past, he had often fallen into excesses of anger <br>and jealousy, even to the point of staining his hands with <br>blood. These lower instincts were appeased by a magical ax <br>the knight had taken from a fallen enemy. The ax accumulat-<br>ed all the negative thoughts of the wielder, transforming him <br>into a person filled with righteous thoughts. But as is often <br>the case, man is not really capable of changing his nature. <br>Despite the magical power of the ax, the knight’s thoughts be-<br>came dark. Convinced that his wife was cheating on him, the <br>knight invited a companion to his court and then pretended <br>to go on a quest, while actually hiding within the castle walls <br>to spy on them. A week passed in which absolutely nothing <br>happened, while the princess and her guest chatted amiably <br>about the knight’s qualities. Blinded by guilt, the knight came <br>to court and told his wife and trusted companion everything. <br>He cried tears of remorse, but only the ax, at the height of the <br>magical power that gave it life, sensed the lie in the Green <br>Knight’s words. To the amazement of all present, the weapon <br>came to life and decapitated him with a single blow, unleash-<br>ing all the anger and envy it had accumulated over the years. <br>Ironically, the widow, saddened by her beloved’s untimely de-<br>parture, found solace in his trusted comrade-in-arms. When <br>the mourning was over, they married and began a long and <br>successful dynasty. <br>Keywords: Trust / Punishment / Retaliation / Sense of <br>honor / Beheading / Masterstroke.<br>Gift - Scales of Justice: The Ax of Retribution protects <br>those who wield it from negative thoughts and punishes <br>those who behave spitefully. At the beginning of each Sce-<br>nario, the Ax contains 3 Retaliation Tokens. The wielder <br>can spend 1 Token to activate one of the following effects:<br>1: Get 2 Additional Successes on a Defense Check against <br>mind manipulation effects.<br>2: Once per Scenario, decapitate a target that suffers 1 <br>Wound from the Ax. This effect immediately reduces any <br>remaining Wounds to zero, but only applies to those who <br>are truly evil, with the Storyteller having the final say. If the <br>target of this effect is not evil, it is the Hunter wielding the <br>Ax who takes the Wound in retaliation.<br>3: Give 1 Additional Success to an ally’s action, but only if <br>the goal is to reveal a truth or punish a villain. <br>Once per Scene, if the wielder succeeds in changing an <br>NPC’s attitude from aggressive to cooperative without re-<br>sorting to violence, the Ax produces 1 Retaliation Token.</p><p>193<br>Zone 7 – Battlefield <br>Description: A vast wasteland littered with corpses. War-<br>riors in armor bearing the crest of Camelot mingle with the <br>bodies of skin-painted barbarians. The stench of death and <br>destruction is everywhere, while distinctly Germanic cries <br>come from an encampment in the center of the Battlefield.<br>Information: The remnants of the Saxon army that in-<br>vaded Camelot are in the camp, ready to celebrate their <br>victory over the Camelot army. There are a total of 30 Sax-<br>on Marauders (page 180), but for every Battle Token the <br>Hunters have accumulated, the number drops by 5. Un-<br>aware that they have landed in a future era not their own, <br>the Marauders plan to march on Camelot Castle. Tied to a <br>post in the middle of the camp is an old, dying knight. He <br>is Uther Pendragon, Arthur’s father, who was at the head of <br>the defending army. The Saxons are torturing him, trying to <br>extract information. <br>Uther Pendragon<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (0 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am an experienced knight and a great strate-<br>gist. I am too old for war now, but that will not stop me from <br>saving my kingdom.<br>Agenda: Protect Camelot and bring Arthur to his senses so <br>that he can once again be a worthy ruler of these lands. <br>Information: Uther is dying, and even if he is saved, it <br>will be clear that his injuries are fatal. Before he breathes <br>his last, however, the old man will reveal important details <br>to the Hunters.<br> ◆ Arthur was always a good ruler, as long as Merlin re-<br>mained at his side as an advisor. Uther, however, could <br>always see envy in the Sorcerer’s eyes, envy for the <br>young king that was his protégé. When Merlin sudden-<br>ly disappeared, Arthur went mad and lost all the traits <br>that made him a righteous and benevolent man.<br> ◆ In the southeast, past the great Lake, lies an old Aban-<br>doned House. Arthur spent his childhood there, and <br>Uther is convinced that the spirit of all that is good in <br>his son’s heart dwells there.<br> ◆ There is a secret passage to enter the Camelot Castle. It <br>is located inside a large oak tree that has been struck by <br>lightning. From there, an underground tunnel leads to <br>the hall of the Round Table. <br>Zone 8 – Camelot Castle<br>Description: Camelot Castle appears to be an ancient <br>abandoned ruin, with only the cackling of soldiers prepar-<br>ing for war revealing that it is still inhabited. Knights and <br>villagers alike are busy crafting weapons and war machines. <br>Information: Arthur is in the hall of the Round Table, <br>where he sits with his most trusted Knights. There are thir-<br>teen seats in total, one is occupied by Arthur, and one is <br>empty as it belongs to Merlin. There are then eleven more <br>Knights (page 181), but for every Empty Seat Token that <br>the Hunters have collected, the number is reduced by one. <br>Without his Virtues, Arthur is an invading madman whose <br>goal is the conquest of Europe, second only to finding his <br>beloved Guinevere. Arthur’s behavior is greatly influenced <br>by finding the Virtue of Wisdom (page 194).</p><p>194<br>Arthur<br>OL Hard 7 - Main NPC (6 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am the king of Camelot, and my word is law. <br>Thanks to the power of the Grail, my body is immortal and I <br>possess abilities far beyond those of ordinary men.<br>Agenda: Bring back my bride, Guinevere, to rule all of Eu-<br>rope by my side / Prepare the army for battle and make all my <br>subjects immortal warriors. <br>Gift - The True Power of the Grail:  Arthur is immor-<br>tal, which means that any Wounds inflicted on him will <br>heal immediately. Arthur can act up to 3 times in an Ex-<br>change, but not back to back.<br>Gift - Merlin’s Curse: Deprived of the Virtues by Mer-<br>lin’s magic, Arthur has become a mad and powerful being <br>who has abandoned his humanity. Activating the power of <br>the Virtues awakens the king’s true soul, making him more <br>human. Each Virtue consumed in front of Arthur will have <br>the following effect:<br>Love: Lower his OL by 2.<br>Innocence: Lower the number of Wounds by 3. <br>Faith: He loses his immortality and, if brought to 0 <br>Wounds, is permanently killed. <br>Courage: Acts only 1 time per Exchange. <br>Wisdom: He regains his wits and realizes that what he is <br>doing is wrong. Arthur’s Agenda changes to: Lead my king-<br>dom to peace by finding a place in this new world.</p><p>195<br>Zone 9 – Fairy Falls<br>Description: A small wooded area hides a series of natu-<br>ral waterfalls. A keen eye might catch a glimpse of female <br>figures dancing gracefully on the water.<br>Information: There are 6 Fairies who will welcome any-<br>one who arrives with smiles and dancing. The Fairies do <br>not hesitate to reveal what they know, engaging guests in <br>a long talk.<br>Fairies<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPCs (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are fairies and we love company and good <br>stories. We like humans, even though they tend to age too fast <br>by our standards.    <br>Agenda: Entertain nice people for as long as possible.    <br>Gift - A Midsummer Night’s Dream: Talking to Fair-<br>ies for a long time can be fatal for a human, as time passes <br>faster in their presence. After a minute of conversation, the <br>subject can make a Defense Check to see if they are getting <br>old. If successful, the subject can end the conversation. If <br>unsuccessful, the subject loses 2 Soma, and if the subject is <br>already at 0 Soma, the subject loses 1 Wound. Succeeding <br>with a Cost is possible, but the easiest way to interrupt the <br>effect of the Gift is to feel pain, so the Cost will always be <br>1 Wound. A new Check can be made after each minute of <br>conversation. An outside party may attempt to break the ef-<br>fect of this Gift with words (Position Check) or by inflicting <br>1 Wound (Automatic).<br>Fairy information:<br> ◆ They come from the great lake where the house once <br>stood, the home of the Lady who cared for all the mag-<br>ical creatures on the island. The Lady then decided <br>to leave, fed up with the many brave young men who <br>came to the lake, insistent on gaining her blessing.<br> ◆ The Fairies have always stayed to guard the Lake, but <br>on the day the Hunters arrived, a grumpy old man who <br>clearly looked like a Sorcerer appeared at the lake ac-<br>companied by a huge knight in armor as black as night. <br>The old man frightened off the Fairies, who, peering <br>from a distance, clearly saw the two of them walking <br>along the shores of the Lake, searching for something.<br> ◆ The island contains many illusions that prevent ordi-<br>nary mortals from discovering certain truths. The Fair-<br>ies possess a Fairy Crystal that allows those who look <br>through it to see the illusions. They are willing to give <br>up the Crystal, but only in exchange for something of <br>equal value. If the Hunters do not know what to pro-<br>pose, the Fairies will say that a beautiful treasure is <br>guarded by a Knight in the Forest to the east.</p><p>196<br>Scenario Gift - Fairy Crystal<br>Requirement: Receive the Crystal as a gift from the Fair-<br>ies. (No need to spend XP)<br>Thanks to the power of the Crystal, you can see beyond il-<br>lusions and receive 3 Sight Tokens. Y ou can spend 1 Token <br>and look through the Crystal to reveal an illusion, a dis-<br>guise, or the effect of magic that makes something appear <br>different than it really is. When you spend the last Token, <br>the Crystal shatters and you lose the effect of this Gift. <br> <br>Zone 10 – Circle of <br>Stones<br>Description: Huge megalithic stones are arranged in a <br>circle at the top of a low hill. The aura of ancient power is <br>easily felt even by those unfamiliar with magic. <br>Information: Inside the large stones are a series of small-<br>er stones that replicate the shape of the island. A person <br>with a Descriptor related to magic can decipher the code <br>of the stones and understand that the Circle is a system for <br>magically moving from one place to another. Naming a <br>Zone with the correct code will immediately transport ev-<br>erybody in the Circle there, but travel is only one-way and <br>can’t be used to return to the Circle of Stones. Using the <br>Fairy Crystal allows one to understand the workings of the <br>Circle, even if the person looking at it does not understand <br>magic.<br>Threat – Magic Menhirs<br>OL Hard 7<br>Descriptor: A circle of ancient stones laid at the dawn of <br>time. <br>Gift - Magical Journey:  Activating the power of the <br>stones is easy, but getting exactly where you want to go is <br>much less so. The journey requires a Position Check: with a <br>single roll, the person activating the power can take all ob-<br>jects within the Circle with them. Depending on the result <br>of the Check, different effects are achieved.<br>Failure: Successful journey but the wrong destination. <br>The Storyteller chooses the arrival Zone from among those <br>adjacent to the original destination. <br>Outcome with a Cost: Successful journey but with some <br>interference. Each subject loses 1 Equipment decided by <br>the Storyteller. The missing Equipment has been transport-<br>ed in a Zone adjacent to the one of arrival.<br>Standard Outcome: Successful trip, no problems. <br>Outcome with an Increment:  Complimentary pan-<br>oramic view. Before arriving, travelers can observe the <br>destination while lingering safely in the astral dimension <br>they have traveled through. The Storyteller will reveal some <br>information about the Zone.</p><p>197<br>Zone 11 – Town of Stow  <br>Description: A small farming town. The people are <br>friendly and hospitable, though you can see in their faces <br>that the shadow of war hangs over their lives. The streets <br>are also filled with outsiders looking for work and a place <br>to sleep. <br>Information: By chatting with villagers, it is possible to <br>obtain the information provided in the Villagers Encounter <br>(page 181). <br>If the Hunters have not already met Guinevere (page 185), <br>the queen will be in Stow, where she has been hired as a <br>handmaiden to hide her true identity. When Guinevere re-<br>alizes that the Hunters are on the island to stop Arthur, she <br>will present herself to them and ask for help. <br>If the Hunters have not already eliminated the Scarred <br>Knight (page 184), he will come to Stow in search of his <br>beloved. <br>Zone 12 – Cliff <br>Description: An impassable overhanging Cliff with the <br>sea crashing against it. The Cliff rises on a small promonto-<br>ry, on the top of which a small house can be seen. <br>Information: If the Hunters have not already encoun-<br>tered Percival the Seeker (page 186), they will find him in <br>the house, cooking fish and recuperating.<br>If the Hunters have not already eliminated the Red Knight <br>(page 183), he will appear to confront Percival.<br>Interacting with the confused Seeker can provide you <br>with relevant information and the story of how he threw <br>the Holy Grail into the sea to awaken Arthur. Percival will <br>lead the Hunters to the Cliff where the current carried the <br>cup after the island emerged. The Grail now lies embedded <br>ninety feet below. <br>Threat – The Sacred Cup Among the <br>Rocks<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: A steep cliff overlooking the sea that hides the <br>cup of the Holy Grail in its rocks. <br>Note: Getting to the cup requires moving along the slip-<br>pery, pointy rocks as the sea crashes relentlessly.    Retriev-<br>ing the embedded cup requires breaking the rock or find-<br>ing a way to slide it out.</p><p>198<br>Zone 13 – Lake<br>Description: A large Lake surrounded by dense vegeta-<br>tion. There seems to be no human settlement. A few boats <br>lie abandoned on the shore, victims of time and weather. <br>Information: In this Zone, the initial situation changes <br>according to the number of Interludes the Hunters have <br>called before their arrival.<br>Up to Two Interludes: Walking along the shore, Merlin <br>can be seen coordinating Mordred’s search for the Virtue. <br>The Knight walks until he disappears into the water, only <br>to reappear a short time later with some muddy objects. <br>Merlin sorts out what his servant has recovered and, with a <br>displeased expression, orders him to continue. The Virtue <br>of Wisdom is in the form of a Crown. Once retrieved, Mer-<br>lin instructs Mordred to wait for him at the bottom of the <br>lake and then he leaves, abandoning his servant.<br>Three or more Interludes: Merlin has already rescued <br>the Virtue and made his way to the Zone 15 - Secret Land-<br>ing (page 199). Hovering on the shore and looking into <br>the Lake, it’s possible to see a motionless suit of armor un-<br>derwater. If the Hunters attempt to interact with Mordred, <br>he will awaken to eliminate any newcomers.<br>Mordred the Peaceless<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (4 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am an undead knight in the service of the evil <br>Merlin. I do whatever my master tells me to do, though I only <br>wish to return to the grave from which I was torn.    <br>Agenda (if Merlin is present):  Obey my master’s or-<br>ders.<br>Agenda (if Merlin is not present):  Eliminate anyone <br>who approaches the waters of the lake, as ordered by my mas-<br>ter / Be destroyed and return to death, receiving a farewell <br>prayer. <br>Information: Mordred can be persuaded to surrender in <br>exchange for the promise of a burial that will bring peace <br>to his soul. If peace is granted, Mordred will reveal Merlin’s <br>plans for why he wants the Virtue of Wisdom and the Se-<br>cret Landing.</p><p>199<br>Zone 14 – Abandoned <br>House <br>Description: A dilapidated cottage sits in the middle of a <br>flat area. Cultivated fields once stretched in every direction, <br>but now only ruins and sun-browned earth remain. <br>Information: The House appears to be in ruins and long <br>abandoned, but with careful investigation, you will notice <br>a trapdoor in the floor. Opening the trapdoor will lead you <br>to the basement, where old clothes and farming tools are <br>piled high. Searching through the junk, the Hunters will <br>find a small wooden crucifix that seems untouched by time. <br>Once picked up, it will reveal its power as the Virtue of In-<br>nocence.<br>Zone 15 – Secret Landing <br>Description: On the surface, this place looks like a quiet <br>beach. The pale coloring of the sand makes it look almost <br>like an expanse of white snow. Merlin’s personal ship waits <br>about 30 yards from the shore, but it cannot be seen be-<br>cause it is hidden by an illusion cast by the Sorcerer.<br>Information: In this Zone, the initial situation changes <br>according to the number of Interludes the Hunters have <br>called before their arrival.<br>Up to Two Interludes:  On the ship, Captain Edgers <br>awaits Merlin’s arrival. <br>Three Interludes: The situation is the same as in the <br>first option, but Merlin has regained the Virtue of Wisdom <br>and will arrive at the beach shortly. If the Hunters wait, they <br>can catch him off guard.    <br>Four Interludes: Merlin has returned to the ship and <br>preparations for departure are in full swing. Unfortunately, <br>part of the crew has contracted a strange disease that makes <br>it difficult for Captain Edgers to control the ship. Merlin, <br>amidst a thousand curses, does his best to create a cure.<br>Threat – Illusory Panorama<br>OL Hard 7<br>Descriptor: A false image that adapts to weather condi-<br>tions. Small, repetitive details are the only sign that some-<br>thing is wrong, such as a flock of seagulls flying following a <br>cyclic trajectory and clouds that seem stuck in the same po-<br>sition.</p>"},"sort":100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513743954,"modifiedTime":1781513743954,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}],"folder":null,"flags":{"broken-tales":{"adventureSlug":"the-kings-awakening","collection":"Lost Stories","sourceFile":"bt-ls-book-1-ENG-SCREEN.pdf","pages":"175-200"}},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513743954,"modifiedTime":1781513743954,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}
{"_id":"k1Dbrd0Ac2a6kBts","name":"Nikola's Pledge","pages":[{"_id":"eijqbaYPnKCv5ZdR","name":"Summary","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h1>Nikola's Pledge</h1><p><strong>Collection:</strong> Lost Stories</p><p><strong>Source:</strong> bt-ls-book-1-ENG-SCREEN.pdf, pages 115-130.</p><p><img src=\"systems/broken-tales/assets/adventures/maps/nikolas-pledge-p115-full.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto;\" /></p>"},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513739249,"modifiedTime":1781513739249,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"JUAKMrJbTbxpBuTm","name":"Setup","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>Nikola's Pledge - Setup</h2><p>114<br>Nikola’s Pledge<br> <br>A Scenario inspired by the story of Santa Claus<br> <br>Safety Keywords: Kidnapping / Gore / Manipulation<br> <br>Once upon a time...<br>The Hunters arrive in the far north, in the village of Rovaniemi, summoned by a letter from a young <br>couple, Tommi and Jutta, who have recently arrived there. As described in the letter, the community of <br>prospectors who founded the village has always been supported by a wealthy craftsman named Nikola <br>Lupei. After years of apparent tranquility, Nikola has begun asking for a pledge and donation in return <br>for his patronage. Gold and valuables can be given as gifts, which each family must leave at their door on <br>the night of December 24 as a token of gratitude. At the first request, however, some ignored the demand. <br>The next morning, they each discovered that one of their loved ones was missing. <br>No one believed it was a coincidence. The furious village elders went to Nikola to make him answer for <br>his actions, only to return and declare that the craftsman was in no way connected to the disappearances. <br>From that moment on, however, the villagers accepted the tribute had to be paid, and no one disappeared <br>anymore. Tommi and Jutta ask the Order for help, because they fear for the life of little Lari, their eldest <br>son, since December 24th is approaching and they have nothing to pay for their own tribute. The Hunters <br>then arrive in the remote village of gold prospectors, on the edge of civilization, knowing that they are the <br>only link between the law of the civilized world and the harsh rules of the cold north...</p><p>115<br>The story that led us here...<br>Nikola Lupei was born and raised in the comfort <br>of a noble family in Walachia. Always in poor health, but <br>extremely intelligent, Nikola devoted himself to the study <br>of esoteric arts from an early age. After years of research, <br>Nikola found a mysterious patron willing to support him <br>and moved into the old man’s mansion to study his im-<br>mense collection of books. The old man later revealed <br>himself to be an ancient vampire and passed his curse <br>on to Nikola one bloody night. Rejuvenated in body but <br>tired in mind, Nikola fled Wallachia in search of a safe <br>place to live in peace and quiet. The Village of Rovaniemi <br>turned out to be just right, far from civilization and with <br>needy families looking for help to build their prospecting <br>community. Using his powers, Nikola allowed the village <br>to flourish. In his mansion, he built a workshop where <br>he could devote himself to making toys, a great passion <br>of his since childhood. Safe from prying eyes, Nikola has <br>always kept his vampirism hidden, feeding on the many <br>animals in the forest around Rovaniemi. Three years ago, <br>however, things changed drastically: while on a quest <br>for magical artifacts, Nikola came into possession of the <br>Badalisk, a powerful bag-shaped creature. The Badalisk, <br>cornering Nikola, forced the vampire to feed him pieces <br>of his body. But animal blood is less powerful than hu-<br>man blood, so Nikola’s body could not regenerate quick-<br>ly enough to feed the Badalisk. Desperate, Nikola began <br>to demand a pledge of valuables from the people of Ro-<br>vaniemi, knowing that many would find it difficult to pay. <br>With that justification, Nikola used his powers to infil-<br>trate the homes of those unable to pay tribute, kidnapping <br>a family member and making them his servants through <br>the Rite of Servitude. His new servants helped Nikola kid-<br>nap poor travelers passing through. Thanks to the riches he <br>accumulated from the tribute, he lured wealthy merchants <br>seeking good deals to the village. All the innocent souls <br>went to feed to the insatiable Badalisk...<br>The story at the arrival of the <br>Hunters...<br>As it feeds, the Badalisk becomes more powerful and its <br>hunger grows month by month. Desperate, Nikola tries <br>every possible way to satiate the demon and preserve the <br>lives of the villagers of Rovaniemi. Every night, the vampire <br>meets with Asmo, one of the Village Elders, who keeps him <br>informed of events. Thanks to Asmo, Nikola learned of the <br>arrival of the Order’s first Hunter and sent his reindeer to <br>hunt them down. After a long battle, the Hunter has taken <br>refuge in the old hunting lodge east of the Village and is <br>waiting for reinforcements. Nikola plans to eliminate the <br>Hunter himself, convinced that a subject of such power <br>would sate the Badalisk for a long time.<br>Note: In this Scenario, a Hunter from the Order has al-<br>ready been sent out before the Players’ group arrives. The <br>Storyteller is free to choose which Hunter this is, to best fit <br>with their Campaign. The Hunter is effectively an NPC un-<br>der the Storyteller’s control. The choice of Hunter can affect <br>the events of the Scenario and create interesting situations. <br>For example, if it is the Immortal, the Hunters may find <br>only his head in the hut, while the body is scattered in the <br>forest, torn apart by the Reindeer. Retrieving the body parts <br>would then become an interesting situation to play out.</p><p>116<br>Note: In this Scenario, the Badalisk has eaten a Treasure of <br>the Order, providing it a source of great power. The Story-<br>teller must decide which Treasure it is, fitting it into their <br>Campaign. If the Scenario is solved successfully, the Hunt-<br>ers will be able to retrieve it.</p>"},"sort":50000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513739250,"modifiedTime":1781513739250,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"itFYZ2VFn5YeM47k","name":"Scene 1","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>Nikola's Pledge - Scene 1</h2><p>First Scene<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  The sun is setting as you <br>finally see smoke billowing from the chimneys of the small <br>town of Rovaniemi. After more than a week of traveling <br>through impassable forests and snow-covered plains, you <br>can’t wait to shed your heavy coats and warm yourself by a <br>fire. Instead, you are greeted by locked doors and suspicious <br>looks from behind windows. It seems that you are not wel-<br>come in the village. A voice attracts your attention, a young <br>man beckons you to his house and when you approach he <br>introduces himself as Tommi, the one who sent the letter to <br>the Order with his wife Jutta. <br>Place: Tommi and Jutta’s little house. <br>Time: The sun is setting as the icy wind bangs on closed <br>windows, announcing the arrival of another snowstorm.<br>Initial Situation: The hosts thank the Hunters for com-<br>ing to their rescue, while Tommi rekindles the fireplace, <br>where a pot of tempting stew is simmering. A loving Jutta <br>cradles a baby sleeping peacefully in her arms.<br>Information: From the interview with Tommi and Jutta, <br>the Hunters can get a lot of information.<br> ◆ Nikola Lupei is considered the most important man in <br>the area. He lives in a large mansion a day’s walk from <br>Rovaniemi and is known as a benefactor who has con-<br>tributed to the growth of the Village. Lupei is a very ec-<br>centric individual who always wears an eye-catching red <br>robe with large slippers to match. He has an emaciated, <br>pale face with the large dark circles of someone who <br>never seems to sleep well. Despite his ghostly appear -<br>ance, he is a gentle man who is always kind to everyone.<br> ◆ The Village is run by a group of six elders who meet in <br>the small town hall during the day. The elders talked to <br>Nikola after the first night of the pledge, but after the <br>meeting they kept a mysterious silence, urging everyone <br>to pay the pledge without fuss. In their opinion, Nikola <br>had nothing to do with the disappearances.    <br> ◆ After the first pledge, the Village always paid, even at <br>great sacrifice. Coincidentally, no one else has disap-<br>peared since then.    <br> ◆ A week ago, a Hunter from the Order arrived in the Vil-<br>lage. Tommi and Jutta met them briefly, but the next day <br>the Hunter left for Nikola’s estate, never to return. Jutta <br>overheard a discussion among the elders and is sure that <br>the Hunter received information from one of them, but <br>she could not say who. Tommi and Jutta can describe <br>the Hunter in broad strokes, given their short meeting.<br> ◆ Tommi and Jutta can describe all six elders, giving their <br>names and the most common information from their <br>Descriptors.<br> ◆ Today is December 15th, so there are only nine days left <br>until the next pledge payment.</p><p>117<br>Tommi and Jutta<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPCs (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are two young prospectors, made tough by <br>a life of hardship and strong by the love that unites us.<br>Agenda: To save our son Lari from that absurd pledge.<br>The Village of Rovaniemi<br>Descriptor: A small town of prospectors where everyone <br>knows everyone else.<br>Information: The streets and the small square are littered <br>with gold panning equipment, carts, and baskets for sort-<br>ing. The numerous wrought-iron plaques remind everyone <br>that these are all donations from Nikola Lupei. The villagers <br>are shy towards the Hunters, avoiding any contact. <br>Rovaniemi Town Hall<br>Descriptor: One of the few brick houses in the village. The <br>imposing wrought iron door has a large plaque engraved with <br>words of gratitude for the town’s benefactor, Nikola Lupei.<br>Whenever the Hunters visit the Town Hall, they will find 2 <br>Village Elders. The Storyteller can decide which ones they <br>are, or roll a die to determine. The following information <br>can be obtained from all elders:<br> ◆ A week ago, a Hunter from the Order arrived, asked <br>a few questions, then left for Nikola’s estate and was <br>never seen again. <br> ◆ Nikola rarely comes to the Village now and seems to be <br>very busy. The villagers never go to him spontaneously, <br>but wait for him to show up.<br>It is possible to meet all the elders, but it takes time: for <br>every hour the Hunters spend in the Village, they can meet <br>one elder.  <br>The Village Elders  <br>1: Asmo<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am the leader of the elders, and my word is <br>final when there is disagreement.<br>Agenda: To serve Nikola by reporting everything that hap-<br>pens in the village / To keep outside attention away from Ro-<br>vaniemi and prevent Nikola from being forced to harm the <br>villagers.</p><p>118<br>Information: Asmo sings Nikola’s praises, calling him <br>the benefactor of Rovaniemi. Rumors that he is a kidnapper <br>are false, and the people who are no longer in the Village <br>are fine and have voluntarily moved to work in Nikola’s toy <br>factory.<br>2: Elna<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a good weaver and know many legends <br>of the area.<br>Agenda: I want my daughter Jaana to come home, but <br>without openly siding against Nikola Lupei.<br>Information: Elna’s family is among those who did not <br>initially pay the pledge, and her daughter Jaana has disap-<br>peared. The old woman will tell you that her daughter is <br>well and has settled in Nikola’s mansion, where she works <br>as a toy factory worker. When questioned about the night <br>of the disappearance, Elna will say that no one noticed any-<br>thing and that there were no signs of forced entry. Talking <br>to Elna, it will become clear that she misses her daughter <br>very much. <br>3: Mikko<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 <br>Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am an accountant who is in <br>charge of the gold trade between the village <br>and the merchants. <br>Agenda: Make the village prosperous and <br>earn good money. <br>Information: Mikko is the newest addition <br>to the group of elders and was not present during the first <br>night of the pledge. He does not believe in rumors and sees <br>the “kidnapped” people simply as workers who choose to <br>stay in the comfort of Nikola’s warm and cozy mansion. <br>However, Mikko noticed that some of the traders missed <br>the appointment to load the gold and he has not heard <br>from them. The old man has noted everything in his re-<br>cords, where it can be seen that the missed appointments <br>and disappearances of the merchants occur on a regular ba-<br>sis. However, the old accountant is extremely jealous of his <br>work and will not share the records with anyone. <br>4: Katri<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a good hunter, but now my venerable age <br>keeps me from hunting. I know the area around Rovaniemi <br>very well.<br>Agenda: Defend the village of Rovaniemi from any possible <br>threat from the wilderness.    <br>Information: Katri leads the hunters in the Village, and <br>lately she has been told that the presence of animals has <br>decreased dramatically. There are several hunting lodges <br>in the forest around the Village, where one <br>can find shelter. The area where Nikola Lu-<br>pei’s mansion was built is full of ravines and <br>natural caves.    <br>5: Usko<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (2 <br>Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a prospector and direct the <br>work of recovering metals from the big river <br>east of Rovaniemi.</p><p>119<br>Agenda: Promote the community’s gold trade.<br>Information: Usko will tell the Hunters that most of the <br>equipment the searchers use was donated by Nikola. Usko <br>will speak of Nikola as a benefactor who has always worked <br>for the good of the Village. As for the disappearances, Usko <br>simply thinks that working in Nikola’s toy factory is much <br>easier than panning for gold in the cold and frost of the big <br>river. That is why several villagers have decided to move to <br>the factory, which is next to Nikola Lupei’s mansion. Usko <br>considers the missing inhabitants to be savvy layabouts <br>who have found a way to live comfortably while everyone <br>else labors. The toys Nikola produces are of the highest <br>quality, and Nikola has built his fortune by selling them to <br>wealthy families all over Europe. <br>6: Soila<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a teacher and I am responsible for the <br>education of the children in the village.        <br>Agenda: Keeping Rovaniemi families together. <br>Information: Soila will say that Nikola’s behavior was al-<br>ways strange. For example, he always came to the village <br>after sunset and never entered anyone’s house without a <br>proper formal invitation. More than once, Soila has seen <br>him lose his temper over the issue. But the Patron’s eccen-<br>tric behavior is nothing compared to all the good he has <br>done for the Village. Soila knows all the families who live <br>in the Village and is responsible for welcoming newcomers. <br>She will tell you that Tommi and Jutta are two good peo-<br>ple, but too reserved to adapt to the rules of the communi-<br>ty. Soila has even offered to help them pay the pledge, but <br>Tommi is too proud to go into debt.<br>The Forest around <br>Rovaniemi<br>Descriptor: A dense forest, always covered by a thick blan-<br>ket of snow. It is easy to find tracks in the snow.<br>Information: It is possible to reach Nikola’s estate from <br>the forest in a six-hour walk. Every three hours, the fol-<br>lowing Encounters are possible. The Storyteller can choose <br>which or roll a die. <br>1-2: The Tracks<br>3-4: Nikola’s Reindeer<br>5-6: Remains of the Merchant Wagon<br>The Tracks<br>The Hunters see the tracks of a single person who veered <br>off the path and got lost in the forest. They were left by the <br>first Hunter to arrive in Rovaniemi and lead to the Hunting <br>Lodge. See page 120.</p><p>120<br>Nikola’s Reindeer<br>Reindeer enslaved to Nikola occupy the entire forest around <br>the Village and the mansion, with the task of killing and <br>dragging to the Badalisk’s lair anyone who is not a resident <br>of Rovaniemi. A Reindeer herd consists of four members.<br>Remains of the Merchant Wagon<br>Not far from the main road, you can see the remains of a <br>wagon, now completely covered in snow. If you examine <br>it, you will find the remains of several mangled bodies and <br>goods that no one has taken. This is a merchant shipment <br>that never made it to Nikola’s estate. It will be easy to see that <br>many of the bodies were dragged into the forest thicket to <br>be taken somewhere. If the Hunters follow the tracks, they <br>will come to the Badalisk’s Lair. See Threat - Lost Trails on <br>page 121.  <br>The Hunting Lodge<br>Descriptor: A small hut, fortified as best it can be. A faint <br>trail of smoke from the chimney indicates that someone has <br>taken refuge inside.<br>Information: The Hunter who arrived a week ago was <br>badly injured in a confrontation with Nikola’s Reindeer and <br>is unable to escape. The Reindeer are patrolling the area, <br>ready to strike. Indeed, shortly after the Hunters arrive, a <br>herd of Reindeer attacks the cabin. The Hunter has suffered <br>their last Wound and is unable to act, but at the Storytell-<br>er’s discretion, they may use one of their Gifts to help. The <br>Hunter can report information about 2 of the Village El-<br>ders, chosen from those the Hunters have not already in-<br>terviewed. They will also say that Nikola himself showed up <br>at the door the night before and asked to be invited in. The <br>Hunter refused, fearing a trap. Nikola asked for their help in <br>“defeating a terrible monster, ” but refused to give any more <br>information. After another refusal to enter, he left mutter -<br>ing.  <br>Nikola’s Reindeer  <br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: We are reindeer mutated by Nikola’s magic, <br>and we crave to sink our teeth into the flesh of living creatures.    <br>Gift - Carnivore: Nikola’s Reindeer have large, clumsy jaws <br>that they use to eat meat. Each Reindeer in the herd increases <br>its OL by 1 when it attacks a marked target. A target is marked <br>when it suffers 1 Wound from a Reindeer bite. Alternatively, <br>a Reindeer can use its action to inflict a Wound on itself and <br>cover up to 3 targets within 20 feet with blood to mark them. A <br>target can dodge the attack with an OL Hard 7 Defense Check.</p><p>121<br>Threat – Lost Trails<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: It is not easy to follow the drag tracks in the <br>forest and keep alert for predators. <br>In case of failure, the Hunters will be caught off guard by a <br>herd of Nikola’s Reindeer. <br>The Badalisk’s Lair<br>Descriptor: A large natural cave that emits a strong stench <br>of death and decay.      <br>Information: The tracks end at the mouth of the gorge, <br>where there is no snow on the rock: this indicates that a <br>large creature often moves to the mouth. Many human re-<br>mains and various objects can be found inside the cave. The <br>deeper you go, the darker it gets.<br>Threat – The Sleeping Badalisk<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: The Badalisk sleeps most of the time, but if you <br>disturb it, it will wake up ready to devour anything.<br>Note: This Threat is activated when Hunters make a loud <br>noise, turn on a light, or come close enough for the Badal-<br>isk to smell them. If the Badalisk does not awaken, it can be <br>examined closely while it is dormant. If the Badalisk suffers <br>1 Wound, it will wake immediately.<br>The Badalisk<br>OL Hard 7 - Main NPC (6 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a huge dirty red sack encrusted with the <br>bloody remains of past meals. I have a large mouth with <br>which I devour my prey in one gulp.    <br>Agenda: Eating whatever comes my way to satiate my end-<br>less hunger.    <br>Gift - Huge Mouth:  When the Badalisk attacks a target <br>and the target fails their Defense Check, the Badalisk can <br>choose between two effects:<br>1. Inflicts 1 additional Wound with its bite. The target can <br>also be thrown a distance of thirty feet or have one of its <br>pieces of equipment swallowed by the Badalisk.<br>2. Swallow the target so that they end up in its giant belly. <br>This effect can also be activated when the target gains an <br>Outcome with a Cost on a Defense Check, but in this <br>case, they will only lose one piece of equipment as it is <br>swallowed by the giant maw.<br>A subject trapped inside the Badalisk can use their action to <br>actively attempt to escape. Depending on their ability, this <br>will be resolved as follows:<br>NPC with OL Easy 3: They cannot free themselves.<br>NPC with OL Medium 5:  They are released during the <br>Scene following the one in which they were swallowed.<br>NPCs with OL Hard 7, Dark Presences, and Bro-<br>ken Tales: Frees itself during the Exchange, but cannot <br>do anything else.<br>Hunter: Gets free with a Defense Check against OL Me-<br>dium 5.</p><p>122<br>A subject trapped inside the Badalisk follows the rules of the <br>Great Stomach Sack Gift.<br>Gift - Great Stomach Sack:  The Badalisk has swal-<br>lowed a Treasure of the Order, and it is making the creature <br>incredibly powerful. It can act 2 times during an Exchange <br>and regenerates all Wounds suffered between Scenes. To <br>retrieve the Treasure, a Hunter must be swallowed by the <br>Badalisk and make a Position Check against the creature. <br>If the Check fails, the Hunter suffers 1 Wound caused by <br>the objects inside the sack hitting him. On the other hand, <br>if the creature is asleep, the subjects inside it must make a <br>Position Check against the Badalisk’s OL for each action to <br>avoid waking it. Removing the swallowed Treasure sends <br>the Badalisk into hibernation: the creature shrinks to its <br>original size and becomes the Treasure of the Order known <br>as The Badalisk.<br>Nikola’s Estate<br>Descriptor: An estate consisting of a large garden and two <br>main buildings.    <br>Information: A herd of Nikola’s Reindeer roam the es-<br>tate’s garden. The larger building is the toy factory, while <br>the smaller mansion is Nikola’s home.  <br>The Toy Factory<br>Descriptor: An imposing building crammed with toys and <br>other wooden creations. Tools and workbenches are buried <br>in a huge mess.<br>Information: The situation in the factory differs depend-<br>ing on whether the Hunters arrive by day or by night.<br>Night: Everything is off, and the Servants rest by sleeping <br>on the floor or on worktables. They are awakened by loud <br>noises. <br>Day: All the villagers enslaved by Nikola’s power, 12 in all, <br>work in the factory. The Servants all wear a green uniform <br>and a funny pointed hat.</p><p>123<br>Threat – Littered with Junk<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: Extreme clutter and piles of toys stacked every-<br>where make it difficult to move around.    <br>Gift - Damn Junk!:  Moving around while trying not to <br>make noise or leave a trail activates this Threat. If the De-<br>fense Check fails, roll a die:<br>1-2: The Hunter suffers 1 Wound.<br>3-4: The Hunter will make a loud noise.    <br>5-6: Junk sticks to the Hunters, causing a penalty of 1 on <br>all Checks that require movement. It is possible to get rid of <br>it by spending a few minutes.<br>Nikola’ Servants<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We live and work only to serve our master Ni-<br>kola. We are skilled in handicrafts and in using the toy facto-<br>ry to eliminate any intruders. <br>Agenda: Produce high-quality toys and then ship them to <br>poor children / Eliminate any intruder who is not a resident <br>of Rovaniemi.<br>Gift - Enslaved to Nikola: While Nikola’s charm is active, <br>a Servant is immune to all mind control effects and can-<br>not be manipulated by social interaction. Nikola’s charm is <br>considered dark magic performed by a supernatural being.    <br>Gift - Toymakers: As long as they are inside the factory, <br>a Servant receives the following effects.<br>1. They increase their OL by 1 when acting to eliminate or <br>capture an intruder.<br>2. They can move around the factory using hooks, toys <br>on wheels, and more without anyone being able to stop <br>them.<br>Nikola’s Mansion<br>Descriptor: A small mansion, richly furnished and filled <br>with all sorts of occult heirlooms.<br>Information: The situation at the Mansion is different if <br>the Hunters arrive by day or by night.<br>Night: Nikola is present and can fully use his powers. With <br>him are the 3 Helpers. <br>Day: Nikola is resting in the crypt and will only wake up <br>if he hears a racket at its entrance. The Helpers are present <br>and active.<br>A large painting in the main hall shows Nikola when he was <br>still a Wallachian nobleman. The painting is dated 1602. <br>Below the painting is a lever that, when pulled, opens the <br>trapdoor to Nikola’s crypt.</p><p>124<br>Helpers <br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We live and work only to serve our master Ni-<br>kola. Our bodies are made stronger by the power that has <br>been infused into them.    <br>Agenda: Defend Nikola from all threats.<br>Gift - Servants of the Mansion: Each Helper can avail themselves of a different effect based on their role.<br>Jori the Cook:  Can inflict 1 additional Wound with his <br>cleaver. Injuries inflicted by Jori count as a mark for Niko-<br>la’s Reindeer.<br>Pete the Butler: When moving inside the mansion, Pete <br>ignores any movement penalty and no one can block him.<br>Verna the Accountant:  Increases her OL to Hard 7 <br>when defending against an attack inside the mansion.<br>Nikola Lupei<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a powerful vampire with a <br>good heart, and I just want to live in peace <br>and quiet. The power I draw from blood <br>makes my body strong and fast. <br>Agenda: Find a way to get rid of the <br>Badalisk without harming the people <br>of Rovaniemi / Keep my secret and my <br>life in Rovaniemi. <br>Gift - Power of the Vampire:  <br>The curse that plagues Nikola’s <br>blood gives him great powers, but <br>also some weaknesses.<br>Powers: Each can be used by Ni-<br>kola once per Scene.<br>1: Recover 1 Wound.<br>2: Turn into mist.<br>3: Enslave a subject with his gaze. Perform a Defense <br>Check against Nikola’s OL to resist. An enslaved subject <br>shares what they see and hear with Nikola and will do <br>whatever the vampire commands. Nikola does not have to <br>be present to command the slave, but the subject must be <br>awake and alert. Enslavement ends when the subject suf-<br>fers 1 Wound.<br>Weaknesses: Nikola cannot enter a place he has nev-<br>er been unless first invited by the person who lives there.    <br>When exposed to sunlight, Nikola loses 1 Wound per <br>minute. Nikola can only be permanently eliminated if the <br>last of his Wounds is inflicted by a magical or consecrated <br>weapon.<br>Gift - Occult Scholar:  Nikola knows many rituals and <br>possesses arcane objects to cast spells. He used these pow-</p><p>125<br>ers to create his Reindeer and make his Helpers stronger. Up to 3 times per Scene, Nikola can block the use <br>of a Gift he has seen in action. Once per Scene, Nikola can imbue an NPC with power by increasing <br>their OL by one category. The Storyteller must rewrite the NPC’s Descriptor to reflect the mutation <br>caused by Nikola’s spell. <br>Nikola’s Crypt<br>Descriptor: A gloomy, dark, unadorned crypt in the center of which rests a gold and <br>diamond-encrusted coffin on a small pedestal.<br>Information: By day, Nikola rests in his coffin, sleeping in a deep slumber. A swarm <br>of Bats, mutated by his power, protects him.  <br>Nikola’s Bats  <br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (5 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: We are a swarm of bats ready to devour any intruder.    <br>Agenda: Protect Nikola while he sleeps.<br>Gift - Swarm: Bats are considered a single unit with 5 Wounds. <br>Any damage dealt reduces the total by 1, and attacks that hit an <br>area inflict 1 additional Wound. As a swarm, Nikola’s Bats can <br>bite up to 3 different targets in a single action. The flapping <br>of the Bats’ wings causes discomfort to living creatures: <br>as the swarm rises, each Hunter present loses 2 Soma, <br>while NPCs suffer 1 Wound from fatigue.</p><p>126<br>Scenario Events<br>There are six Events in this Scenario. As the Storyteller, feel <br>free to create new ones in response to the Hunters’ actions.<br>If the Hunters have an NPC in their retinue: Nikola <br>will arrive in Rovaniemi on the first evening to enslave the <br>NPC. When threatened by the Hunter’s presence, he will <br>flee by turning into mist. <br>If the Hunters do not rescue the captive Hunter in <br>the Hunting Lodge within one day:  Nikola will attack <br>with his servants and take the Hunters to the toy factory to <br>prepare them as a meal for the Badalisk.<br>If the Hunters capture Nikola:  The vampire will ask <br>for their help in getting rid of the Badalisk, warning them <br>that if the creature does not find a meal when it awakens, it <br>will rampage through the village. <br>If the Hunters eliminate the Badalisk before meet-<br>ing Nikola: The vampire will thank them and invite them <br>to his mansion to understand the Order’s intentions toward <br>him and to mediate a peaceful resolution. <br>If the Hunters enter the mansion during the day:  Jori and Pete will attack the Hunters while Verna runs to <br>wake her master. <br>If the Hunters bring a Rovaniemi resident with <br>them: Nikola will try to capture and enslave the resident, <br>but under no circumstances will he risk their life. <br>Scenario Gifts<br>These Gifts represent special abilities related to the Nikola’s <br>Pledge Scenario and can be acquired once the conditions <br>are met. A Hunter can only have one Scenario Gift, and if <br>they acquire a new one, they will have to forgo the previous <br>one.<br>Aberration Killer<br>Requirement: Eliminate a herd of Reindeer or a swarm <br>of Nikola’s Bats. <br>Y ou have learned how to deal with creatures empowered by <br>dark magic. Once per Scene, if you vanquish an enchanted <br>creature (at the discretion of the Storyteller), you will re-<br>cover 1 Soma and gain 1 XP .<br>A Special Gift<br>Requirement: Free one or more of the enslaved inhabi-<br>tants of the toy factory or negotiate a deal with Nikola.<br>Y ou have received a special toy, a carving of a bearded man <br>on a sled. Y ou can spend 1 Soma to animate the toy, which <br>will be able to move around and perform small tasks such <br>as carrying an object or delivering a message to someone. <br>The toy remains active for the duration of the Scene. Y ou <br>can spend 1 Soma to return the toy to you. It will disappear <br>from its location and reappear in your hand.</p><p>127<br>The Scenario Nikola’s Pledge in Scenes</p><p>FIRST SCENE –  Arrival in <br>Rovaniemi<br>It’s the same one you find on page 116.<br>End of Scene: Tommi and Jutta will tell the Hunters that <br>they can meet the Village Elders the next morning, go to</p>"},"sort":100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513739250,"modifiedTime":1781513739250,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"97so6WnNCuBHFt9A","name":"Scene 2","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>Nikola's Pledge - Scene 2</h2><p>SECOND SCENE – The Town Hall.</p><p>SECOND SCENE –  The Town <br>Hall<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  As you walk through Ro-<br>vaniemi, you may notice that many of the equipment and <br>houses have engraved plaques identifying them as donations <br>from Nikola Lupei. It is very clear that this Nikola is a true <br>patron and that with his support the small village of miners <br>was able to prosper. The town hall is one of the few mason-<br>ry buildings in the village, rising above the roofs of the sur -<br>rounding wooden houses.<br>Place: Rovaniemi’s Town Hall. <br>Time: Early in the morning, the villagers are already work-<br>ing feverishly to take advantage of every hour of sunshine.<br>Information: Asmo and Mikko are present at the Town <br>Hall and are busy examining some documents. Asmo will <br>be very helpful and try to clear up any doubts about Nikola <br>Lupei. The Elder will prepare a letter of introduction for the <br>Hunters to take to Lupei’s estate. The Elder will recommend <br>that they arrive at night, as Nikola is a real night owl, while <br>during the day he is too busy working at the toy factory. <br>Mikko will complain that a wealthy merchant who was sup-<br>posed to be in the village missed his appointment and did <br>not send a messenger. The two Elders will also report gen-<br>eral information (see page 116), urging the Hunters to go <br>to Nikola to clear up any doubts.<br>End of Scene: Ask the Hunters if they want to go to Niko-<br>la’s by night (as Asmo recommended) or by day. To get to <br>the estate, they can choose to take the main road (THIRD <br>SCENE OPTION A - The High Road) or venture into the <br>woods (THIRD SCENE OPTION B - The Lodge).</p>"},"sort":200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513739250,"modifiedTime":1781513739250,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"LzHMPG4AIfTSzgnF","name":"Scene 3","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>Nikola's Pledge - Scene 3</h2><p>THIRD SCENE OPTION A –  <br>The High Road<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: The road to the Lupei estate is <br>wide and well-trodden. Once again, it is easy to see how much <br>effort and money Nikola has put into creating a good connec-<br>tion between his home and the village of Rovaniemi. Several <br>tracks in the fresh snow indicate that herds of animals are con-<br>stantly moving through the area, and just as you are about to <br>look around, a group of reindeer emerges from the trees and <br>gallops toward you. By the time they come into focus, the mon-<br>strous muzzles of the creatures are only a few feet away...<br>Place: The main road leading to the Lupei estate. <br>Time: It’s either night or afternoon, depending on the Hunt-<br>ers’ choice. Snow is starting to fall, promising a blizzard soon. <br>2 3a<br>1</p><p>128<br>Information: The Hunters are attacked by a herd of 4 <br>Reindeer. When they examine the bodies of the creatures, <br>using Descriptors related to hunting or magic, it is easy to <br>see that the creatures have been altered by dark magic. <br>End of Scene: The Hunters arrive at the Lupei Estate, go <br>to the FOURTH SCENE - The Estate.</p><p>THIRD SCENE OPTION B –  <br>The Lodge<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  As you make your way <br>through the bush, your attention is drawn to a cabin where <br>you see signs of life. Someone has barred the doors and win-<br>dows as if to defend against an attack, but you can tell from <br>the light you can see between the boards that they are proba-<br>bly still barricaded inside. <br>Place: An old hunting lodge often used by hunters in Ro-<br>vaniemi. <br>Time: It’s either night or afternoon, depending on the <br>Hunters’ choice. Snow is starting to fall, promising a bliz-<br>zard soon.<br>Information: The wounded Hunter has taken refuge in <br>the hut, the Scene takes place with the information associ-<br>ated with a result of 1-2 The Tracks on page 119.<br>End of Scene: The Hunters arrive at the Lupei Estate, go <br>to the FOURTH SCENE - The Estate.</p>"},"sort":300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513739250,"modifiedTime":1781513739250,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"E2SzLtqCeP3j5JKT","name":"Scene 4","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>Nikola's Pledge - Scene 4</h2><p>FOURTH SCENE –  The Estate<br>If the Hunters arrive during the day, read aloud:  <br>The Lupei estate consists of two large buildings. The sound <br>of work comes from what looks like a large factory. The other <br>building is a large baroque-style villa, its doors and windows <br>barred as if it were unoccupied.<br>If the Hunters arrive at night, read aloud:  The Lu-<br>pei estate consists of two large buildings. From the first one, <br>which looks like a big factory, everything seems to be quiet, <br>as you would expect from a workplace after work. From the <br>other, a large baroque villa, you can see the lights on and a <br>few silhouettes passing by the windows.<br>Place: Nikola Lupei’s estate. <br>Time: Day or night. <br>Information: The snow is falling heavily and the icy <br>wind is blowing, making it easy to move around the es-<br>tate inconspicuously. At this point, the Hunters can decide <br>which building to go to; the Factory is on page 122 and <br>the Mansion is on page 123. <br>The Factory: During the day, the Servants will be at work <br>and will not hesitate to attack any intruders. Once defeated, <br>they will be free from Nikola’s subjugation and can give the <br>Hunters useful information about the vampire. At night, <br>they will sleep. But when awakened, they will attack.<br>The Mansion: During the day, the Helpers will guard Ni-<br>kola’s coffin. Once defeated, it will be easy to imprison Ni-<br>kola. At night Nikola will be awake and will try to confront <br>the Hunters with his Helpers. <br>Either way, Nikola will surrender if the Hunters prove too <br>strong or hurt the Helpers. The vampire will then ask for <br>their help in getting rid of the Badalisk and explain the <br>reasons behind all his dark business and why the pledge is <br>needed. <br>3b<br>4</p><p>129<br>End of Scene: The Hunters have discovered Nikola’s se-<br>cret and can now try to defeat the Badalisk, go to FIFTH <br>SCENE - In the Badalisk’s Lair.</p>"},"sort":400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513739250,"modifiedTime":1781513739250,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"3lkll3WIBPHKpQpD","name":"Scene 5","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>Nikola's Pledge - Scene 5</h2><p>FIFTH SCENE –  In the <br>Badalisk’s Lair<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: You arrive at the mouth <br>of a large cave, from which emanates a terrible stench of <br>death. As you prepare to descend, you hear a deep snor-<br>ing in the distance.<br>Place: The Badalisk’s Lair. <br>Time: The moment of reckoning.<br>End of Scene:  See page 121 for instructions on how to <br>deal with the Badalisk. If present, Nikola will actively as-<br>sist the Hunters in two ways: he can either be devoured to <br>give a Hunter time to enter the Badalisk unharmed, or he <br>can distract the creature for an Exchange, allowing every-<br>one else to act without fear of the monster’s powerful bite. <br>After defeating the Badalisk and recovering the Treasure, <br>Nikola will ask the Hunters for permission to return to his <br>reclusive life. <br>5</p>"},"sort":500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513739250,"modifiedTime":1781513739250,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}],"folder":null,"flags":{"broken-tales":{"adventureSlug":"nikolas-pledge","collection":"Lost Stories","sourceFile":"bt-ls-book-1-ENG-SCREEN.pdf","pages":"115-130"}},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513739250,"modifiedTime":1781513739250,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}
{"_id":"yijZEQpOGEfmoGT0","name":"Journey of a Thousand and One Nights","pages":[{"_id":"O67mKKEaDtEFl7cB","name":"Summary","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h1>Journey of a Thousand and One Nights</h1><p><strong>Collection:</strong> Lost Stories</p><p><strong>Source:</strong> bt-ls-book-1-ENG-SCREEN.pdf, pages 147-168.</p><p><img src=\"systems/broken-tales/assets/adventures/maps/journey-of-a-thousand-and-one-nights-p147-full.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%; height: auto;\" /></p>"},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513741649,"modifiedTime":1781513741649,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"UdyqSMdXvPTqSu2N","name":"Scenario Text","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"markdown":"","content":"<h2>Journey of a Thousand and One Nights - Scenario Text</h2><p>146<br>Journey of a Thousand <br>and One Nights<br> <br>A Scenario inspired by One Thousand and One NightsJourney of a Thousand and One Nights is a special Scenario constructed as a Scene Tree <br>(see page 100 of the Broken Tales Core Book) and is well suited for staging the final <br>confrontation with the Dark Presence, Sherazade the Weaver of Tales. This Scenario <br>takes place within a story told by Sherazade, an emissary of the One Who Plots in the <br>Shadows (page 196 of the Broken Tales Core Book). Awakening aboard a lost ship in <br>a mysterious archipelago, the Hunters must retrieve enough Tarì (Arabic gold coins) <br>to defeat powerful Djinn guarding the Dream Gate, the only way to return to the real <br>world.<br>In this Scenario, Sherazade can be introduced in two ways.<br>As an Enemy. She follows the normal rules of a Dark Presence: Hunters can capture her <br>once she is defeated in the Fourth Leg - The Execution of Sherazade. <br>As a future ally. The One Who Plots in the Shadows urged Sherazade to abuse her power <br>and lead the Weaver of Tales to self-destruction. In the Fourth Leg - The Execution of <br>Sherazade, she will be a prisoner of the Sultan. <br>Once upon a time...<br>Good evening my dear hosts, my name is Sherazade and I am a weaver <br>of tales. My words will take you to incredible worlds and follow the feats <br>of brave Hunters… however this story is not like the others and these <br>feats are not just imaginary. Will our heroes succeed in their quest? Or <br>will they perish, disappearing forever from the memory of time?<br>Safety Keywords: Blackmail / <br>Imprisonment / Toxic relationships <br>/ Animal violence / Slavery</p><p>147<br>The story that led us here...<br>Tired of the Hunters’ continued success, the One <br>Who Plots in the Shadows commands Sherazade to cre-<br>ate the deadliest of tales to eliminate the Hunters once <br>and for all. Since the power of Sherazade’s stories comes <br>from the emotions the weaver evokes in the audience, <br>Sherazade gives voice to the most powerful emotion she <br>possesses: grief over the loss of her sister, Dinarzad. Thus <br>a long tale is born, one that encompasses all the stories <br>the weaver told in the vain hope of saving her sister when <br>they were captives of the Sultan. Unable to cope with the <br>pain of those memories, Sherazade fell prey to her own <br>power and was eventually sucked into the story, as were <br>the Hunters. Now back in the Sultan’s court, the weaver <br>struggles to find a way back to the reality of Broken Eu-<br>rope. Absorbed by yet another of Sherazade’s tales, the <br>Hunters instead wake up on a great ship, where they see <br>an old acquaintance of theirs: Sinbad the Traveller of a <br>Thousand Seas.<br>How to manage the Scenario<br>This Scenario unfolds as a ship voyage, where each Leg <br>(randomly generated) will put the Hunters in front of a <br>specific mission to face. If the problem is solved, the Hunt-<br>ers will receive a Tarì. Each accumulated Tarì will make the <br>fight against the Djinn in the Dream Gate easier. <br>The Scenario unfolds as follows:<br>1. First Leg - The group generates a Type A Leg.  <br>2. Second Leg - The group generates a Type B Leg.    <br>3. Third Leg - The group generates a Type A Leg.    <br>4. Fourth Leg - The Execution of Sherazade.<br>5. Fifth Leg -The group generates a Type B Leg. <br>6. Sixth Leg - The group generates a Type A Leg.    <br>7. Seventh Leg - The group generates a Type B Leg. <br>8. Eighth Leg - The Dream Gate.<br>Each Leg, with the exception of the Fourth and Eighth, <br>presents a Place, Information, and a list of challenges to be <br>solved in order to obtain the Tarì. The Storyteller is then <br>free to develop the events according to their taste, and to <br>decide when to end the event and begin the journey again. <br>Each Leg should last a maximum of two or three Scenes, <br>the equivalent of a Campaign Encounter. In this Scenario, <br>calling for an Interlude will make the Fourth and Eighth <br>Legs more complex, as explained in the relevant sections. <br>To reduce the length of the Scenario, simply remove the <br>Third and Fifth Legs, and remove the Seventh and Eighth <br>Djinn in the Eighth Leg. <br>The unique nature of this Scenario may require a great deal <br>of improvisation on the part of the Storyteller, as each Leg <br>provides clues and potential situations, but doesn’t go into</p><p>148<br>as much detail as typical Scenarios. There are two ways to <br>manage this issue:<br>Preparation<br>The Storyteller creates all the Legs and sets up the Scenario <br>in its entirety before proposing it for the Session. With this <br>approach, the various Legs can be planned in detail, Places, <br>and NPCs can be added, and the Villain’s Journey rules on <br>page 43 can be used for additional ideas.<br>Improvisation<br>The Storyteller prepares nothing and details everything on <br>the fly, generating the Leg when it is actually played. This <br>system allows much more freedom for the table: for it to <br>work best, it is recommended that the Storyteller give the <br>Hunters all the Information they deem useful at the begin-<br>ning of the Leg, so the group can decide on their intentions <br>right away. <br>First Leg<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: The rocking of the waves ac-<br>companies your awakening. Startled, you jump out of your <br>bunks. You fell asleep the night before in an inn on the road <br>to Rome, and now, judging by what you can see through the <br>porthole of a ship’s cabin, you are on the high seas. Once at <br>deck, you can admire an entire crew of sailors, moving like <br>an efficient swarm of ants, working diligently to maintain the <br>course of a large sailing ship. “ Awake at last!” A rough, famil-<br>iar voice comes from behind you. It is that of Sinbad, an old <br>sea dog who served the Order long before you.<br>Place: Sinbad’s sailing ship. <br>Time: Early in the morning, the sun is high and bright. A <br>soft, warm breeze blows, gently moving the sails. <br>Initial Situation: Sinbad will greet the Hunters by trying <br>to calm their confusion. This is not the first time the old <br>sailor has ended up in a Sherazade story, and from what he <br>heard in Rome, the Hunters know what he is talking about. <br>Information: Sinbad will provide all of the following <br>info. <br> ◆ The Hunters and Sinbad have found themselves in one <br>of Sherazade’s stories. Sinbad was the first to wake up <br>and by talking to a sea Djinn he was able to get some in-<br>formation. To return to the real world, it is necessary to <br>pass through the Dream Gate, a magical portal located <br>on the last island of the great archipelago that the sailing <br>ship is passing through. The Dream Gate is guarded by a <br>group of very powerful Djinn, and each of them requires <br>a token to gain access to the door. What the Djinn crave <br>is the magical Tarì.<br> ◆ Several Legs will be required to reach the final island, <br>each of which will give the Hunters one day to retrieve <br>the Tarì. The coins are not simply hidden, but in the <br>1</p><p>149<br>possession of a character from the story. Resolving the <br>situations they encounter will be the only way for the <br>Hunters to receive the Tarì as a reward.<br> ◆ At the end of each day, the ship must leave port, because <br>a giant wave in the shape of a turned page will sweep <br>everything away, engulfing each island as if it had faded <br>into history. The only way to escape the wave and save <br>themselves from disappearing forever is to move on to <br>the next destination.<br>Sinbad is very excited about this voyage, which will allow <br>him to relive the glory of his youth <br>as a sailor. The Hunters know <br>that if they can keep the old sea <br>dog from getting bored, he will <br>do his best to make the Hunt-<br>ers’ journey easier. <br>After providing all this infor -<br>mation, you can create a First <br>Leg (A). <br>Sinbad the Traveler <br>of the Thousand Seas<br>Inspired by Sinbad of the Thousand and One <br>Nights (Allied)<br>Descriptor: I am an experienced traveler and have seen <br>every known land. I get bored easily if I’m not interested in <br>what I’m doing.<br>1 Wound<br>Opposition Level: Medium 5<br>Agenda: I am willing to do anything to experience <br>the thrill of discovery once again.<br>Special Agenda (Sherazade the Weav -<br>er of Tales):  I boast of knowing every story <br>and legend, and I love to mock those who pride <br>themselves on limited knowledge. I want to rid-<br>icule the stories Sherazade tells, highlighting the <br>truths that only I know.<br>Gift - Traveler of a Thousand Places:  <br>Sinbad has seen the whole world and much <br>of what the Broken Tales hide. In the <br>course of a Scene, a Hunter can invoke <br>his help to obtain information or <br>create an additional Descriptor <br>that represents a specific area <br>of Sinbad’s knowledge. But <br>the old sailor is an eccentric <br>type, and to provide his help <br>he first must be entertained. <br>The Storyteller will evaluate <br>the current situation and</p><p>150<br>Sinbad’s level of boredom. A Hunter can capture Sinbad’s <br>interest with creative actions, as long as they’re appropriate <br>to the current Scene.<br>Gift - I Know How to Do It:  Once per Scene, a Hunter <br>can get 1 Additional Success in their Check, asking Sinbad <br>for helpful advice. As with Traveler of a Thousand Places, <br>Sinbad needs to be intrigued before helping. Sinbad be-<br>gins each Leg bored. If the Hunters take the old sailor with <br>them, the excitement of discovery will immediately relieve <br>Sinbad’s boredom. Alternatively, the Hunters can ask Sin-<br>bad to stay on the ship, and if they fulfill one of his requests, <br>he will not be bored.<br>Sinbad Requests<br>Roll 1 die or choose.<br>1: Bring me a rare and precious item. <br>2: Bring me someone who can tell me a good story.<br>3: Bring me rare and tasty food. <br>4: Bring me a strange person. <br>5: Bring me a sincere promise.<br>6: Bring me a picture of a beautiful place.<br>If Sinbad suffers all his Wounds, he will be out of action for <br>the current and next Leg. In addition to his normal Gifts, <br>Sinbad also has the Gift - The Sailing Ship.<br>Gift - The Sailing Ship:  Sinbad’s large sailing ship con-<br>tains all kinds of comforts and knowledge that the old sail-<br>or only makes available to his guests. At the end of a Leg, <br>if Sinbad is not bored, he will allow each Hunter to choose <br>one of the following effects:<br>1. Rest in the Sultan’s Rooms: To recover 1 Wound.<br>2. Meditate in the Lotus Hall: To recover 3 Soma.<br>3. Study in the Library of Alexandria:  To obtain the <br>effect of a Descriptor Specialization in the following Leg.<br>4. Access Solomon’s Treasury: To obtain a Treasure <br>of Order for the next Leg. <br>5. Call of Duty (from the Fifth Leg onwards only):  <br>A new Hunter is summoned into the story by Sherazade, <br>allowing the group to switch members or replace a Hunter <br>who is out of action.</p><p>151<br>“A” Legs (First, Third, and Sixth)<br>Roll 1 die to determine the Leg. Increase the result by 1 <br>if you obtain a Leg you have already faced. Alternatively, <br>choose directly which Leg you prefer to play.<br>1A The Merchant and the Djinn<br>The story that led us here...<br>The ship lands on a small island where there are only two vil-<br>lages of poor people. Some of the villagers throw themselves at <br>the Hunters’ feet, begging for their help. A powerful Djinn is <br>killing an innocent person every day, and the blame lies with <br>a clever Merchant who escaped the spirit’s wrath by claiming <br>to be honor-bound to settle a debt. Thirty days ago, the Mer-<br>chant accidentally killed the Djinn’s son in a heated argument <br>over date seeds. Enraged, the Djinn showed up to behead the <br>culprit, but the cunning man asked for a day to settle some <br>unfinished business before he died. The Merchant then fled <br>and has not been seen since. The Djinn demanded the entire <br>population find him, or else he would cut off the head of an <br>innocent person every day. <br>Place: It is not possible to leave the island without a ship. <br>Therefore, the Merchant must be hiding in one of the two <br>villages. <br>Information: The Djinn arrives in the village at dusk to <br>see if the Merchant has been captured. The Merchant can-<br>not have fled the island, as the Hunter’s ship is the first to <br>arrive in over a month.<br>Challenges: The Merchant has simply disguised himself <br>as a local woman, and is impatiently awaiting the arrival <br>of a ship like the Hunters’ . The Djinn is furious and resents <br>being tricked. <br>How to get the Tarì: If the Hunters succeed in appeasing <br>the Djinn’s wrath without killing the Merchant, the Mer -<br>chant will give them the Tarì as a thank-you gift.<br>The Merchant<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a cunning old Merchant, I am a good <br>mimic and I love to disguise myself. <br>Agenda: Escape the island by secretly boarding a ship, or <br>find a way to appease the Djinn’s wrath.</p><p>152<br>The Furious Djinn<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (4 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a powerful Djinn, skilled with a scimitar. <br>I hate lies and those who break agreements.<br>Agenda: To avenge my son’s death by punishing the Mer -<br>chant who caused it. <br>Gift - Frenzied: When the Djinn suffers 1 Wound, it can <br>immediately attack with its giant scimitar to strike the one <br>who did the damage. <br>2A The Island Fish<br>The story that led us here...<br>Sinbad’s ship has docked at a large island dense with plants <br>that bear delicious fruits. The entire crew has gone ashore to <br>resupply, but what no one can imagine is that this lush land is <br>actually resting on the back of a giant, sleeping fish. While the <br>sailors are busy harvesting fruit, the island begins to tremble <br>and the land cracks. Sinbad begs the Hunters to save his men, <br>or no one will be able to sail the ship to continue the journey.  <br> <br>Place: A large natural island filled with plants and fruits. <br>Information: Sailors are divided into six groups, each in a <br>different part of the island. <br>Challenges: Traveling by land is very dangerous due to the <br>constant movements of the Island Fish. When a group of <br>sailors is rescued, roll 1 die: if you roll a 6, the sailors are <br>carrying a strange barrel found in the vegetation. If a 6 is <br>never rolled, the barrel is automatically in the hands of the <br>sixth party.<br>How to get the Tarì: Found inside the barrel.<br>Threat – The Island Fish<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: The earth cracks and trees fall on those unlucky <br>enough to be nearby. Seawater slowly submerges everything. <br>Gift - The Island Moves!:  Moving around the island is <br>very dangerous, rescuing a group of sailors requires at least <br>2 Checks against this Threat, one to get to the group and one <br>to return to the ship. The Check can only be made by the <br>Hunter leading the search party. For each failed Check, roll <br>1 die and apply the result to one of the Hunters.<br>1: Suffers 1 Wound caused by falling trees and rocks.<br>2: Receives 1 Penalty at the next Check due to mud.    <br>3: Loses 1 Soma due to fatigue. <br>4: Loses 1 Equipment in the waves of the sea.<br>5: Loses more time than expected. Increase the OL of this <br>Threat by 1 for those performing the next Check.</p><p>153<br>6: The Hunter falls into a crevasse and remains separated <br>from the others, they will have to do a Position Check to <br>return to the ship or be lost until the end of this Leg. <br>3A The Roc<br>The story that led us here...<br>The Hunters are jolted from their beds, and to their horror, <br>they discover that the ship is tilting dangerously. Climbing <br>on deck, they see a giant bird perched on the bow, apparent-<br>ly intending to build a nest. However, the weight of the bird <br>threatens to sink the ship...<br>Place: Sinbad’s ship in the middle of the sea. <br>Information: Sinbad warns the Hunters that they must <br>move the Roc calmly, for if the creature takes off at full <br>power, it could completely overturn the ship. In the dis-<br>tance, a huge spire of stone juts out of the sea. Perhaps that <br>is where the Roc came from.<br>Challenges: Move or knock down the Roc without mak-<br>ing it shake the boat. The stone island in the middle of the <br>sea is constantly battered by great waves, and among the <br>surrounding rocks are the remains of many nests that the <br>Roc attempted to build, but which were destroyed by the <br>fury of the sea. <br>How to obtain the Tarì:  When the Roc leaves the ship, <br>the Tarì can be found in the remains of its nest.<br>Roc<br>See Dark Presence on page 13.<br>4A Monkey Island<br>The story that led us here...<br>It is early morning when the Hunters are summoned by Sin-<br>bad: the ship has landed on a large natural island full of cute <br>little monkeys. The problem is that seven sailors disappeared <br>during the night, and tracks found on the deck lead Sinbad <br>to believe that the monkeys kidnapped them. Sinbad asks the <br>Hunters to explore the island and rescue his men. <br>Place: A large wild island with a small volcano in the mid-<br>dle. <br>Information: The Monkeys’ tracks seem to lead straight <br>to the volcano, but what the Hunters don’t know is that the <br>poor animals bring the unfortunates they capture to the <br>volcano to appease the hunger of a ferocious Giant who, in <br>the absence of prey, pounces on primates.<br>Challenges: Monkeys (2 per Hunter) trying to scare off  <br>the Hunters by throwing rocks from trees, or laying traps <br>and false trails; the Elephant-Eared Giant that lives in the <br>volcano. <br>How to get the Tarì:  It is guarded by the Monkeys and <br>they will give it to the Hunters if they eliminate the Giant.</p><p>154<br>The Monkeys<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are agile and fast, and we move quickly <br>through the trees to escape threats. <br>Agenda: Satisfy the Giant’s hunger to prevent it from de-<br>vouring us. <br>The Elephant-Eared Giant<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (6 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a huge Giant of herculean strength, I <br>have no natural predators on the island. I consider all crea-<br>tures smaller than me to be weak, and I am not afraid that <br>they will harm me.<br>Gift - Elephant Ears: As a free action, the Giant can use <br>its massive ears to create a gust of wind capable of hurling <br>a human thirty feet. The gust affects 2 targets and can be <br>avoided with a Defense Check. If someone is pushed back, <br>roll 1 die:  <br>1-2: Loses an Equipment.<br>3-4: Suffers 1 Wound.<br>5-6: Ends up in impassable terrain, requiring a Check to <br>get out.  <br>5A An Old Bride<br>The story that led us here...<br>The ship lands on a large island that is familiar to Sinbad. <br>The old sailor goes down with some of his crew to resupply, <br>but only one of his men returns. The survivor tells the Hunt-<br>ers that Sinbad once married the daughter of the island’s king, <br>but she died shortly after the wedding. According to local tra-<br>dition, Sinbad was buried alive with his bride to be united <br>with her forever. The cunning traveler, however, managed to <br>escape, and now that more than fifty years had passed, he be-<br>lieved that all had been forgotten by the new ruler. But to his <br>astonishment, Sinbad and his people found themselves in the <br>presence of a centenarian king who did not hesitate to return <br>poor Sinbad to the tomb of his wife. <br>Place: A large pyramid-shaped tomb not far from the <br>town where the island’s ruler resides. <br>Information: The tomb is protected by a notorious order <br>of Guardians who are said to devour intruders alive. <br>Challenges: The tomb is patrolled by over a hundred <br>Guardians. Entering it requires some sort of distraction. <br>On the east side of the tomb, there is a crack in the wall <br>through which a person can safely pass. While waiting for <br>it to be repaired, a team of six Guardians stands watch by <br>the wall. The king is the only one who insists on enforcing</p><p>155<br>the old traditions, but no one dares to contradict him. The <br>old monarch lives protected by hundreds of guards, but his <br>death would end the absurd law. <br>How to get the Tarì:  In the funeral ritual, the groom is <br>given seven loaves of bread and some water. Back on the <br>ship, Sinbad takes a bite of the last loaf, breaking a tooth on <br>the Tarì hidden inside. <br>Guardians of the Tomb <br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are an order of fighting Guardians, and <br>our vow of loyalty comes before all else. Only the taste of hu-<br>man flesh can distract us from our duty.<br>Agenda: Defend the tomb from intruders. <br>6A The Crystal Cliffs<br>The story that led us here...<br>Overwhelmed by a strong current, the ship is pushed toward <br>a large group of rocks that Sinbad recognizes as very danger-<br>ous. The crystal that makes up the rocks is fragile, but also <br>extremely sharp, and touching them would damage the ship’s <br>hull. Beneath the crystal layer, the “rocks” are made up of all <br>sorts of precious stones, and in each of them lies a real trea-<br>sure. Even though the main goal is to get out unharmed, there <br>might be a Tarì among all the riches.  <br>Place: A large group of crystal rocks reflecting the sun-<br>light.<br>Information: It’s not easy to shatter the crystal without <br>dangerous shards flying everywhere. Sinbad can keep con-<br>trol of the ship, but it will be up to the Hunters to clear the <br>way. <br>Challenges: Destroy the crystal rocks that block the path <br>and recover valuable items from the inner rocks. At least 4 <br>rocks must be cleared to cross this part of the sea. <br>How to get the Tarì:  If the Hunters find at least 5 valu-<br>ables, the Tarì will also be in the sixth rock.</p><p>156<br>Threat – Crystal Rock<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: I am a fragile, sharp agglomeration of crystal. <br>The wrong vibration can make me explode.        <br>Note: The Storyteller rolls 1 die or chooses from the list to <br>complete the Threat Descriptor. <br>1: A flock of seagulls nested among the rocks. <br>2: Part of me juts underwater dangerously. <br>3: My crystal is harder than normal. <br>4: I am, in reality, a floating block moving without control.<br>5: My crystal reflects sunlight much more intensely than nor -<br>mal. I blind those who approach.<br>6: I am filled with subtle overgrowths extending in every di-<br>rection.<br>Gift - Sensitive to Vibration:  If a crystal is destroyed <br>without obtaining a positive Outcome on a Check, the ship <br>receives 1 Damage Token. The person who caused the explo-<br>sion gets 1 Wound and loses 1 Soma. If there are 2 or more <br>Damage Tokens on the ship at the end of the Leg, Sinbad will <br>not be able to use his Gift - The Sailing Ship, regardless of <br>whether he is bored or not, and will go directly to the next <br>Leg.  <br>“B” Legs (Second, Fifth, and Seventh)<br>Roll 1 die to determine the Leg. Increase the result by 1 if you <br>obtain a Leg you have already faced. Alternatively, choose di-<br>rectly which Leg you prefer to play.<br>1B Raging Rocs<br>Note: This Leg can only be played after Leg 3A - The Roc. If <br>the Hunters have not yet faced it, consider this a 1A roll.<br>The story that led us here...<br>Two huge winged figures appear in the sky, identical to the large <br>bird that tried to nest on the ship. The creatures have huge boul-<br>ders in their talons and seem intent on dropping them on the <br>deck. Sinbad begs the Hunters to save the ship before he cau-<br>tiously flees below deck.  <br>Place: Sinbad’s ship in the middle of the sea. <br>Information: Sinbad has hidden a Roc egg that he secretly <br>retrieved from the nest the last time around. The old sailor is <br>too greedy to return it, and intends to use the Hunters to get <br>rid of the two Rocs. <br>Challenges: Deflect the fall of the 4 boulders the Rocs in-<br>tend to drop on the ship and convince Sinbad to return the <br>egg.<br>How to get the Tarì: When the egg is returned, one of the <br>Rocs will drop the coin on the deck of the ship. <br>Roc<br>See Dark Presence on page 13.</p><p>157<br>2B The Elephant Cemetery<br>The story that led us here...<br>The ship lands on a small island that looks like an elephant <br>graveyard. Another ship has landed on the opposite side, fly-<br>ing a pirate flag. Sinbad will tell the Hunters that the island is <br>home to a community of peaceful elephants and an old Giant <br>friend, Rull. The pirates are ivory hunters, and Rull and the <br>elephants may be in danger.<br>Place: A small island full of vegetation and elephant bones. <br>Information: The Pirates have captured almost all of <br>the elephants and used them as hostages to force Rull to <br>surrender. Not content with taking all the ivory from the <br>graveyard, they have set up a veritable factory in the Giant’s <br>hut, cutting the tusks from the elephants that are still alive. <br>Rull has been badly wounded by the Pirates and, even if <br>freed, will be unable to help the Hunters. <br>Challenges: Defeat the Pirates to free Rull. The Pirate <br>Captain is a cunning old buccaneer, and if he understands <br>the Hunters’ strength, he will use Rull as a hostage to force <br>their surrender. In total, there are twenty Pirates plus the <br>Captain on the island. However, there are only eight on <br>their ship.<br>How to get the Tarì:  If Rull is freed, he will donate the <br>coin as a thank you. <br>Ivory Seeking Pirates<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are ruthless pirates who win every battle <br>with our sabers and guns.    <br>Agenda: Obey the captain’s orders. <br>Gift - Pirate Crew: A Pirate increases their OL by 1 when <br>the Captain is present. <br>Captain of the Ivory Seeking <br>Pirates<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am an old sea wolf and I have faced all kinds <br>of adventures. I am too old to be afraid of anything. <br>Agenda: Earn as much as possible and risk as little as pos-<br>sible. <br>Gift - Old Bastard: The Captain is adept at using the sit-</p><p>158<br>uation to his advantage. Once per Exchange, if he suffers <br>1 Wound, he can sacrifice a Pirate in his place, placing the <br>casualty between himself and the threat at the last second. <br>Once per Scene, the Captain can interrupt the effect of a <br>Gift that instills fear or restricts the actions of his Pirates <br>toward an enemy by telling them how he overcame that <br>problem before. <br>3B Aladdin of a Thousand <br>Wishes<br>The story that led us here...<br>The ship arrives at an island ruled by a young Sultan named <br>Aladdin. Evil rumors of his deeds are whispered: it is said <br>that he came to the throne by usurping the old regent, who <br>was loved and well-liked by all. Aladdin seems to have a very <br>powerful Djinn at his service, carrying out his every wish <br>without fail. In reality, the Sultan has allowed himself to be-<br>come more and more perverted, because being able to accom-<br>plish anything he wants, he is plagued by a boredom that he <br>cannot satisfy in any way. The inhabitants of the island are <br>terrified by his constant and absurd demands, which often <br>result in deadly games.  <br>Place: A large and wealthy city where ships from all over <br>the world dock.<br>Information: The city is kept under control by the Eyes <br>of Aladdin, giant eyeballs that suddenly appear on the walls <br>of houses. This, too, is the result of the young Sultan’s wish <br>to be sure that no one is plotting behind his back. In the <br>slums of the city, Jasmina, Aladdin’s young wife and daugh-<br>ter of the former king, has taken refuge. The girl fled after <br>her husband showed the first signs of madness, and she <br>tries in every way to help the people of the city. Everyone <br>knows that the only way to depose him is to take away the</p><p>159<br>lamp that grants his every wish. Jasmina knows of a secret <br>passage that leads into the Sultan’s palace, as it is the same <br>one she used to escape.<br>Challenges: Take the lamp from Aladdin, who lives holed <br>up in his palace, protected by a large army of soldiers who <br>constantly patrol the city looking for any potential threat.<br>How to get the Tarì: Once retrieved, the magic lamp will <br>turn into the coin. <br>Aladdin the Mad Sultan<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am drunk with the power the lamp gives me <br>and I demand that the whole world do as I command. I have <br>a background as a street thief and know all the tricks of the <br>trade.      <br>Agenda: To find something to kill my terrible boredom.<br>Gift - Wishing Lamp: Whatever Aladdin wishes for will <br>be granted by the Djinn who lives in the lamp. As an action, <br>Aladdin can rub the lamp and ask for the following wishes:<br>1. Eliminate:  (as an action) The target is somehow <br>knocked out and suffers all the remaining Wounds, or is <br>teleported to a place where they cannot harm Aladdin. The <br>target can make a Defense Check to avoid the effect of the <br>wish, but will still take 1 Wound even if it succeeds.<br>2. Create:  (1 time per Scene) Aladdin creates up to 4 <br>Monsters to do his bidding.<br>3. Block: (as an action) Aladdin will remove the effect of <br>a spell or mind control from a subject. Alternatively, he can <br>prevent the use of a Gift that he has already seen in action <br>in the Scene.<br>Aladdin has already made some wishes to make himself <br>more powerful, so he can act up to 3 times in an Exchange <br>(but not back-to-back).<br>City Guards<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are skilled soldiers defending the city.      <br>Agenda: We obey Aladdin’s orders because we fear his <br>wrath, but we also want to stop his madness. <br>Jasmina the Brave<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am the true ruler of the island and would <br>give my life for my people. I am charismatic and skilled with <br>a scimitar.    <br>Agenda: Defeat Aladdin and restore the island’s fortunes.  <br>Monsters Summoned by Aladdin<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC  <br>(2 Wounds - 4 Monsters)<br>Descriptor: We are mindless monsters, using claws and <br>tentacles to snatch prey.</p><p>160<br>Threat – Eyes of Aladdin<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: Magic eyes that keep watch on the whole city. <br>Gift - Big Brother:  At the beginning of each Scene, a <br>stranger in the city must make a Defense Check against this <br>Threat. Roll 1 die and apply the result to all subjects who <br>failed.<br>1-2: Aladdin learns 1 Gift of the observed subject. During <br>a confrontation with Aladdin, the learned Gift is automat-<br>ically considered blocked by the third effect of the Gift - <br>Wishing Lamp. <br>3-4: Aladdin turns an unsuspecting passerby into a Mon-<br>ster to attack the foreigners.    <br>5-6: A lightning bolt springs from the eye, dealing 1 <br>Wound to the target. A Defense Check can prevent this ef-<br>fect.<br>4B The Forty Thieves<br>The story that led us here...<br>The ship lands on a large, mostly deserted island with only <br>one town. In the harbor, the Hunters meet Baba, a poor man <br>begging for help in rescuing his brother, who has been kid-<br>napped by a band of terrible Thieves. They live in an oasis <br>near the city, but no one has ever been able to pinpoint the <br>exact location of their lair. Baba knows the magic word to <br>access the hideout, having heard his brother speak of it. He <br>will lead the Hunters to the oasis, promising them a share of <br>the Thieves’ treasure as a reward. <br>Place: A large oasis in the desert, full of palm trees and <br>waterholes. <br>Information: In fact, Baba has already killed most of the <br>Thieves with the help of Dirana, a skilled slave girl in his <br>service. However, the woman is trapped in the gang’s secret <br>lair, and Baba plans to free her and recover the treasure. His <br>goal is to get the Hunters to fight the remaining ten Thieves <br>and lock himself in their lair, waiting for the survivors of <br>the battle to leave. Baba will not tell anyone how to open the <br>lair, saying that he cannot fully trust the Hunters without a <br>demonstration of their good faith. <br>Challenges: Confront the ten remaining Thieves, pre-<br>venting Baba from entering the secret lair alone and closing <br>the door behind him. Dirana is a fearsome fighter and, once <br>freed, will face the Hunters to defend her master.<br>How to get the Tarì:  If Baba fails to lock himself in the <br>cave, he will offer the coin to the Hunters for their services, <br>begging them to let him live. <br>Baba the Poor Conman<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a cunning, poor man who struggles to get <br>by. My greed is matched only by my nerve.<br>Agenda: Use others to eliminate the remaining thieves and <br>keep the treasure all to myself.</p><p>161<br>Dirana the Faithful Slave<br>OL Hard 7 - Main NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a fighting slave and fear nothing and no <br>one. My kicks can even cut through metal as if it were plain <br>paper.<br>Agenda: Baba saved my life and now I will do the same to <br>repay him. <br>Gift - Death Machine: As deadly as she is agile, Dirana <br>can act 2 times during an Exchange. <br>The Thieves<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are looters, skilled with scimitar and sling. <br>Our numbers are our strength.<br>Agenda: Protect our lair and discover the password to enter, <br>which only our late leader knew.<br>Gift - Band of Thieves:  A Thief increases their OL by 1 <br>as long as the total number of band members is greater than <br>the total number of enemies. <br>The Oasis <br>Descriptor: A large, lush oasis that the Thieves have trans-<br>formed into the perfect hideout. <br>Gift - The Lair:  While fighting inside the Oasis, Thieves <br>can benefit from the improvements they have made to the <br>place. Once per Exchange, one of these effects will be acti-<br>vated:<br>1. Trap: A large coconut falls on enemies, requiring a De-<br>fense Check against OL Medium 5 to avoid 1 Wound.<br>2. Shelter: A Thief can literally disappear from sight, re-<br>appear in another part of the Oasis, and then do their thing. <br>No one can stop this movement.<br>3. Wave: A jet of water engulfs enemies, dragging them <br>away. Up to 3 targets in a thirty-foot area must make a De-<br>fense Check against OL Medium 5 to avoid being tossed to <br>the ground. <br>5B The Sleeping Man<br>The story that led us here...<br>The ship lands in a large port city, where Sinbad meets Hazir, <br>an old friend of his. Hazir was a very wealthy merchant, but <br>now he has fallen on hard times. The man will explain to <br>the Hunters that one day he saw a beggar on the street who <br>looked exactly like him, and in order to take a little vacation <br>from his work commitments, he suggested an identity swap. <br>After a few days off, Hazir was ready to resume his role and <br>pay the beggar handsomely, but the beggar, made greedy by <br>the possibility of a life of wealth, had Hazir thrown out and <br>threatened him to never show his face again. Now the impos-<br>tor lives under the guise of Hazir, and the poor merchant does <br>not know how to regain his identity. <br>Place: A large and rich port city full of markets and ships <br>from all over the world.<br>Information: The Imposter resides in Hazir’s palace, just <br>outside the harbor, and has enlisted twin warriors who are <br>known to be unbeatable when fighting as a pair. The Im-</p><p>162<br>poster has instructed his men to behead Hazir if he even <br>dares to approach the palace. Hazir has a moon-shaped <br>birthmark on his back that the Imposter does not: this is <br>a good way to show who is the original, as Hazir’s four <br>daughters are aware of this feature.<br>Challenges: Defeat the twin fighters and prove that the <br>Imposter is not the real Hazir.<br>How to get the Tarì:  If the Hunters can reach an agree-<br>ment between Hazir and the Imposter without using force, <br>the Imposter will give them the first coin he received as a <br>gift, the Tarì. <br>Hazir the Poor Merchant<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am an honest merchant who has always <br>shown respect for others. My wealth is as great as my good <br>heart.    <br>Agenda: Return to my old life, perhaps without punishing <br>the beggar, for I understand the reasons for his selfishness.  <br>The Imposter<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a poor beggar who pretends to be Hazir. I <br>am good at adapting to any situation.<br>Agenda: To keep the life that was gifted to me. I am not evil <br>and therefore I can play the role of the good Hazir well.   <br>The Four Daughters of Hazir <br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are the Daughters of Hazir and we love our <br>father because he taught us kindness and humility.  <br>Hazir’s Guards<br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are well-trained in the protection of our <br>master.<br>Agenda: Protect Hazir from all threats / Eliminate the beg-<br>gar who persecutes our master.</p><p>163<br>Fury and Wrath, the Two Deadly <br>Twins <br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: We are two Djinn fighters who watch each oth-<br>er’s back. There is no match for our pair fighting technique.      <br>Agenda: Carry out every order of Hazir.    <br>Gift - Invincible Duo:  While fighting as a pair, Fury <br>and Wrath cannot take Wounds. Any attack or method of <br>wounding them will be blocked by one of the two Djinn. <br>To avoid this Gift, it is necessary to use an effect that affects <br>both Djinn at the same time or to separate them so that <br>they cannot support each other. <br>6B The Djinn King<br>The story that led us here...<br>The Hunters are summoned to the deck of the ship, where <br>they will find a mysterious old man smoking a water pipe. <br>The old man will ask them to run errands for him, and if they <br>do a good job, he will reward them with a golden Tarì. The <br>old man exudes a strong aura of power, and the Hunters un-<br>derstand that the strange figure is hiding his true nature. The <br>ship lands on a large island and the old man claps his hands <br>in satisfaction: it is time to begin. The Hunters must find nine <br>golden columns scattered throughout the city and bring them <br>back to him so he can furnish his palace.<br>Place: A large port city filled with temples and merchant <br>districts.<br>Information: Finding the columns is only a matter of <br>time for the Hunters, but they will encounter several people <br>who need help. Even if they don’t know it, spending time <br>with others will earn the Hunters a positive rating from the <br>Djinn King. <br>Challenges: Each column requires 1 hour of time and at <br>least one Position Check. The list below shows where they <br>can be found. Using Gifts and Descriptors for additional in-<br>formation can speed up the search. For every two columns <br>found, roll 1 die to see who needs help, up to a maximum <br>of 3 requests. <br>The Columns<br>First: On the pier in the harbor, covered with seaweed and <br>shells. / Second: In a dung-covered square used as a hitch-<br>ing post for horses and camels. / Third: In the inner court-<br>yard of a merchant’s mansion. / Fourth: In the middle of <br>an olive grove, not far from the city walls. / Fifth: In the art <br>collection of a wealthy Vizier. / Sixth: In the middle of a <br>notorious tavern, as a pillar supporting the roof. / Seventh: <br>In the wall of a watchtower. / Eighth: In the bedroom of the <br>first daughter of the Sultan. / Ninth: In the hold of Sinbad’s <br>ship, stolen and then forgotten by the old sailor years ago.<br>The Needy<br>1: A poor farmer has no money to buy seeds for the coming <br>season. Without the precious seeds, he will not be able to <br>feed his family. <br>2: A child just five years old is lost and has wandered clear <br>across the city from where he lives. He struggles to speak <br>and is frightened, but no one seems to care about him. <br>3: A poor sailor was poisoned by some villains because he <br>won too much at dice. If he does not get an antidote he will <br>die. <br>4: A merchant was robbed of a precious gold crown he <br>had bought for his daughter’s wedding. Without the crown,</p><p>164<br>promised as a gift to the groom’s mother, the wedding will <br>be canceled and the man will have no peace. <br>5: A brave slave girl rebelled against her tormentor, who or-<br>dered her to be hanged in the marketplace as punishment. <br>Everyone looks on in horror, but no one dares to intervene. <br>6: An old blind man has lost his faithful dog that helps him <br>get around town. The animal has been taken by a greedy <br>merchant, attracted by its ability to do as it is told.  <br>How to get the Tarì:  The old man will give the Tarì to <br>the Hunters if they help those in need, even at the cost of <br>restoring the columns.  <br>Fourth Leg - The Execution of <br>Sherazade<br>The story that led us here...<br>The ship lands on the largest island of the archipelago, and <br>Sinbad explains to the Hunters that the Sultan himself resides <br>in the beautiful palace that towers over the great city. As they <br>go ashore, the Hunters see several posters calling the people <br>to a great event: the Sultan’s wedding to the young Dinarzad <br>and the execution of her evil sister Sherazade (see the Broken <br>Tales Core Book, page 200 for details). The event is less than <br>an hour away, and Sinbad is concerned. If Sherazade, the <br>creator of this story, dies, what will happen to everyone in it?<br>Note: If Sherazade is an enemy of the Hunters, her execu-<br>tion will be a trap set to remove her enemies from the game. <br>Otherwise, she is truly a prisoner of the Sultan, who has <br>forced her to create a Shadow of her dead sister Dinarzad. <br>Place: The large town square, where a huge stage was set <br>up for the wedding and the execution.<br>Information: A large crowd of people spills out of each <br>street, providing good cover for the Hunters but also slow-<br>ing their movement. In the crowd are 4 Shadows of Sher -<br>azade, ready to intervene if anyone tries to stop the event. <br>Sherazade is handcuffed to a precious wooden and gold <br>chair. Behind her, a masked executioner wields a large <br>scimitar. <br>Meanwhile, the Sultan stands at center stage, hand in hand <br>with Dinarzad, dressed as the most beautiful bride of all.<br>Challenges: Hunters must stop the execution. Depending <br>on their relationship with Sherazade, they will face different <br>situations.<br>Enemy: Sherazade will have the Hunters fight the Sultan’s <br>Guards and the executioner to free her, and then she will <br>unleash the 4 Shadows against the Hunters.<br>Ally: Sherazade is clearly in shock and unable to resist the <br>Sultan’s psychological subjugation. The memory of what <br>happened has led her to create an alternate ending to the <br>story in which her sister can live happily with the Sultan <br>and Sherazade can sacrifice herself in Dinarzad’s place. <br>Breaking the Sultan’s hold on Sherazade will allow her to <br>regain control of the Shadows and punish the Sultan once <br>again by overcoming, once and for all, the painful memory <br>of what she suffered.</p><p>165<br>How to obtain the Tarì: After capturing or freeing Sher-<br>azade, the ghost of Dinarzad will appear to thank the Hunt-<br>ers and deliver the Tarì. <br>Sherazade (Dark Presence <br>Opponent/Allied)<br>See Core Book, page 200.<br>Shadows of Sherazade (Dark <br>Presence Opponent)<br>OL Medium 5 - (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We disguise ourselves as helpless citizens, but <br>in reality, we are ready to strike with our shadow sabers. <br>Agenda: Interfere with and complicate the lives of the Or -<br>der’s Hunters, preventing them from fulfilling their mission.<br>Gift - Shadow Body:  A Shadow is a darker, sadder ver -<br>sion of the original. They can speak and behave like the <br>character they are modelled after, but on a careful inspec-<br>tion they will appear cold and mechanical. Once per Scene, <br>a Shadow can appear or disappear from the darkness by <br>moving through walls and other solid obstacles. When it <br>spawns, it increases its OL by 1 because of the element of <br>surprise. When it suffers the Wound that would kill it, the <br>Shadow dissipates until its turn in the Exchange. At that <br>point, it will emerge from the darkness as if nothing had <br>happened. The Shadow will not reappear if the area the <br>Hunters are in is fully illuminated with light sources or <br>magic. The only way to truly destroy the Shadow is to ex-<br>pose it to sunlight.<br>Sultan’s Guards<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are the chosen Guards of the Sultan, and <br>with our warrior skills we protect our lord.    <br>The Executioner<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a ruthless enforcer, and with one stroke of <br>my scimitar I can cut a man in two.        <br>Gift - Art of Death: Wounds inflicted by the Executioner <br>are not easily healed and will remain for the next Leg unless <br>the Hunter can heal them with an Interlude, Gifts, or by <br>using the Gift of Sinbad - The Sailing Ship. <br>Epilogue of the Leg:  Whatever the outcome, Sherazade <br>is now in the hands of the Hunters. She can be used as a <br>Hunter for the next few Legs if the Players wish.</p><p>166<br>Eighth Leg - The Dream Gate<br>The story that led us here...<br>When the Hunters reach the end of their journey, where the <br>sea seems to fall in an endless cascade, there is a tiny island <br>with a large golden gate in the center. Eight Djinn, arms <br>crossed, sit in a circle, blocking the way to the gate. The mo-<br>ment of reckoning has come. Sherazade will explain to the <br>Hunters that they must defeat the Djinn to get through, and <br>if they lose, the One Who Plots in the Shadows will take them <br>all.<br>Place: The Island of the Dream Gate.<br>Information: The Djinn are not aggressive and will ask <br>the Hunters for a Tarì as a toll. For every coin the Hunters <br>hand over, one of the Djinn disappears. The Djinn collect <br>the payment, starting with the Eighth and going down to <br>the Second. The Djinn who remain without a token try <br>to intimidate the Hunters into leaving, unsheathing their <br>scimitars to protect the Dream Gate.<br>Challenges: Defeat the Djinn to gain access to the Dream <br>Gate.<br>Djinn of the Dream Gate<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC  <br>(3 Wounds - the Guardian and the Servant)  <br>(1 Wound - All other Djinn)  <br>(1 Djinn for each undelivered Tarì)<br>Descriptor: I am a powerful Djinn, my body is pure magic <br>and my strength transcends that of wretched humans. I pay <br>respect to those who show purity of spirit and courage.          <br>Gift - Duty: Each Djinn is immune to any effect of mind <br>control, deception, or magic that would influence them to <br>relinquish their duty.<br>Gift - Power of the Djinn:  Each Djinn has a different <br>power:<br>First - The Guardian:  If the Djinn receives 1 Wound, <br>roll a die; on a roll of 5 or 6, the person who inflicted the <br>Wound receives 1 in turn. <br>Second - The Warrior:  Once per Scene, even if a De-<br>fense Check to avoid a Djinn attack succeeds, the target still <br>suffers 1 Wound.<br>Third - The Mage: If an enemy uses a magic-related Gift <br>in the presence of the Djinn, they must spend 1 Soma or see <br>their spell dissolve without effect.<br>Fourth - The Servant: If a Djinn takes 1 Wound, it can <br>transfer it to the Servant who takes it instead.</p><p>167<br>Fifth - The Wise: Once per Scene, as an extra action, the <br>Djinn can block a Gift (except Dark Ego) that an opponent <br>has just activated. This Gift cannot be used again for the <br>rest of the Scene.<br>Sixth - The Thief:  After acting, the Djinn can make 1 <br>Hunter’s piece of Equipment disappear.<br>Seventh - The Sailor: After acting, the Djinn can move <br>to attack a new enemy without being blocked.<br>Eighth - The Storyteller:  If a Hunter activates their <br>Dark Ego, they must suffer a Wound even if they satisfy the <br>Activator.<br>Epilogue – The End of the Journey<br>If the Hunters defeat the Djinn, they will be able to pass <br>through the Gate and return to Broken Europe, Sherazade <br>and Sinbad with them. If they lose the battle, the Hunters <br>will awaken in a small, dark prison, captured by the One <br>Who Plots in the Shadows. The Storyteller will have to de-<br>cide whether to create a custom Scenario for the Hunters’ <br>escape, or to remove them from the Campaign and create <br>a new group with which to continue and perhaps find the <br>missing companions.</p>"},"sort":100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513741651,"modifiedTime":1781513741651,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}],"folder":null,"flags":{"broken-tales":{"adventureSlug":"journey-of-a-thousand-and-one-nights","collection":"Lost Stories","sourceFile":"bt-ls-book-1-ENG-SCREEN.pdf","pages":"147-168"}},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1781513741651,"modifiedTime":1781513741651,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}
